<FIRST>u w AM-Nixon-China 240   07-07 0225</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nixon-China, 240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nixon Planning China Trip: Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Richard Nixon, who reopened
ties with China in the 1970s, is planning to visit China in
September, according to a published report.
   U.S. officials and diplomatic sources were quoted in Saturday's
editions of The Washington Post as saying that Nixon and former
Secretary of State Henry Kissinger were likely to be among the first
prominent Americans to visit China since the bloody crackdown on
pro-democracy demonstrators last month.
   Nixon did not respond to inquiries about his China plans, the
newspaper said.
   Kissinger, who served under Nixon and helped forge relations with
China, was quoted as saying he was considering a ``long-standing
invitation'' to visit China in October to take part in a
government-sponsored investment conference.
   ``I won't conduct foreign policy on my own,'' Kissinger said. ``I
wouldn't do anything without consulting the administration.''
   President Bush has barred high-level official trips to China as a
sign of U.S. displeasure with the massacre in Tiananmen Square. The
order extends only to executive branch officials.
   Nixon's trip to China in February 1972 re-established
Sino-American relations for the first time since the 1949 communist
revolution. He has made three other trips to China.
   Nixon has expressed disapproval of U.S. sanctions, saying that
messages should be sent through private channels asking the Chinese
to show restraint.
</TEXT>
