<DOCNO> AP890707-0007 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-89 0022EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-ArtsAppointment     07-07 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Arts Appointment,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oregon Lawyer to Head National Endowment for Arts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush has selected Portland, Ore.,
lawyer John E. Frohnmayer to head the National Endowment for the
Arts, The New York Times reported.
   The arts agency dispenses $170 million a year in grants.
   Frohnmayer, 47, is being checked by the FBI and would have to be
confirmed by the Senate, the Times reported in its Friday editions.
   He would succeed Frank Hodsoll, who left in February to take a
post at the Office of Management and Budget.
   Bush passed over several candidates, including Schuyler G.
Chapin, former dean of the school of the arts at Columbia
University; Milton Rhodes, president of the American Council of the
Arts, and Barnabas McHenry, chairman of the Empire State Plaza Art
Commission, the Times said.
   The NEA recently has faced criticism from members of Congress for
some of its projects.
   Most recently, an NEA-supported photographic retrospective,
``Robert Mapplethorpe: The Perfect Moment,'' an exhibition that some
lawmakers said was pornographic, was cancelled before it was to have
opened at the Corcoran Gallery in Washington.
   Other lawmakers have criticized the NEA for supporting the work
of artist Andres Serrano, who depicted in a photograph Jesus Christ
on a crucifix submerged in the artist's urine.
   Frohnmayer is married and has two teen-age sons. He is a lawyer
with a Portland law firm and has spent years working in arts
organizations in Oregon.
   A native of Medford, Ore., he attended Stanford University and
the University of Oregon Law School.
</TEXT>
