<FIRST>u a AM-PhotoRescue     07-07 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Photo Rescue,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper Photo Session Nearly Results in Tragedy</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto ATN1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANNISTON, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A weather-related photo session for an
Anniston newspaper nearly turned into tragedy when rushing waters
swept a woman through a flooded 50-foot culvert and her would-be
rescuer was trapped by the current.
   Neither Angie Shockley, a 24-year-old employee of the Golden
Springs Community Center in Anniston, nor Paul Kennedy, 32, of
Anniston was seriously injured Wednesday. Kennedy was treated at
Regional Medical Center and released.
   Miss Shockley was posing for a rain-related feature for Anniston
Star photographer Eddie Motes when she stepped into a flooded ditch.
She was swept under the water when she attempted to reach higher
ground.
   ``You couldn't tell how deep the water was,'' Motes said. ``She
fell in up to her shoulders and was smiling, then she disappeared.''
   Kennedy, who was watching the photo session, jumped in after Miss
Shockley.
   ``When he jumped in, I noticed she'd washed up on the other side
(of the culvert),'' Motes said. ``It just happened so quickly.''
   By then, Kennedy had been slammed against the culvert and was
pinned by the current. A group of basketball players left the
community center's gymnasium to help free Kennedy.
   But it took the Anniston Rescue Squad, a chain and bystanders'
help to save him. At one point, Anniston Fire Department personnel
attached a breathing apparatus to Kennedy so he could be lowered
temporarily under water during the rescue operation.
</TEXT>
