<FIRST>r a PM-Nielsens     07-07 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nielsens,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>NBC Extends Its Winning Run to 54 Weeks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC extended its winning streak in the Nielsen
television ratings to 54 weeks as the network's ``Cheers'' tied
ABC's ``Roseanne'' for first place.
   Altogether, NBC captured seven slots in the Top 10. ABC had three
shows at the top. CBS was squeezed out.
   In the week that ended July 2, the two top-rated shows were
closely followed by another NBC comedy, ``Dear John,'' which placed
third.
   NBC won the A.C. Nielsen Co. ratings with an average of 11.9, ABC
had 8.5 and CBS had 8.3. For the season to date, since Sept. 19, the
ratings are NBC 15.2, ABC 12.2 and CBS 12.1.
   The rating is a percentage of the estimated 90.4 million homes in
the United States with television. The share is a percentage of sets
in use.
   The Top 10: NBC's ``Cheers'' and ABC's ``Roseanne,'' tied for
first; NBC's ``Dear John,'' third; NBC's ``Different World'' and
``L.A. Law,'' tied for fourth; NBC's ``Night Court,'' sixth; NBC's
``The Cosby Show,'' seventh; NBC's ``Empty Nest,'' eighth; ABC's
``Wonder Years'' and ``Coach,'' tied for ninth.
   CBS did have two shows in the next 10, ``Murder, She Wrote'' in
16th place and ``60 Minutes'' tied for 19th place with NBC's
``Hunter.''
   ``Doctor, Doctor,'' a CBS summer series was 37th in the ranking.
   ABC and CBS tied for first among the nightly news shows. Each had
a rating of 8.7. NBC was third with 8.2.
   Fox's ``Married ... With Children'' was in a three-way tie for
46th place and its ``America's Most Wanted'' series was in a two-way
tie for 52nd.
   The lowest-rated network show was ABC's ``Have Faith,'' which
collected a lower rating than five shows on Fox Broadcasting Co. The
bottom network shows were CBS' ``Paradise'' and ABC's Thursday Night
Baseball, tied, CBS' ``B-Men,'' CBS' ``Tour of Duty,'' ABC's ``Great
Circuses of the World'' and ABC's ``Have Faith.''
</TEXT>
