<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     07-07 0804</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,760</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sugar Production on the Rise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. sugar production is rising after a slump
because of last year's drought, according to Agriculture Department
forecasters.
   Total production in the 1989-90 crop year that begins Sept. 1 is
expected to be about 7.3 million tons, up 5.6 percent from 1988-89
output estimated at 6.91 million tons.
   Prompted by prices guaranteed under the government's system of
supports and protective quotas that limit the entry of cheaper
foreign sugar, domestic output climbed to a record 7.33 million tons
in 1987-88.
   In 1985-86, by comparison, total U.S. sugar production was barely
6 million tons.
   With improved growing conditions, sugar production in the coming
year could match or exceed the record level of two years ago.
   Beet sugar production, forecast at 3.9 million tons, would be up
11 percent from the drought-reduced level of 3.51 million tons this
season, the department's Economic Research Service said Thursday.
   Cane sugar, which rose to a record of just under 3.4 million tons
in 1988-89, is forecast at about the same in 1989-90.
   ``According to field information through mid-June, beet planting
and early development have generally gone well throughout the beet
areas,'' the report said. ``This is in sharp contrast to last year
when a series of spring weather problems was followed by drought in
key eastern growing areas.''
   The report added: ``Drought, particularly in the non-irrigated
Red River Valley of western Minnesota and eastern North Dakota, and
disease and weather problems in California, lowered yields.''
   These three states accounted for 55 percent of total sugar beet
harvested acreage in 1988-89 and 51 percent of the total beet
tonnage. That compared with 56 percent and 54 percent, respectively,
during the three previous seasons.
   Yields would have been even lower had it not been for good
growing conditions late in the season, excellent harvesting weather
and higher rates of sugar recovered from the beets, the report said.
   Farmers are expected to have about 1.3 million acres of beets for
harvest in 1989-90, about the same as this season.
   The area for sugar cane harvest is expected to be about 807,000
acres, up 10 percent from 1988-89, reflecting small increases in
Florida, Louisiana and Texas. Mainland production is forecast at
about 2.45 million tons, and Hawaii's output, 940,000 tons.
   ``Hawaii's sugar cane acreage continues to contract, with only
77,000 acres likely to be harvested this season, compared with
almost 100,000 in the early 1980s,'' the report said. ``Alternative
land use continues to encroach on traditional sugar acreage.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hong Kong has turned into a growing market for
U.S. duck feet and tongues, says the Agriculture Department.
   Deep-fried duck feet in oyster sauce, and duck tongues soaked in
fish sauce or stir-fried with seasonal vegetables are some of the
dishes offered by Chinese restaurants in Hong Kong, the department's
Foreign Agricultural Service said.
   The demand for whole ducklings, feet, tongues and gizzards is so
brisk that the local supply can't keep up.
   As a result, the agency said in the July issue of AgExporter
magazine, a number of U.S. poultry plants have built a thriving
export business on supplying the Hong Kong duck market.
   Jim Hoben, an executive with one processing plant, Concord Farms
of Concord, N.C., said U.S. duck processors sold more than 4 million
pounds of duck feet to Hong Kong alone last year.
   ``All of our duck feet and tongues are exported to Hong Kong,''
Hoben said ``That market represents 4 percent of our total business,
and it is a very important market for Concord Farms.''
   Aggressive market promotion in Hong Kong has been part of the
reason for U.S. success in the duck market. The USDA's Targeted
Export Assistance Program, which helps finance approved overseas
promotional efforts, has been particularly effective.
   For example, the program financed a booklet featuring recipes for
duck feet, tongue and duckling recipes for the Hong Kong market,
available there in both Chinese and English, the report said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ice cream production jumped sharply in May,
just in time for the summer rush, according to an Agriculture
Department report.
   With production at 79.8 million gallons, that was up 16 percent
from April and 3 percent from May of last year, the department's
National Agricultural Statistics Service reported Thursday.
   And that was only ``hard'' ice cream. There were no estimates for
soft versions produced by machines across the country.
   But the report did show that ice milk production, at 37.4 million
gallons in May, was up 20 percent from April and 9 percent from a
year earlier. Sherbet production was 5.4 million gallons, up 26
percent and 20 percent, respectively.
   Frozen yogurt output was estimated at 6.74 million gallons in
May, virtually the same as in April. No year-earlier figures were
available.
</TEXT>
