<FIRST>r a PM-CollegeByMail     07-07 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-College By Mail,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marine Corps Signs Up for Correspondence Courses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID S. MARTIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STATE COLLEGE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marines guarding the U.S. embassies
abroad are often limited in off-duty activities, but now there's
something for their minds _ college by mail.
   The Marine Security Guard Battalion reached an agreement recently
with Penn State University to offer an associate-degree program to
the 1,450 Marines guarding 141 embassies and consulates around the
world.
   Taking classes by mail will help relieve boredom in such hardship
posts as the embassy in Ouagadougou, the capital of the west African
nation of Burkina Faso, Marine Capt. David Vindich said.
   ``There's absolutely nothing there,'' said Vindich, the
battalion's education officer.
   Also, Marines stationed at embassies and consulates in the Soviet
Union are restricted by a non-fraternization policy, while those in
Beirut can't leave the compound because of the country's civil war.
   ``A lot of these places are really isolated,'' Vindich said.
``We're providing an educational opportunity and we're also giving
them something to do.''
   Vindich said Marines in the elite, all-volunteer battalion
generally spend 15 months in a hardship post and then 15 months at a
less rigorous embassy or consulate.
   More than 400 Marines serving in embassies and consulates already
take courses, but their efforts toward degrees have been largely
unstructured, he said.
   ``They were out there spinning their wheels. You talk college
credits and semester hours and that kind of thing, it boggles the
mind of a 19-year-old kid just out of high school, 10,000 miles from
home,'' Vindich said in a telephone interview from Quantico, Va.
   Under an agreement reached in May, Penn State will offer liberal
arts degrees in letters, arts and sciences. The university has
planned course concentrations for the Marines including business,
security and justice, political analysis and foreign policy, and
language and culture.
   Vindich said he expects 400 would sign up this year.
   An associate degree would cost about $4,800 or $5,000, said Peter
Forster, coordinator of special programs at Penn State's Department
of Independent Learning. Vindich said the Marine Corps pays 75
percent of tuition costs.
   Penn State has the largest university-based correspondence course
program in the United States, offering 225 courses to 22,000
students.
</TEXT>
