<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-89 0225EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-CruiseShips     07-07 0628</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cruise Ships,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Safety Board Eyes U.S.-Owned Ships Carrying Americans Under Foreign
Flags</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal safety officials want the Coast Guard
to be allowed to regulate luxury cruise ships that are owned by
Americans, carry Americans and use American ports but fly under
foreign flags.
   ``We're not in a position to protect the lives of an American
citizen in these types of vessels, and something's got to be done
about it,'' said Jim Burnett, a member of the National
Transportation Safety Board.
   The NTSB on Thursday issued several recommendations that would
affect more than 80 cruise ships that dock at U.S. ports.
   Only two or three such cruise ships are registered in the United
States, board investigators said.
   The board, which is preparing a more extensive report on the
cruise ship industry in a few months, recently concluded an
investigation into a fire that caused a near-catastrophe aboard a
Bahamian-flagged vessel off the Florida coast 16 months ago.
   The board concluded that a lack of maintenance, lack of
fire-fighting procedures and poor crew training caused the fire
aboard the Scandinavian Star, which was carrying 700 people back to
St. Petersburg, Fla., from a two-day Gulf of Mexico cruise.
   The board said failure of a fire-fighting system and the
inability of crew members, who spoke a variety of languages, to
communicate with each other and with passengers contributed to the
emergency.
   ``It was only sheer luck'' that no injuries or deaths occurred
aboard the 10,000-ton vessel owned by Sea Escape of Miami, said NTSB
Chairman James L. Kolstad.
   ``This is an invitation to disaster,'' said Kolstad. He said
U.S.-owned cruise ships are registered in several different
countries because of the high expenses involved in meeting
requirements as U.S. flag carriers.
   Jill DeChello, spokeswoman for Sea Escape, said the company had
no immediate comment on the board decision. She said the company
operates four 10,000-ton ships, each carrying 950 to 1,100
passengers on cruises out of Miami.
   In the last decade, the board has investigated five major fires
aboard cruise vessels, three of them on Sea Escape ships. One in
1984 killed one passenger and one crew member. Scores of people have
been injured, mostly from smoke inhalation.
   No other deaths have been reported in accidents aboard
American-operated cruise ships, but a Cuban ship captain and two
sailors were killed when the U.S.-owned Celebration cut their
freighter in half Feb. 10.
   The board is seeking court orders to force witnesses to give
testimony in its investigation of the Celebration accident. The
ship's owner, Carnival Cruise Ship Lines, has refused to cooperate
in the safety investigation, saying it is responding only to
authorities in Liberia, where the vessel is registered.
   In Thursday's action, the board asked the Coast Guard, which
regulates civilian shipping, to seek legislation that would give it
authority over the safety of cruise ships.
   The board also called for smoke detectors that automatically shut
down ventilation systems so smoke won't spread through passenger
cabins; improved testing of fire extinguishing systems; back-up
generators for fire alarms, public address systems and smoke
detectors, and several other safety improvements for all cruise
ships. The safety board has no authority to impose its
recommendations.
   The board said the Scandinavian Star fire on March 15, 1988,
started with an oil leak. It said fuel pipe packing seals and
deflector sleeves that would have prevented the oil from being
ignited were deteriorated and had not been replaced.
   ``I'm afraid this ship was being managed more like a night club
than a vessel,'' said board member Burnett, who led the
investigation into the fire.
   The ship, which was towed to Miami after the fire was put out,
has since been repaired and is back in operation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
