<FIRST>r w PM-Fiske     07-07 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fiske,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conservative Opposition Forces Withdrawal of Thornburgh Choice</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert B. Fiske Jr. says he withdrew from
consideration for the No. 2 job at the Justice Department to avoid a
lengthy confirmation battle threatened by conservative Republican
senators.
   The withdrawal marked a setback for Attorney General Dick
Thornburgh, who had lobbied conservatives on behalf of his choice
for deputy attorney general.
   Fiske's letter to Thornburgh taking his name out of consideration
was released Thursday by the Justice Department.
   Last month, 14 mostly conservative Republican senators, objecting
to Fiske's role as chairman of the American Bar Association's
Standing Committee on Federal Judiciary from 1984 to 1987, urged
President Bush not to nominate him for the Justice Department post.
   In his letter, Fiske wrote: ``While I have no doubt that my
nomination would have won the overwhelming support of the members of
the United States Senate, there could have been a long delay in
final action.
   ``Knowing of your need to fill this important position as quickly
as possible, I reluctantly concluded that it would be best for me to
step aside at this time.''
   Fiske, reached by telephone, declined to comment, saying only
that he would continue his private legal practice in New York.
   A pillar of the New York legal establishment, Fiske served as
U.S. attorney in Manhattan during the Ford administration.
   But conservatives criticized him for his role in screening
President Ronald Reagan's judicial nominees for the American Bar
Association.
   Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C., the ranking GOP member on the Senate
Judiciary Committee, had urged Fiske to withdraw to avoid a lengthy,
divisive confirmation fight in the Senate. Thurmond warned Fiske
that some opponents might wage filibusters to stall his confirmation.
   Opponents accused him of torpedoing Reagan's nominations by
forwarding the names of prospective nominees to liberal
organizations, giving the groups an advance opportunity to organize
opposition.
   Fiske acknowledged that names were sent to these organizations as
part of a longstanding ABA practice of determining if potential
nominees had shown a history of bias against minorities and women.
   The conservatives also accused Fiske of using ideological
criteria to rate the professional qualifications of Reagan's
nominees.
   In his reply to Fiske, Thornburgh expressed ``great regret'' at
the decision and said conservatives had ``misstated and
misunderstood'' his record as chairman of the ABA screening panel.
   ``I am glad to have been part of the effort to set the record
straight, which now has been done,'' Thornburgh said.
</TEXT>
