<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     07-07 0546</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0569</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPARTANBURG, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Greg Gardner is getting used to his
roommates' comings and goings, now that they've settled in behind
the cereal boxes.
   About six weeks ago, two Carolina wrens flew in through his
unscreened kitchen window. Gardner then noticed some sticks and
twigs near the cereal boxes, the beginnings of a nest, and he
decided to let them stay.
   Gardner tried to help the birds by leaving a torn cotton ball.
But they preferred their own materials, and wouldn't use it, he said.
   As the nest neared completion, the mother wren, a small brown
bird about three inches long, became more familiar with Gardner. She
did not easily frighten when he went into the kitchen, he said.
   ``After a while, she got used to me,'' he said.
   Once the nest was completed, the brown bird laid a set of
blue-speckled eggs. Within two weeks, five eggs hatched and the baby
birds began begging for food.
   Gardner said he's awaiting the day when the mother bird begins
teaching her chicks to fly. He's ready for his kitchen to become a
training ground.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>STORRS, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At the University of Connecticut, the
political climate has improved for a dog.
   Twenty years ago, the student Senate voted to sell Jonathan, the
school's Siberian husky mascot, because he represented the
establishment.
   But later this month, Jonathan VIII, the latest in a line of
huskies that have represented the college, may win back his
ancestors' status as symbol of school spirit.
   Alpha Phi Omega, a coeducational service fraternity, has asked
the board of trustees to restore Jonathan's status. The board is
expected to take up the issue July 14.
   The huskies were named after an early Connecticut governor,
Jonathan Trumbull. Many of the dogs figure prominently in the lore,
especially Jonathan IV which survived a dog-nabbing by University of
Massachusetts students.
   In 1969, the Student Senate's decision to sell the mascot was
protested by about 2,500 students. Alpha Phi Omega took
responsibility for the dog; Jonathan VIII lives with a family off
campus.
   Fraternity members say if the trustees name the newest Jonathan
as school mascot, they will trot him out for events.
   They plan to show him off at sporting and social events, and will
lobby for him as grand marshal of the Homecoming Day parade.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Tennessee county isn't the weight-loss
king, but don't call its residents fat.
   Three months ago, Bradley County accepted a challenge from Sac
County, Iowa, to see which could shed the largest percentage of
weight over a 90-day period, the loser to fly the winner's flag over
the loser's courthouse for a month.
   Sac County, completing its third year of a communitywide
weight-loss program, dropped 4,021.4 pounds, or 5.1 percent, from
its starting weight of 78,851 pounds.
   Bradley County lost 971.25 pounds, or 4.2 percent, from its
beginning total of 22,895.5 pounds. Sac County began with 543
participants and Bradley County with 203, but not all completed the
contest.
   ``They beat us, but we're still pleased,'' said Sue Little,
publications director of the Cleveland-Bradley County Chamber of
Commerce. She said Thursday that one Bradley County woman, Joyce
Renner, lost 73 pounds and her husband, Rick Renner, lost 50.
</TEXT>
