<DOCNO> AP890707-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-89 0253EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Bangladesh-Presidency     07-07 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bangladesh-Presidency,0273</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ershad Presidency to be Limited to 10 Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Hussain Mohammad Ershad, who
took power in a bloodless coup in 1982, has proposed a
constitutional amendment limiting the presidency to 10 years.
   The proposed amendment was presented to parliament Thursday,
where it is assured of passage because Ershad's Jatiya Party holds
251 of the 300 seats.
   ``I am certain that they (the legislators) are going to pass it,
so it is good from my side and I am certain it is good for our
country,'' the 59-year-old former army general said.
   Ershad resigned from the army in 1985 and a year later was
elected to a five-year presidential term in national balloting that
political opponents and foreign observers said was tainted by
widespread vote fraud.
   Under the proposed amendment, Ershad can seek re-election in 1991
to another 5-year term but he would be banned from seeking a third
term.
   Bangladesh has had nine presidents since it won independence from
Pakistan in 1971. Each took office through military intervention,
either through coup and assassination or through installation of
civilians who heeded the army's dictates.
   Ershad, who has governed Bangladesh longer than any other leader,
said the decision to limit the term of the president was part of his
effort to modernize the nation.
   ``We have to prove to the world that Bangladesh is something more
than a poor country,'' Ershad said.
   Bangladesh, whose 110 million people have an average annual
income of only $160, is perennially buffeted by floods, cyclones,
tornadoes and drought.
</TEXT>
