<HEAD>Dollar Steady Againt Yen, Nikkei Rises Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar closed firm against the Japanese yen
Friday, while the market's key index continued to rise.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which rose
113.77 points Thursday, gained another 280.49 points, or 0.83
percent, to close the week at 33,703.97.
   The dollar finished trading at 139.65 yen. After opening at
139.33 yen, up 0.43 yen from Thursday's close of 138.90 yen, the
currency ranged between 139.00 yen and 139.83 yen.
   Currency dealers said market players were cautious in morning
trading in anticipation of the release of U.S. unemployment figures
for June, due out later Friday in Washington.
   ``It's hard to move around with that announcement coming up,''
said a trader of a major commercial bank in Tokyo, who spoke
anonymously.
   The jobless data is considered an important indicator to judge
the state of the U.S. economy.
   On the stock market, the market's main barometer gained steadily
from the start with domestic-demand issues attracting investors'
attention because of the upward trend of the yen this week.
   But traders said said the morning trading was not very active,
with some market participants retreating to the sidelines with a
wait-and-see position.
