<FIRST>r i PM-Kadar     07-07 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kadar,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Party Leaders Say Kadar Left Mixed Legacy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Warsaw Pact, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX BANDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist officials dealt a parting blow
to longtime Hungarian leader Janos Kadar hours after his death by
saying political changes had passed him by.
   Kadar, who died Thursday at age 77, came to power as Soviet
troops crushed the 1956 anti-Stalinist uprising. He oversaw early
stirrings of economic and political reform but lost power last year
to enthusiasts of quicker change.
   In remembering his life, the party leadership, in a statement
carried Thursday by state media, said Kadar had led the way to
national consensus and always aimed at a ``humanist socialism.''
   However, it said that ``time and the (communist) Hungarian
Socialist Workers Party have surpassed the life work of Kadar, the
politician. In the spirit of his heritage demanding justice, we must
declare this painful fact.''
   In the 1960's, Kadar gained a degree of popularity at home and
abroad with cautious economic reform and relative political
tolerance.
   However, in the late 1970's, he backed away from reforms, and the
country's economy went into a slow tailspin.
   Plans for his funeral were not announced. The four members of the
party's ruling presidium were named to a special committee to
organize the funeral. The committee was to be headed by party
chairman Rezso Nyers.
   However, Nyers and other government figures left for Bucharest,
Romania, on Thursday for a Warsaw Pact summit that is to include
Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev. There was speculation Kadar's
funeral would be delayed until after next week's visit to Hungary by
President Bush.
</TEXT>
