<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     07-07 0228</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Firms Against Yen, Tokyo Stocks Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar firmed today against the Japanese
yen after four-consecutive days of decline, while the key index on
the Tokyo Stock Exchange rose.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 280.49 points, or 0.83
percent, closing at 33,703.97. The index posted a 113.77-point gain
the previous day.
   The dollar closed at 139.65 yen, up 0.75 yen from Thursday's
close of 138.90 yen. It opened at 139.33 yen and ranged between
139.00 yen and 139.83 yen.
   Today's turnaround in the dollar's direction came after a fall of
5.05 yen over the past four trading days.
   A dealer with Mitsubishi Bank said the dollar firmed on buying
for ``short-cover positions.''
   ``Otherwise there was relative quiet'' as market players were
waiting for U.S. unemployment figures for June to be released later
today in Washington, said the dealer.
   The jobless data is considered an important indicator of the
state of the economy.
   On the stock exchange, the Nikkei index rose steadily throughout
the day, as investors were encouraged by declining long-term
interest rates in Japan, traders said.
   ``The attention is now whether the U.S. monetary authorities will
ease their credit further in an already slowed-down economy,'' said
Masahiro Umemori, an equity researcher with Nomura Securities,
Japan's largest brokerage.
   Lower U.S. interest rates tend to make dollar-denominated
investments less attractive.
</TEXT>
