<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     07-07 0619</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0637</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rains Lighten in East; Heat Wave Continues to Bake West</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rains lightened in the soaked Tennessee Valley and mid-Atlantic
states today while a heat wave continued to grip much of the West.
   Afternoon highs were generally above 90 degrees Thursday in the
western two-thirds of the nation, and at least 11 cities in five
states set or tied record highs for the date.
   Record-breaking hot spots included Sacramento, Calif., where the
high of 105 degrees exceeded by one degree a mark set in 1921; Las
Vegas, where a high of 115 broke a 37-year-old record by one degree;
and Corpus Christi, Texas, which broke a 1965 mark by two degrees
with a high of 99.
   Tucson, Ariz., set its seventh record high in the last eight days
with a reading of 109, and Grand Junction, Colo., set its third
straight record high with 104.
   Temperatures were still close to 100 degrees in some parts of the
Desert Southwest early today.
   Scattered showers and thunderstorms extended from the Tennessee
Valley to the Middle Atlantic Coast early this morning, and a few
showers and thunderstorms doused the Southeast. Millville, N.J.,
recorded just over an inch of rain in the six hours ended at 2 a.m.
EDT, and Fort Polk, La., received just over three quarters of an
inch.
   That rainfall was nothing like the torrents that have caused
floods and damage in the region in recent days.
   The bodies of two 15-year-old boys were found in East Brunswick,
N.J., on Thursday, one day after they apparently were sucked into a
sewer by rainwaters. More than 5 inches of rain were recorded in the
area on Wednesday.
   Waters receded in Cobb County, northwest of Atlanta, where as
much as 8.85 inches of rain fell Wednesday night and Thursday
morning. The storm demolished an unoccupied house, flooded several
residences and flooded more than a dozen roads, and at least six
roads were expected to remain closed through the weekend.
   Strong thunderstorms developed along a cold front during the
night over southern South Dakota and northern Nebraska, and one-inch
hail fell at Kadoka, S.D.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms in the
lower Mississippi Valley, northwest Pennsylvania, western North
Carolina and northern through central Florida. Scattered rain was
forecast for northern New England and northeast New York state.
   Highs were expected to be in the 70s in Upper Michigan and
northeast Minnesota, and scattered along the Pacific Coast; the
mid-90s and hotter over southeast Texas, the central Plains, from
southern Montana across New Mexico and Arizona, and from Idaho
across eastern California; near 100 degrees from southwest Idaho
across Utah and Nevada; and near 115 degrees over inland California
and the Desert Southwest. Highs in the rest of the nation were
expected to reach the 80s and low 90s.
   Temperatures at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 51 degrees at Quillayute,
Wash., and Yellowstone Park, Wyo., to 100 degrees at Phoenix.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 74 fair; Buffalo 71 foggy; Charleston, S.C. 80
cloudy; Cincinnati 75 hazy; Cleveland 69 fair; Detroit 71 hazy;
Miami 79 fair; New York 74 foggy; Philadelphia 73 foggy; Pittsburgh
71 foggy; Portland, Maine 63 foggy; Washington 74 foggy.
   _Central: Bismarck 61 fair; Chicago 77 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth 73
fair; Denver 77 fair; Des Moines 75 fair; Indianapolis 69 foggy;
Kansas City 75 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 75 fair; Nashville 73
fair; New Orleans 76 fair; St. Louis 78 hazy.
   _West: Albuquerque 78 fair; Anchorage 55 partly cloudy; Las Vegas
92 fair; Los Angeles 67 cloudy; Phoenix 00 fair; Salt Lake City 72
fair; San Diego 66 cloudy; San Francisco 55 fair; Seattle 64 partly
cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 73 fair; Toronto 70 foggy.
</TEXT>
