<FIRST>r a PM-Mecham     07-07 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mecham,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Governor Files Petition Challenging Impeachment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Gov. Evan Mecham is challenging his
impeachment last yeer by the Arizona Senate in a petition with the
state Supreme Court.
   In the petition, which was filed Thursday, he asks for more than
$570,000 in expenses and demands the impeachment be quashed or that
he be given a new trial by the Senate.
   ``We can't let it stand because _ not so much the effect on me
but _ if that's the case, then no governor in America is sitting
safe,'' said Mecham, who is campaigning for governor in 1990.
   Companion petitions filed by supporters claimed that they were
deprived of a constitutional right to lobby lawmakers to keep Mecham
in office when Chief Justice Frank Gordon Jr., sitting as head of
the Senate Court of Impeachment, said it would be illegal to try to
influence the impeachment vote.
   Mecham, a Republican, was ousted by the GOP-controlled Senate on
April 4, 1988, on charges he obstructed justice and misused a state
protocol fund.
   Speaking with reporters after Thursday's court filings, Mecham
and his lawyer, Donald MacPherson, said they would rather have
Mecham reinstated outright but would settle for a new trial and for
proceedings on whether some senators were biased.
   MacPherson said the impeachment was flawed because senators never
took a separate vote on each element of the potential offenses and
because of confusion over the state of the law.
   The lawyer said the House bill of impeachment described Mecham as
doing some things in the course of his official duties when he
actually had done them before his election.
   MacPherson also accused Mecham's impeachment trial lawyers, Fred
Craft and Jerris Leonard, of ineffective representation, saying they
had not raised key issues such as the separate votes.
   Mecham, who had praised Craft and Leonard in the past, declined
to comment on that portion of the petition.
   Craft and Leonard said they understood why Mecham's new lawyer
would raise the issue but recalled that Mecham also had criticized
all the other lawyers involved in the impeachment. Craft said Mecham
had called him for legal advice as recently as June 29.
   The Senate earlier this year rejected Mecham's call for a new
trial, and legislative leaders said Thursday they would turn over
the new challenge to their lawyers.
   Mecham's lawyers had to wait until now to file the petition
because the Arizona Constitution does not allow lawmakers to be sued
while they are in session. The Legislature's 1989 regular session
ended last month.
   Mecham's ouster elevated elected Secretary of State Rose Mofford,
a Democrat, to the governorship. Mrs. Mofford's press secretary,
Vada Manager, declined to comment on the petitions.
   ``We're not going to speculate that far in the future,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
