<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-89 0553EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-US-JapanLeaders     07-07 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Japan Leaders,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S., Japanese Leaders Asked to Focus on `Real Issues'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. and Japanese leaders are urged in a new
report to stress to their people that both sides have more to gain
through cooperation than ruthless rivalry.
   ``But unless the United States can come to terms with its fear of
`being taken' by the Japanese'' and the Japanese abandon ``their
mercantilist view of the world, such cooperation remains beyond
reach,'' says the report published by the Johns Hopkins University
School of Advanced International Studies.
   Leaders of ``both Japan and the United States need to foster
greater public understanding of the real issues,'' especially on
defense, said the 68-page study issued this week, entitled ``The
United States and Japan in 1989.''
   Three previous reports in the annual series dealt in detail with
individual economic disputes between the two countries. The latest
study focused more on managing the relationship to prevent conflicts
from overshadowing basic advantages.
   ``Political leaders in Washington and Tokyo should take the lead
in working to eliminate misconceptions and reaffirm the basic
premises of U.S.-Japan cooperation, lest misunderstanding lead to
bad legislation,'' the report said.
   ``Although fundamentals supporting the U.S.-Japan relationship
are almost universally positive, these can be quickly forgotten in
bouts of name-calling,'' it cautioned.
   The report voiced concern over ``the rapid growth of a cottage
industry of Japan-bashers in Washington who warn us that Japan
represents a greater threat than the Soviet Union to our economic
and security interests. ... Their various allegations, if left
unanswered, can erode the relationship ... leading to the
self-fulfilling prophecy syndrome.''
   Tracing what it called ``real issues,'' the study said,
``Japanese political leaders will have to make unprecedented efforts
to present Japan's defense responsibilities in a straightforward
manner and stress the importance of the U.S. (military) bases to
Japan.
   ``U.S. government officials must ... educate the American public
on Japanese contributions to U.S. defense ... (and) make clear that
the United States is in Japan for its own national security, not
simply to defend Japan.''
   The study said both countries should correct domestic problems
creating U.S.-Japanese friction.
</TEXT>
