<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--DisabledBicyclist     07-07 0141</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Disabled Bicyclist,0143</SECOND>
<HEAD>Disabled Bicyclist Injured, Continues Trek</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRISTOL, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A blind bicyclist who hoped to ride from
San Francisco to the nation's capital to demonstrate the ableness of
the disabled is finishing her trip in a van because of a foot
infection.
   Deeanne Eggleston lost her sight 10 years ago from complications
of diabetes that also left her with little feeling in her feet and a
locked ankle joint.
   ``We may have different limbs, eyes or minds, but underneath we
still have the same heart,'' she said Wednesday during a stop in
Bristol.
   Eggleston, 38, left her hometown of San Francisco on April 1. An
ulcer on one of her feet became infected and she had to have surgery
in Memphis. She was there for two weeks before continuing northeast
through Nashville and Bristol in the van.
</TEXT>
