<FIRST>u i PM-ASEAN-Baker     07-07 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-ASEAN-Baker,0472</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker Criticizes Israeli Party's Plan to Restrict Elections</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-ASEAN-Conference</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANDAR SERI BEGAWAN, Brunei (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A.
Baker III today criticized Israel's Likud party for imposing new
restrictions on the holding of Palestinian elections in the West
Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Baker said the Likud action was ``not helpful,'' but he noted the
step was taken by a political party and was not a government action.
   Speaking to reporters at the conclusion of a meeting of key
Southeast Asian nations, Baker said the United States will continue
to support the Israeli government's proposals for Palestinian
elections in the occupied territories.
   Among other restrictions, the Likud resolution said there can be
no such elections so long as the 19-month Palestinian ``intefadah,''
or uprising, persists.
   The elections would be for Palestinians to choose leaders for the
purpose of opening settlement talks with Israeli authorities.
   Baker spoke to reporters after attending a meeting of the
six-nation Southeast Asian Nations and other interested parties. He
is to fly later today to the Arabian peninsula nation of Oman.
   Additionally, Baker said he and his ASEAN colleagues agreed on
the importance of maintaining open lines with China. While
denouncing the ``horrible'' actions of the Chinese in cracking down
on pro-democracy demonstrators a month ago, Baker said there was
agreement that outsiders ``must encourage China's full return to the
international community.''
   The principal topic of discussion was how next to deal with the
situation in Cambodia once Vietnam completes its scheduled troop
withdrawal by the end of September.
   Baker said that he had received assurances from Soviet officials
of their willingness to establish an international peacekeeping
force to guard against the outbreak of war in that country once the
Vietnamese are gone.
   Baker said it would be his preference that the Khmer Rouge, who
ruled with a heavy hand from 1975-1978, not be represented in any
provisional government that may form after Hanoi's forces withdraw.
   He acknowledged too that he is in disagreeement with former
Cambodia head of state, Price Norodom Sihanouk, on this issue.
   Sihanouk has said that it is better to have moderate elements of
the Khmer Rouge in government than to have the rebel movement to
continue its armed struggle in the field.
   In earlier remarks to his ASEAN colleagues, Baker said there is a
critical need for ASEAN and western unity to insure the emergence
and survival of a new independent Cambodia.
   ``This new Cambodia must be free to determine its own future and
it must not be dominated by the murderous Khmer Rouge,'' he said.
   He called for a comprehensive solution encompassing a cease-fire,
measures to control the Khmer Rouge effectively, transitional
power-sharing arrangements and free elections.
</TEXT>
