<HEAD>Weapons Turn-In Offer Gets Quick Response</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to remove garble in population figure.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>APPLETON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A police chief says his plea for people to
turn in weapons and ammunition brought an immediate response, and he
hopes other police agencies will follow his lead.
   ``If by getting these weapons off the streets we save even one
life, it would be worth it,'' said Paul Reque, chief of police for
the Town of Grand Chute, a rural community of about 11,200 people.
   Reque announced late last month he would accept any and all guns
and ammunition, legal or illegal, no questions asked, from anyone
who brought them to the police station during business hours from
July 1-15.
   The goal, he said, was to get dangerous weapons out of homes
where they can pose a lethal risk to children. Wisconsin has had
several cases in recent weeks of shootings involving children in
their homes.
