<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-89 0829EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SpillRecords     07-07 0508</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spill Records,0523</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exxon Agrees to Permit State to Interview its Records Employees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN S. AKRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Exxon Co. USA said it will make employees
available for questioning in the state investigation of how some
copies of company records on the Exxon Valdez oil spill were
destroyed.
   Company officials said Thursday that the destroyed records were
backup computer files and that ``all primary records and documents''
on the spill remained on other computer tapes in company possession.
   ``I can assure you of Exxon's continued cooperation in assisting
your office to fully understand the circumstances and insignificance
of the computer backup-tape matter,'' Exxon lawyer E.D. Ackerman
wrote Alaska Attorney General Douglas Baily.
   Baily demanded Wednesday that Exxon allow the state to take
depositions from employees involved in the records destruction,
which Exxon says was an accident. He termed it ``potentially a loss
of devastating proportions.''
   David Ramseur, a spokesman for Gov. Steve Cowper, said Exxon had
agreed to supply affidavits next week from employees who handled the
records. Baily said he hoped to get the depositions under way within
two weeks.
   Les Rogers, an Exxon spokesman in Houston, said the affidavits
are part of an internal company report on the tape incident, which
will be provided to the state.
   The oil company is under state and federal court orders to
preserve its records of the March 24 tanker spill in which nearly 11
million gallons of Alaska crude oil fouled Prince William Sound.
   While the state has not yet filed any spill-related lawsuits
against Exxon, it plans to by the end of summer, Baily said.
   Baily said he became aware of the records destruction when he was
contacted by a New York Times reporter who had interviewed the main
Exxon employee involved, Kenneth A. Davis.
   Davis told the newspaper that he had inadvertently destroyed the
files and feared he was being made a scapegoat to cover his
superiors' negligence in protecting company records. Davis was fired
June 8, the day after the damage was discovered, the Times reported.
   The destroyed material included internal memos and
word-processing documents from Exxon Shipping Co., which owns the
Exxon Valdez, and Exxon USA, the newspaper said.
   Exxon's Ackerman said the records were lost when the computer
tapes were inadvertently ``written over'' with other information.
The tapes normally are kept for a time to restore the computer
system should its primary tapes be damaged.
   ``These backup tapes normally would be recycled every few weeks
and are not intended to serve as a permanent archive of Exxon
documents,'' he said.
   In San Diego, meanwhile, the Coast Guard said it will provide the
Exxon Valdez with a protective escort Tuesday when the damaged
tanker arrives at the the National Steel and Shipbuilding Co.
shipyard for repairs.
   Seven Coast Guard and Harbor Police boats will maintain a 300-to
500-yard safety zone around the tanker as it travels through the San
Diego bay to keep boat-borne gawkers and protesters from impeding
the vessel, Coast Guard Cmdr. Jack Scarborough said Thursday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
