<DOCNO> AP890707-0062 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-89 0847EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Perrin     07-07 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Perrin,0355</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Outer Limits' Narrator Vic Perrin Dies At Age 73</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor and announcer Vic Perrin, who provided
the spooky voice that told viewers of ``The Outer Limits'' TV show
that their sets had just been taken over by mysterious forces, has
died of cancer. He was 73.
   Perrin, who died Tuesday at Cedars-Sinai Medical Center, was
known to millions in the 1960s for saying at the beginning of each
``Outer Limits'' show: ``There is nothing wrong with your television
set. ... Do not attempt to adjust the picture. ... We are
controlling transmission.''
   He would come on again at the show's conclusion to ``return
control'' of the set to the viewer and leave the audience with a
moral for that week's episode of the science fiction anthology
series.
   Perrin, born in Menomonee Falls, Wis., graduated from the
University of Wisconsin before moving West in 1940. In Hollywood, he
embarked on a career in radio that was to make his voice, if not his
face or name, known to millions.
   His worked as a radio announcer for both ABC and NBC and was a
regular on such shows as the radio version of ``Gunsmoke,'' ``One
Man's Family,'' ``Fort Laramie'' and ``Yours Truly Johnny Dollar.''
   In 1956, Perrin joined ``The CBS Radio Workshop'' a short-lived
but critically praised series that broadcast experimental dramas and
classics, including a narration by Aldous Huxley of his ``Brave New
World.''
   Later, Perrin appeared regularly on such TV shows as ``Dragnet,''
``Mission Impossible,'' ``Gunsmoke,'' ``Star Trek,'' ``Big Valley''
and ``Maverick.''
   He also was the announcer on several commercials, but refused to
go before the cameras to sell products, saying that ``if they see me
in a commercial, they can't believe me as an actor.''
   Perrin's voice can still be heard on reruns of ``The Outer
Limits,'' which originally aired form 1963 to 1965, and at Disney
World's The Spaceship Earth and Exxon Energy Pavilion attractions.
   He is survived by his wife, Rita; a son; and a stepson. A
memorial service was scheduled for Wednesday in Studio City.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890707-0063 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-89 0850EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-UN-Israel 1stLd-Writethru   07-07 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UN-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0453,0476</SECOND>
<HEAD>Council Criticizes Expulsions, Silent on Bus Massacre</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 2 grafs to RECAST lede. Pickup 3rd graf ``This proves...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Mideast, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Security Council passed a resolution
saying it ``deeply regrets'' Israel's continued expulsions of
Palestinians from the occupied lands.
   With the United States abstaining, the 15-nation council on
Thursday voted 14-0 for the resolution that cites the deportations
last month of eight Palestinians.
   ``This proves once again the irrelevance of the whole
institution,'' Ambassador Johanan Bein of Israel said after the
meeting. ``On the day of a major terrorist attack, in which 14
people are dead and 27 wounded, the Security Council finds fit to
deal with expulsions.''
   He was referring to an attack in which a Palestinian shouting
``God is great!'' seized the steering wheel of an Israeli bus on the
highway outside Jerusalem and caused it to veer into a ravine where
it exploded in flames.
   U.S. Ambassador Thomas R. Pickering said the United States
opposes expulsions but abstained from voting on the resolution
because it did not take into account the violence and security
problems facing Israel.
   Israel has expelled about 55 Palestinians since the Palestinian
uprising against Israeli rule of the Gaza Strip and West Bank began
19 months ago.
   The United States, Israel's staunch ally, frequently votes in
favor of Israel. By not exercising its veto power as one of five
permanent members of the Security Council, the United States
delivered a rare, but mild, chastizing of Israel.
   The resolution was adopted after days of negotiations in which
the United States succeeded in changing its language from
``deplores'' to ``deeply regrets.''
   ``In the absence of incitement and violence, expulsions would not
be necessary,'' Bein said. ``Should quiet be restored, the
possibility of allowing the return of the expelled persons will be
considered.''
   Since the uprising began, 550 Palestinians and 23 Israelis have
been killed.
   Bein said the expelled were involved in activities ranging from
throwing fire bombs and hand grenades to planting bombs, possessing
arms, blocking roads and imposing a reign of terror on the local
population.
   ``Expulsions, therefore, were the only means left to curtail
these activities,'' he said.
   The resolution, sponsored by Syria and the Arab League, demands
that Israel ensure the immediate return to the territories of
deported Palestinians and stop deportations.
   It cites the Geneva Convention of 1949, which covers treatment of
civilians in time of war and prohibits expulsions. Israel says the
convention permits limited deportations under special conditions,
and that its expulsions qualify.
   Current members of the council are Algeria, Brazil, Canada,
Colombia, Ethiopia, Finland, Nepal, Malaysia, Senegal, Yugoslavia
and the five permanent members: the United States, Soviet Union,
Britain, China and France.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890707-0064 </DOCNO>
