<FIRST>r a PM-People-Casinos     07-07 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Casinos,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>Showroom Stars Voice Support of Vegas Musicians in Tape Dispute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM DAHLBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A battle by musicians to block taped music in
resort showrooms got a boost when several stars led by Sammy Davis
Jr. rallied for live entertainment.
   ``We can't have this town, which was built on live entertainment,
live music, go the other way,'' said Davis. ``Don't let them do this
thing to us.''
   The entertainers show of support came Thursday for members of the
Musicians Union Local 369 who are locked in a dispute with five
major resorts.
   Davis, Jerry Lewis, Robert Goulet, Tony Orlando and Shecky Greene
turned out at a press conference called by the musicians to
publicize a fight musicians say will cost them dozens of their jobs.
   ``I don't want to see my friends _ the musicians _ go the way of
dinosaurs,'' Goulet said. ``For all of our sakes, let's bend a
little and come to a mutual understanding.''
   Some of the entertainers, however, professed little knowledge of
the details of the dispute, and some contradicted the union's
staunch position against eliminating jobs in production shows _
shows that feature an ensemble rather than a visiting headliner.
   ``I think that might be a concession the musicians can make,''
Lewis said, referring to the idea of using taped music at the
production shows. ``But don't bring it into the celebrity rooms,
where the Sinatras and the others perform.''
   The union is fighting a July 26 deadline three resorts have set
to eliminate musicians in production shows. The resorts, and two
others, have also proposed hiring musicians playing for showroom
singers only for the time they actually work instead of guaranteeing
them a certain number of paid weeks a year.
   ``How do you throw 45 lives away?'' Union President Mark Tully
Massagli said of those employed full-time in production shows.
``We've learned to live with some taping in town, but for an entire
production show to be put to a recording is not fair to the
musicians or the public.''
   Musicians went on strike last month against the Tropicana Hotel
when talks stalled on the resort's plan to use tape in its ``Folies
Bergere'' show and have warned of strikes against the Flamingo
Hilton, Caesars Palace, Bally's and the Las Vegas Hilton.
</TEXT>
