<FIRST>u i PM-Israel-Bus 2ndLd-Writethru a0491 07-07 0788</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Bus, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0491,0811</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reports Say Assailant Carefully Planned Bus Attack In Israel</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with criticism of Peres, Arabs praising
attack, police breaking up anti-Arab rally. No Pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Palestinian who grabbed the steering wheel of
a bus and forced the vehicle into a ravine, killing 14 people, rode
the route several times to choose the moment for the attack,
newspapers said today.
   The bearded attacker, identified only as a Palestinian refugee
camp resident, told investigators he was avenging beatings of family
members by soldiers, Israeli newspapers said.
   National Police Commissioner David Krauss announced a second
injured suspect was detained in connection with the bus crash
Thursday, the bloodiest assault since the Palestinian uprising began
19 months ago. Army radio identified him as the attacker's father,
but a police source denied that.
   Anger in Israel brought calls for imposing the death penalty on
terrorists.
   Arab newspapers hailed the attack.
   At the funeral of one Israeli victim in Jerusalem, security
forces rescued Finance Minister Shimon Peres from hundreds of people
shouting and pounding on his car. Peres heads the center-left Labor
Party, which calls for giving up occupied land for peace.
   Police on horseback dispersed supporters of the anti-Arab Kach
movement at a Jerusalem rally after 200 attacked officers arresting
six unruly protesters.
   ``Kill those who come to kill you!'' American-born Kach leader
Rabbi Meir Kahane told 1,000 supporters who screamed back, ``Death
to Arabs!''
   At another victim's funeral, Cabinet Minister Avner Shaki of the
National Religious Party demanded harsh measures.
   ``We must make supreme efforts at the next Cabinet meeting to ...
look for new, stubborn, non-routine and harsh ways so this filthy
Arab terrorism will end,'' said Shaki, who has no portfolio.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said the attack was ``the fruit of
a disgusting mind, wracked with hatred.''
   Jerusalem's daily Haaretz said the attacker ``planned in
detail,'' riding buses several times along route No. 405 from Tel
Aviv to Jerusalem, studying the road and drivers' behavior.
   The daily Hadashot said the suspect ``caused the bus to swerve at
a point in the road where the security barrier is the lowest and the
drop is dozens of meters.''
   Pro-government newspapers in the Persian Gulf praise the attack.
   Bahrain's Akhbar al-Khaleej said it was a ``unique and bold
operation ... affirming that the Palestinian people will not be
broken.''
   Qatar's al-Raya said, ``The bold guerrilla operation by a young
Palestinian man affirmed to the Zionist enemy that ... the Israelis
cannot continue with their repressive practices and brutal
oppression without a Palestinian response.''
   A senior Palestine Liberation Organization official in Tunisia,
Bassam Abu Sharif, said the attack was ``a human reaction by someone
who has had his children killed, seen families deported, houses
demolished.''
   The crash Thursday was the worst attack in Israel since a PLO
assault on a bus on March 11, 1978, that killed 33 people and
wounded 82.
   The crowded state-owned bus plunged Thursday into a 200-foot
ravine and exploded in flames after the attacker, shouting ``God is
Great!'' grabbed the steering wheel. The phrase is a rallying cry
for the uprising.
   The attacker was slightly hurt in the crash and arrested at the
scene, seven miles west of Jerusalem.
   Police said two of the dead were Canadians, the first foreigners
killed since the uprising began. They were identified as Shelley
Halpenny, a dentist in her mid-30s from Vancouver, British Columbia,
and Fern Rykiss, 17, of Winnipeg, Manitoba. Ten other fatalities
were identified as Israelis. The nationalities of the remaining two
were not known Thursday, but the U.S. Embassy said they were not
believed to be American.
   Twenty-seven passengers were injured and 25 remained hospitalized
today, five in serious condition, officials said. U.S. diplomats
said eight Amnerican passport holders were among them but refused to
identify the victims.
   Hospital officials identified four as Rita Levine, 39, in serious
condition; Eliezra Ben-Yehuda Cassuto, 53, in moderate condition;
and Paul Fingersh, 25, and Victor Assal, 24, with minor injuries.
Hometowns were not available. Mrs. Cassuto of New York is the
granddaughter of Eliezer Ben-Yahuda, a famous Jewish scholar who
helped revive Hebrew as a spoken language.
   Reuven Hazak, former head of the Shin Bet security service, told
Israel army radio the attack probably is linked to the Palestinian
uprising against Israeli rule in the occupied West Bank and Gaza
Strip.
   Arab reports said the assailant is believed to belong to either
Hamas or Islamic Jihad, which are fundamentalist Moslem groups.
Security officials told Israel radio they suspect
``nationalistic-religious motives.''
   Thursday's victims bring the toll in the uprising to 33 Israelis
and two Canadians killed. At least 546 Palsetinian have been killed.
</TEXT>
