<SECOND>PM-Barricaded Nun, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0493,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Last Barricaded Nun Leaves Carmelite Monastery</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS one graf on end with detail on first nun to give up protest,
who left in March.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MORRIS TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The last of five cloistered Roman
Catholic nuns has left her monastery after spending nine months
barricaded in the infirmary to protest liberal changes.
   Sister Teresita, who with four others locked herself in the room
on Oct. 4, left the Carmelite monastery Thursday, leaving no word on
her destination, said Tim Manning, a spokesman for the diocese of
Paterson.
   ``She indicated to another sister that she was going to a safe
place and would be in touch with Mother Theresa Hewitt,'' the
monastery's prioress, Manning said.
   Last Friday, three other nuns ended their self-imposed exile,
leaving only Sister Teresita in the infirmary. The three left with
an Akron, N.Y., priest, according to laywoman Betty Sutton, a
spokeswoman for the rebellious nuns.
   Neither Ms. Sutton nor Manning knew if Sister Teresita was to
join the other three nuns or how to reach them, they said.
   The five nuns began their protest quietly last October at the
monastery about 25 miles from New York City but soon found
themselves in a bitter struggle with Paterson Bishop Frank Rodimer
and their prioress.
   Reached by The Associated Press in March, Sister John of the
Cross, one of the five, said the group objected to reforms
instituted by the newly appointed prioress. They included such
things as candy, television and popular music that she said
detracted from the prayerful atmosphere intended by the founders of
the Carmelite order.
   The five held out through threatened evictions by Rodimer, hoping
their appeal to the Vatican would overrule the bishop's order to
leave the monastery. But in February, the Vatican affirmed Rodimer's
authority and the bishop ordered the nuns to leave.
   The first of the five protesting nuns left the monastery in
March, because of health problems.
</TEXT>
