<SECOND>PM-Tainted Wine,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Report Incidents Of Tainted Wine; No One Injured</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several bottles of cheap wine
tainted with a soapy solution or broken glass have been found
recently in areas frequented by transients, but no one has been
injured, police said.
   The tamperings might have been attempts to harm the homeless, but
if so, they were clumsy ones, police said. Officers noted that the
bottle seals had obviously been broken and the caps simply screwed
back on. The bottles were full.
   ``No one, under any circumstances, would want to have anything to
do with bottles like that,'' Sgt. Richard Glaus said. ``We made an
assumption, and we think it's a big assumption, that there might be
an intent to do harm.''
   The first three bottles were reported by a woman on May 27 at
Vera Cruz Park, an area often frequented by homeless people in this
seaside community 90 miles northwest of Los Angeles.
   The three bottles of Boones Farm Strawberry Hill contained a
soapy liquid, Glaus said. The liquid has not been tested.
   Last Saturday, three more tainted bottles, containing small bits
of broken glass, were found near railroad tracks and near a pathway
to a beach often used by homeless people, Glaus said.
   Police also had a report from a man who said he found some wine
that looked tainted June 27 but had thrown the bottles away.
</TEXT>
