<FIRST>r i PM-NATO-Galvin     07-07 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NATO-Galvin,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>NATO Commander Doesn't Want Talks on Short-Range Weapons</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NATO's supreme commander in Europe, Gen. John
Galvin, said today the Warsaw Pact's superiority in conventional
weapons is much more of a threat than its superiority in short-range
nuclear arms.
   Galvin also said that jumping into negotiations on reducing
short-range nuclear forces could make it tougher to bring the Warsaw
Pact to the bargaining table to discuss conventional weapons.
   ``If we get into the shorter-range nuclear forces too early,
we're giving away the major motivating idea, because the Soviets do
want to see us get rid of nuclear weapons,'' said Galvin. ``They are
not so anxious to get rid of conventional weapons.''
   He was commenting on Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev's
statement Thursday that the Warsaw Pact could agree on unilateral
cuts in Soviet short-range nuclear missiles in Eastern Europe if
NATO would negotiate reductions on those weapons. Galvin said the
Soviets have 1,400 short-range missiles launchers compared with
NATO's 88.
   Galvin also said that despite the appeal of glasnost, or
openness, he questioned whether Europe was safer because of the risk
of Soviet instability.
   ``I applaud the way the Soviet Union is moving,'' said Galvin.
``But it's a rocky road they're heading down. They're saying they
can't turn back, but they don't know precisely where they're going.''
   He also discussed the crash Tuesday of a Soviet MiG-23, which
zoomed across Western Europe, apparently missed by Soviet radar,
after its pilot ejected over Poland. The plane eventually crashed in
Belgium, killing a man in his house.
   Galvin said NATO troops' ability to spot the jet on radar and
follow it proved the Allied system works.
   ``Mathias Rust is one thing _ a little tiny plane flying at low
altitudes.'' said Galvin. ``But this plane took off from their own
airfield and was flying at high altitude.''
   He was referring to West German teen-ager Mathias Rust's ability
to evade Soviet air defenses two years ago and fly a small plane
into Red Square.
   Two U.S. F-15 fighters scrambled from a NATO base in the
Netherlands ``as a policing action'' as the Mig-23 crossed into
Western Europe on Tuesday, said Galvin. They shadowed it, hoping it
would crash into the North Sea.
   Galvin said he accepted Moscow's explanation that the incident
was an accident. The pilot ejected after reporting the plane was
smoking. The Soviets say their radar missed the MiG-23 as it flew on
for 500 miles.
   Galvin said the U.S. pilots did not shoot down the Mig-23 or move
alongside and tip it over because it was flying over populated areas.
</TEXT>
