<FIRST>u i PM-Burma 1stLd-Writethru   07-07 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Burma, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0536,0416</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands in Rangoon Commemorate Army Massacres</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 2nd graf, `Western diplomats...' to ADD radio report of
arrests. Pickup 3rd graf, `Up to...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of people today defied martial
law and rallied in memory of citizens killed during military
crackdowns, waving flags and shouting slogans, witnesses and
diplomats said.
   Western diplomats said groups of up to several hundred students
gathered in the center of Rangoon. Official Rangoon Radio said six
students were arrested.
   Up to 1,000 students gathered outside the gates of Rangoon
University in an attempt to lay a wreath, but armed troops forced
them to leave, said one diplomat who asked not to be identified by
name.
   Diplomats reported that soldiers blocked off some streets in an
effort to control the sporadic protests.
   Leading opposition figure Aung San Suu Kyi, speaking to a crowd
of several thousand in Rangoon, repeated her denunciations of the
ruling military for its refusal to hold talks with opposition
groups, a witness said.
   She spoke during a ceremony to remember a massacre of students
after the 1962 military coup and those killed during army crackdowns
on pro-democracy protests last year.
   Dozens of students were killed when the military put down a
demonstration at Rangoon University 26 years ago and blew up the
student union building.
   Several thousand were killed last year when troops crushed months
of pro-democracy demonstrations.
   Burma's former leader, Ne Win, is held responsible for ordering
both the 1962 and 1988 massacres. He officially relinquished control
in July 1988, but Suu Kyi has repeatedly charged that he is the
power behind the nominal head of state, Saw Maung.
   Suu Kyi, general secretary of the largest oppostion group, the
National League for Democracy, has drawn big crowds that have defied
martial law to hear her speak in Rangoon. Under existing military
law, gatherings of more than five people are forbidden.
   ``General Saw Maung and U Ne Win have identical views in their
disregard for dialogue and civil authority,'' Suu Kyi said.
   Residents said many people stayed indoors to avoid anticipated
clashes and some shops in the city closed during the afternoon.
   But witnesses said the military appeared to be keeping a low
profile and did not attempt to prevent political leaders from
speaking.
   On Wednesday, more than 10,000 Burmese rallied to hear Suu Kyi
speak in what Rangoon-based diplomats said was the largest political
gathering since last September.
</TEXT>
