<FIRST>u a PM-CollapseAnniversary 1stLd-Writethru a0430 07-07 0583</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Collapse Anniversary, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0430,0594</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Year Later, Brownsville Breaks Ground For Memorial On Store Collapse</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with quotes, detail from ceremony.
Picks up 9th graf pvs, `Levin faces...'.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY17</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Community leaders today broke ground
for a memorial to 14 people who were killed in the collapse of a
three-story department store during a torrential rain a year ago
today.
   ``For a brief moment in our day-to-day lives, everybody in this
community stopped ... to climb upon a rock pile and rub elbows with
some of the people that they pass on a day-to-day basis without ever
stopping,'' said Rusty Faulk, who was local disaster chairman for
the American Red Cross.
   Residents gathered this morning to remember the 14 people who
died July 7, 1988, when the Amigo Store collapsed in this border
town. At least 47 other people were injured.
   The memorial, which includes a palm tree planted near the former
store for each of the victims, was donated by the Rotary Club of
Brownsville-Sunrise. The memorial also honors the survivors and
hundreds of people who joined the rescue effort.
   Mayor Ygnacio Garza, who in the past year has also led the city
through a hurricane and a series of drug cult murders at nearby
Matamoros, Mexico, said people from out of town most often ask about
the Amigo Store disaster.
   ``They remember how the community responded, how we worked
together to save lives,'' Garza said.
   Store owner Bernard Levin, who was in the building when it
collapsed, escaped unscathed but said the thought of death and
suffering remain.
   ``Naturally, I feel a little beat,'' Levin said Wednesday. ``It's
very hard for me to keep going. Like today, it poured down raining
and I thought back to the Amigo Store.''
   Dr. Carmen Rocco, who treated survivors and consoled families
while rescuers clawed through the rubble, said she recalls events
just before the disaster and after the site was cleared.
   ``In between, there was so much pain and so much tragedy that I
really blocked it out,'' she said. ``All I really remember is an
incredible thunderstorm, and today we had one of those.''
   All that remains at the site a year later is vinyl flooring, the
tiles at the entrance and a gaping hole in the downtown business
district.
   Levin faces personal injury lawsuits seeking millions of dollars
in damages. The city, Public Utilities Board and various
construction firms and suppliers have been named as defendants, too.
   Among the survivors was 32-year-old Mexican Jose Luis Gaytan who
suffered brain damage while trapped in the rubble and no longer is
able to teach school, said Ernesto Gamez, his attorney.
   No official report has been released to explain what caused the
three-story structure to collapse in a storm that dumped two inches
of rain on the city in 30 minutes. The store was built in 1969 and
the third floor added in 1975.
   Dr. Lorenzo Pelly, who hitchhiked to the scene from Brownsville
Medical Center, said: ``The first thing I saw there was a guy who
had his face crushed between a parking meter and a car parked there
on the street.''
   Pelly said the outpouring of volunteers from throughout the lower
Rio Grande Valley united the region, but he regrets the bickering
among rescuers and the decision to dig instead of looking first for
survivors.
   Survivors were not located until hours later.
</TEXT>
