<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon     07-07 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moslems Asking Syria for Missiles, Tanks, to Counter Christian Armory</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem leaders said today they will ask
Syria for surface-to-surface missiles and tanks to counter new
missiles reportedly acquired from Iraq by their Christian foes.
   Syrian artillery shells continued to besiege the coast of the
Christian enclave north of Beirut today. Police said two people were
killed and seven wounded.
   The deaths raise the toll to 404 people killed and 1,558 wounded
since fighting erupted March 8 between the mainly Christian troops
of Gen. Michel Aoun's Lebanese army and Syrian-backed militiamen.
   Tension also heightened amid reports that 42 Christians were
kidnapped in Moslem sectors after Syrian-backed Moslem forces lifted
a land blockade of the Christian heartland two days ago.
   The An-Nahar newspaper reported the kidnappings, and Aoun's
command said the report was true. But police said they knew about no
abductions.
   Syria's barrage of Christian ports is to prevent Aoun from
receiving armaments, but Shiite Moslem leader Nabih Berri declared
today that the Christians on Thursday received a shipload of
Soviet-designed Frog-7 missiles and T-54 and T-55 tanks from Iraq.
Berri, leader of the mainstream Amal militia and Syria's closest
ally in Lebanon, was speaking in Damascus, after meeting with
Lebanese Druse warlord Walid Jumblatt.
   Aoun's command refused to comment on the report he has acquired
the missiles, which have a range of 43 miles and can carry warheads
containing 1,210 pounds of explosive.
   Berri charged the Christians will deploy the new armaments
against Moslem forces.
   ``They're not to threaten Syria or any other country,'' he said.
``They're to be used against the Lebanese and the parties of the
national coalition,'' an alliance of six Moslem parties.
   Syria this week charged Christian forces received six Frog-7
missiles in April and demanded they be removed because they could
hit Damascus if fired from Christian-held positions in mountains
northeast of Beirut. The mountains are 40 miles from Damascus.
   Berri claimed Christian missiles are ``aimed at my house, the
house of Walid Jumblatt and at the Syrian headquarters'' in Beirut.
   He said he has not officially asked Syria for the missiles and is
waiting for President Hafez Assad to return from his summer
residence ``in order to put this request to him.''
   ``The Syrians must help us. We are their allies. If they cannot,
or will not, then it is our right to seek to purchase such advanced
weapons from any source,'' Berri told reporters.
   A statement from his Amal militia published by Beirut newspapers
said acquisition of the missiles would ``lead to a destructive
catastrophe that will not spare areas in east or west Beirut.''
</TEXT>
