<FIRST>r i PM-ArmsTalks     07-07 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Arms Talks,0424</SECOND>
<HEAD>Warsaw Pact Asks NATO to Present Bush Arms Proposal Soon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIOREL URMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Warsaw Pact nations today asked NATO to
present President Bush's arms reduction initiatives at the East-West
disarmament talks.
   Officials said they hope details of the proposal will be
submitted before next week, when the current round of talks is to
end.
   ``We're pressing strongly that they present the framework of the
proposals by the end of this round on July 13,'' said Wlodzimierz
Konarski, Polish delegation chief at the talks on conventional armed
forces in Europe.
   In May, Bush won NATO support for a proposal to reduce U.S. and
Soviet troops in Europe to 275,000 on each side. That would require
the Soviets to withdraw and demobilize 325,000 Red Army soldiers.
   Bush also proposed limits on tanks, armored troop carriers and
artillery pieces. And he said the West is willing to expand its
proposal to include, for the first time, land-based combat aircraft
and helicopters from the Atlantic to the Soviet Ural mountains.
   Western experts at the Western alliance headquarters in Brussels
said last month they would formally present Bush's proposals to the
Warsaw Pact when talks open for their third round on Sept. 5.
   Konarski, speaking for the East bloc, was optimistic about
progress but mentioned some differences.
   ``We all now agree that a future agreement should cover six
categories of conventional armed forces even though a formal
proposal of our Western partners to this effect has not yet been
submitted,'' Konarski told reporters.
   He said if the main obstacles were overcome during the next round
``then the agreement could indeed be concluded within 12 months,''
the timetable suggested by Bush.
   NATO opened the Vienna talks on conventional arms reductions
March 9 proposing each military bloc reduce three kinds of weapons _
tanks, artillery and armored personnel carriers.
   The Soviet military bloc countered with a far broader, less
specific proposal to reduce six kinds of weapons 10 percent to 15
percent below present levels by 1994, then add a further 25 percent
reduction by 1997 before moving to only defensive forces in 2000.
   Reductions in aircraft are among points of disagreement. Western
delegates say aircraft are difficult to count and can be redeployed
in any disarmed zone within hours. Konarski made clear the issue is
of vital importance for the future of the talks. ``The issue of
aircraft remains to be solved as a matter of priority,'' he said.
</TEXT>
