<FIRST>r i AM-Baltics-Land     07-07 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baltics-Land,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baltic Republic Steps Beyond Kremlin in Decollectivizing Land</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The parliament of Soviet Lithuania passed a law
this week that goes a step beyond national legislation in giving
land back to farmers after decades of collectization, newspapers
reported Friday.
   The law stops short of total decollectivization, but would _
without charge _ give farmers the land they farm now with the right
to pass it on to heirs, according to Sovietskaya Litva, the
Lithuanian Communist Party daily.
   The law does not allow farmers to sell land, a step the Kremlin
might view as a violation of the communist ban on ownership of major
private property.
   Soviet farms have been owned by the state or by state-controlled
collectives since 1929-30.
   The bill could strengthen efforts by the Baltic republics of
Lithuania, Estonia and Lativa to become more autonomous. They were
occupied and annexed by the Soviet Union in 1940.
   It was not clear whether the national legislature, the Supreme
Soviet, would try to override the new Lithuanian law in the same way
it vetoed a law passed by the legislature of Estonia last fall
proclaiming autonomy in the republic.
   The Lithuanian law, which has not yet been published in full,
went beyond national legislation passed in April allowing farmers to
rent land on 50-year leases with a right to pass it on to
descendants.
   Farmers have been slow to take out leases, fearing the reforms
could be overturned, according to poll results published in April by
the Communist Party daily newspaper Pravda.
   The Lithuanian law, according to the newspaper Izvestia, said
``land, granted to the peasant for use with no fixed term, with
rights of inheritance and without payment, does not include the
right to sale.''
   Activists in the Lithuanian grassroots political group Sajudis
had been pushing for more radical legislation that would have
granted farmers the right to buy and sell land, but a compromise was
reached in the republic's legislature, said Zhilvenas Glebus,
reached by telephone in the Lithuanian capital of Vilnius.
   The Lithuanian law will go into effect Aug. 1, according to
Sajudis workers, quoting the Sovietskaya Litva article.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
