<FIRST>r i PM-Poland-WestGermany 1stLd-Writethru   07-07 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland-West Germany, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0518,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poles Express Anger at West German's Remarks on Border</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 3 grafs with Solidarity official's comment. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party newspaper reacted
angrily to remarks by West Germany's finance minister that Germany
should be reunified within its 1937 borders, which include about a
third of Poland.
   Finance Minister Theo Waigel said in Hanover on Sunday that the
German Reich in its borders of 1937 did not cease to exist with the
German army's 1945 capitulation to the Allies.
   Waigel said his party, the Christian Social Union, would never
allow the demand for reunification of the two Germanies to be
stricken from the West German Constitution.
   If the old German borders were recognized, Poland would lose some
of its largest cities, such as Wroclaw and Szczecin, and its biggest
industrial region in southeastern Silesia.
   ``Questioning at a revisionist rally the map of postwar Europe
and the irreversible character of the border on the Odra and Nysa
rivers, Minister Waigel, as a government representative, strikes at
our fundamental national and state rationale,'' said the editorial
in the Polish Communist Party's Trybuna Ludu on Thursday.
   ``Such a line .... is unacceptable for the Polish nation and for
all Poles regardless of their political orientation.''
   Although West Germany has been the most active Western country in
promoting relations with the communist countries of Central and East
Europe, Polish-West German relations have been strained by a host of
bilateral issues.
   West Germany wants better treatment for the German minority that
remained in the former German territories after World War II, and
there is resentment toward the flood of Polish emigrants or illegal
workers who have taken advantage of liberalized passport laws to
travel to West Germany.
   Poland has accused West Germany of insensitivity to its
sovereignty because of the calls by rightist politicians for old
German territories and because of West Germany's refusal to grant
economic assistance unless Poland makes concessions on the
minorities issue.
   In Bonn today, a leading Solidarity official urged Polish
reconciliation with West Germany but said his country should not
give up any land.
   ``Those who question existing borders damage perspectives for
stability in Europe,'' said Bronislaw Geremek, leader of
Solidarity's deputies in the Polish parliament.
   Geremek also said he sees ``new chances for (closer) relations
between Germans and Poles,'' and that problems holding up an
agreement in ongoing bilateral talks ``are only of the second
order.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890707-0097 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-89 1231EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-OilProbe     07-07 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oil Probe,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>N.C. Attorney General Calls for Federal Probe Of Gasoline Price-Fixing</HEAD>
<HEAD>By DENNIS PATTERSON</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Carolina's attorney general called
today for a federal investigation of price-fixing by major oil
companies, saying a state probe showed either greed or collusion is
behind recent price increases.
   ``Greed isn't illegal, but price fixing is, and that has been the
focus of our investigation here in North Carolina,'' Attorney
General Lacy Thornburg said.
   Thornburg said the oil companies have blamed the wreck of the
Exxon Valdez in Alaska and normal market forces such as increased
summer demand and higher crude oil prices for the rapid increase in
gasoline prices over the past four months.
   But Thornburg said Valdez spill ``was simply a small drop in a
very large bucket.'' He said crude oil prices have not affected
prices for other petroleum products, such as heating oil and diesel
fuel.
   ``The oil companies have put forward other excuses for the
simultaneous gas price increases, but their arguments have more
holes than the hull of the Exxon Valdez,'' Thornburg said.
   He said investigators tracked prices for three months from
retailers back through wholesale terminals and the major
out-of-state suppliers, finding that price increases took place at
the refinery level, while profits of wholesalers and retailers
remained stable.
   Thornburg said he had forwarded the state's investigation and a
formal request for a federal investigation to U.S. Attorney General
Richard Thornburgh in Washington.
   The North Carolina official said he also will ask his
counterparts in other states at a meeting this weekend to form a
task force to examine the price fixing allegations.
   ``I anticipate we will get a good response from the federal
government,'' Thornburg said. ``We can demonstrate with other states
a general outcry around the country, and when you have a widespread
public outcry, you usually can get a positive response.
   ``It is awfully difficult to prove price-fixing. It always has
been,'' Thornburg said. ``But we're certainly going to give it our
best shot.''
