<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan-US     07-07 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan-US,0240</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Embassy Delhi Trying for Journalist's Release</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Embassy will send a
representative to Kabul to secure the release of an American
photojournalist arrested by the Afghan government, an official said
Friday.
   Arrangements were being made to obtain the release of Tony
O'Brien, a free-lance photographer on assignment for Time-Life Inc.,
said an embassy official, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   ``Things are still on track,'' the official said. He said he
could not estimate how long it would take for arrangements to be
completed.
   The Kabul government said July 1 that O'Brien, of Santa Fe, N.M.,
would be released without trial if the State Department sent an
official to take him home. It said the decision was made in response
to an appeal from Palestine Liberation Organization Chairman Yasser
Arafat.
   O'Brien, 42, was arrested June 8 for entering Afghanistan without
legal documents and in the company of Moslem rebels fighting the
Soviet-backed government.
   He had been covering the Afghan civil war from Peshawar,
Pakistan, the base for many Moslem guerrilla groups.
   O'Brien has made several trips into Afghanistan with the
guerrillas. Under emergency laws in Afghanistan, he could have been
jailed for entering the country without legal documents, for which
there is no maximum sentence.
   The U.S. Embassy in Kabul was closed in January, before the
Soviet Union completed its troop withdrawal from Afghanistan.
</TEXT>
