<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Vietnam     07-07 0171</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Vietnam,0176</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vietnam Population Grows to 64 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam announced its population has
grown to 64.4 million, and it called on all families to have no more
than two children.
   The official Vietnam News Agency said the population had grown by
11.7 million since the last census in 1979, representing a high
annual growth rate of 2.13 percent.
   An editorial in the Communist Party's newspaper, Nhan Dan, urged
all people to observe the national target of one or two children per
family, the agency said.
   Vietnam's already high and rapidly growing population has emerged
as a major problem for the country, which faces large-scale
unemployment, a poor social and economic infrastructure and
difficulties in feeding its current population.
   The most populous city in Vietnam is Ho Chi Minh City with 3.9
million people, according to the census, conducted April 1. Hanoi,
the capital, has 3.1 million.
   The census also showed there were 2,432 people _ 1,728 women and
704 men _ over the age of 100.
</TEXT>
