<FIRST>r i AM-Philippines     07-07 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines,0508</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aquino to Seek Investment, Political Support in Europe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Buoyed by the promise of billions in
foreign aid, President Corazon Aquino leaves Saturday on a
three-nation West European tour in search of financial and political
support for her troubled country.
   Philippine officials say Mrs. Aquino will try to exploit her
image as savior of Filipino democracy to encourage greater trade and
investment to help cope with problems of poverty, communist
insurgency and a $28 billion foreign debt.
   She also hopes to dispel European fears that her government has
been laggard in fulfilling the pledge to protect human rights made
when she was swept to power in the 1986 uprising that toppled
Ferdinand Marcos' authoritarian administration.
   ``I would like to deliver to the people and countries of Europe
the message that the Philippines is committed to democracy, which
our people restored in a very unique way, by peaceful means,'' she
said in a radio broadcast this week.
   Mrs. Aquino will travel to West Germany, then to France to join
bicentennial celebration of the French Revolution, and finally to
Belgium.
   Mrs. Aquino's trip, her second to Europe as president, follows a
commitment Wednesday by industrial countries and international
financial institutions to provide $3.5 billion in 1989 in aid for
the Philippines. As part of the program, the European Economic
Community promised to triple its aid to about $350 million a year.
   The visit represents another step in Manila's efforts to expand
trade and contacts with Western Europe and broaden its foreign
policy, which traditionally focused on its former colonial power,
the United States.
   In February, the European Parliament expressed support for Mrs.
Aquino but added it was concerned about mounting human rights
violations.
   Human rights groups, including Amnesty International, accuse the
military and government-backed vigilante groups of widespread
torture, assassinations and illegal abductions of suspected rebels
on flimsy evidence.
   Officials say Mrs. Aquino will argue her government is committed
to human rights but faces a serious threat from the 23,000-member
communist New People's Army, which has been waging a 20-year war to
establish a Marxist state.
   Ten policemen and soldiers have been slain in the Manila area in
the last two weeks in attacks which the military blames on communist
rebels.
   Opposition Sen. Juan Ponce Enrile said Friday that Mrs. Aquino's
trip will reinforce the country's image as a borrower and a beggar.
He said Mrs. Aquino was leaving behind a nation in turmoil.
   On the eve of her departure, the government announced the arrest
of a soldier in the 1988 murder of a left-wing activist and the
attempted slaying of a companion in one of the country's best-known
human rights cases.
   The National Bureau of Investigation said Constable 2nd Class
Dioscoro Ambagay Jr., was arrested and warrants have been issued for
two more soldiers in the slaying of leftist Reynaldo Francisco and
an attempt on the life of Hilario Bustamante in March 1988.
</TEXT>
