<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-89 1333EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Namibia     07-07 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia,0423</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Refugee Flights to Capital Halted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Nations has halted refugee
flights to the capital of Namibia because resettlement camps are
overflowing, a U.N. spokesman said Friday.
   The refugees, most of them supporters of the guerrilla movement
that fought for 23 years against South African rule, have stayed in
the camps around Windhoek longer than the seven days the U.N. High
Commissioner for Refugees had planned on.
   U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said the refugees are reluctant to
leave and go to their home villages in the north, where the
South-West African People's Organization has most of its support,
because they fear Namibian police will harass them.
   Refugees who have been flown into northern cities have moved out
of the temporary settlement camps and those flights will continue,
Eckhard said. The United Nations has arranged for representatives in
the camps near Windhoek to travel to the north, see the situation
and report back, with the hope that the refugees in the camps will
be persuaded to leave.
   The U.N. spokesman said 16,244 of the 41,000 Namibians registered
with the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees have returned so far,
mostly from SWAPO camps in Angola and Zambia.
   All refugees are to return by Sept. 15, the end of the
registration period for voting in elections planned for November.
   He said two planeloads of Namibians from Cuba were due to arrive
on July 18 and July 24, and that small groups have returned from
Britain and the United States.
   SWAPO said before the independence process began that it was
caring for some 80,000 refugees with U.N. aid, but there has been no
explanation for the change in numbers.
   About 150 refugees who returned this week had been held prisoner
by SWAPO in Angolan camps. In response to their tales of torture and
allegations that SWAPO is holding hundreds more prisoners, Martti
Ahtisaari, the U.N. special representative in Namibia, appealed
Friday for all prisoners on both sides to be freed under terms of
U.N. Resolution 435.
   South Africa has withdrawn all but 1,500 of its troops from the
territory it has ruled since 1915 and has agreed to grant Namibia
independence.
   But Louis Pienaar, the South African administrator of the
territory until it becomes independent, said Wednesday he will not
free about 30 SWAPO prisoners held by the police until a full
accounting is made of all prisoners who may still be in the hands of
the guerrilla movement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
