<HEAD>Air Base Reports Three F-16 Engines Missing, Each Weighing 3,500
Pounds</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to DELETE incorrect reference to engines being
16 feet tall; that is height when they are sitting on the trailer they
are stored on. Spokeswoman did not have exact height of engine alone.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HILL AIR FORCE BASE, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three F-16 fighter jet engines
worth about $2 million apiece have disappeared from Hill Air Force
Base, a spokeswoman said today.
   The missing engines are 17 feet long and weigh 3,500 pounds
apiece. They apparently were taken off the base sometime between
noon Saturday and noon Monday, said Maj. Portia McCracken.
   ``Nothing like this has ever happened in my memory. I would say
that it is very unusual,'' McCracken said.
   McCracken was unable to say whether the Air Force had any
suspects, and said investigators would have little to say about the
disappearances until they finish their probe.
   Utah FBI spokesman Tim Screen said he could not comment on the
investigation.
   The Air Force had said Thursday that at least one engine was
missing, and then confirmed this morning that three were missing.
   The missing engines are rebuilt Pratt &amp; Whitney F-100 TW200
series. McCracken said she was unsure whether the engines belonged
to Hill or if they had been sent from another base to be serviced.
   The Air Force's 388th Tactical Fighter Wing and the Utah Air
National Guard's 419th Tactical Fighter Wing, both based at Hill,
fly the F-16.
   Some of the engines housed at Hill are used for the fighters, and
others are shipped in from other bases for maintenance at the Ogden
Air Logistics Center.
</TEXT>
