<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-89 1429EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     07-07 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zoo officials are hoping a blind date between
two mateless gorillas will blossom into romance _ and a baby gorilla.
   Hercules, 23, is on loan indefinitely from the National Zoo in
Washington to the Pittsburgh Zoo as part of the national Species
Survival Plan in the hopes that Zakula, 22, will find him attractive.
   Hercules never mated with any of the gorillas he lived with at
the Baltimore Zoo and National Zoo.
   Zakula lived for 19 years with Sultan, who died of a heart attack
in October. She had three miscarriages but no live births.
   Zakula didn't show signs of love at first sight when Hercules
arrived in Pittsburgh Thursday, but she wasn't acting angry either,
said Janice Frazier, one of the gorilla's keepers.
   ``Right now, she's mostly curious,'' she said. ``I'm sure she can
smell him. I'm sure she knows a gorilla is here.''
   Hercules will be quarantined for 30 days to give him time to
adjust to his new home and let zoo officials monitor his health.
   The two are lowland gorillas, an endangered species. Only five
lowland gorillas have been born in zoos, bringing the North American
population to 293.
   Melanie Bond, Hercules' keeper in Washington since 1981, said the
low birthrate in captivity reflects the animals' mating habits.
   ``They do not like everyone they date. They have to find the
right one,'' she said.

</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MINOT AIR FORCE BASE, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After Minot Air Force Base
Master Sgt. Paul R. Engeldinger re-enlisted for the fifth time, he
gave the re-enlistment officer a big kiss.
   After all, she was his wife, 1st Lt. Kathleen Engeldinger.
   ``This is definitely something special,'' Lt. Engeldinger said.
   Sgt. Engeldinger, who has been in the Air Force more than 20
years, is in charge of the scheduling control branch of the 4091st
Missile Maintenance Group.
   His re-enlistment Wednesday was for three more years.
   The Engeldingers, who have been married 12 years, said they try
to keep their professional and personal lives separate.
   ``When we were married, it was frowned upon that an officer would
become involved with an enlisted person,'' Lt. Engeldinger said.
   ``I think we've done a good job in supporting each other,'' her
husband added.
</TEXT>
