<FIRST>r i AM-Bulgaria-Turks     07-07 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bulgaria-Turks,0401</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bulgaria Decrees Conscription for Emergencies as Ethnic Turks Leave</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOFIA, Bulgaria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has issued a decree
empowering authorities to conscript civilians to work in
``emergencies'' threatening the economy, apparently to counter a
massive exodus of ethnic Turks.
   Authorities can send civilians to work anywhere in the country
under the decree.
   Western diplomats and journalists who have visited areas where
ethnic Turks lived say many towns and villages are nearly empty and
fields remain unharvested.
   Austrian TV showed footage this week from Bulgaria of fields
strewn with unharvested fruit and rotting vegetables.
   About 100,000 ethnic Turks have fled to Turkey in recent months,
claiming they have been victimized by an assimilation campaign begun
in 1984 which bans them from using their Turkish names, speaking
Turkish or practicing Islamic rites.
   Bulgaria's State Council issued the decree on June 30, but it was
not published until this week, Western diplomats said. Excerpts were
made available to The Associated Press on Friday.
   According to the decree, men aged 18 to 60 and women 18 to 55 can
be mobilized nationwide or on a regional basis. It did not say for
how long.
   People can be called up ``to ensure the necessary manpower and
equipment in emergencies or natural calamities presenting
considerable difficulties to the national economy and to the
country.''
   Invalids, pregnant women and mothers of children under 7 are
exempt.
   ``Those who evade civilian mobilization or without a plausible
reason fail to fulfill their assignments will be fined'' up to
$3,000, the decree said.
   Mobilized civilians will be paid according to undisclosed norms
established by the Council of Ministers, it said.
   Diplomats in Sofia said they have no information that any
mobilization has begun, and the decree does not say when it takes
effect.
   Ethnic Turks make up the main workforce in parts of eastern and
southern Bulgaria, especially in agricultural, tobacco and food
production.
   Turkish Premier Turgut Ozal said earlier this week that Bulgaria
is suffering labor shortages and economic hardships as a result of
the exodus.
   Mesut Yilmaz, Turkey's Foreign Minister, said last week the flow
would increase immensely if Bulgaria signs an immigration agreement
with Turkey.
   Turkish officials say as many as 300,000 ethnic Turks could
arrive from Bulgaria. About 1 million of Bulgaria's 9 million people
are ethnic Turks.
</TEXT>
