<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     07-07 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0401</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspapers Criticize Censorship</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The following report was submitted to a
government censor. No changes were made.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security forces armed with emergency
laws arrested at least 49 suspected Sinhalese radicals as continuing
civil unrest claimed 25 lives, the government said Friday.
   Military and police, operating under new shoot-on-sight orders,
killed eight radicals in skirmishes when they made the arrests, the
information department said. Ten radicals were injured, it said.
   Extremists of the left-wing People's Liberation Front killed 12
civilians, three soldiers and a police officer since Wednesday, the
statement said.
   No further details were given to the press, working under strict
censorship laws clamped Thursday to coincide with a government
crackdown on the anti-government extremists. A nationwide emergency
was imposed June 20.
   The country's two main newspapers Friday warned that censoring
the news fuels rumors.
   Critical editorials in The Island and The Sun newspapers were
submitted to government censors. Sources at the dailies said the
editorials were approved without changes.
   ``Tongues wag in Sri Lanka ... censorship will be of no avail,''
said The Island. ``The danger of censorship is that all fantastic
rumors tend to gain more credibility.''
   The Sun said: ``What must necessarily be stressed is the futility
of the exercise, as censorship often in the past turned out to be
counterproductive. With the technical stoppage of news and views,
the flow of rumor, gossip and electronic tele-talk takes over with
no holds barred.''
   Police in Colombo, meanwhile, said leading human rights activist
and criminal lawyer Charita Lankapura was shot and killed Friday by
two unidentified men. No details were released.
   Sinhalese radicals launched a campaign to topple the government
two years ago to protest peace overtures being made to Tamil rebels
demanding an independent nation in the northeast.
   The Sinhalese front says too many concessions are being made to
the minority Tamils, who make up 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16
million people. Sinhalese make up 75 percent of the population.
   The front has been blamed for killing 3,500 people in two years,
mostly government officials, governing party members and security
force personnel.
   The government says the radicals instigated an ongoing strike by
public transport workers that has been crippling the economy for
four weeks.
</TEXT>
