<FIRST>u w PM-PayRaise 5thLd-Writethru a0616-a0621 07-07 0566</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pay Raise, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0616-a0621,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Asks 8-25 Percent Pay Hike for Senior Officials</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Combines pvs files; edits reference to pay raise rejection in
next last graf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush today asked Congress to give
some 7,200 federal executives pay increases of 8 percent to 25
percent, with even higher raises going to a selected 200 with
special skills.
   However, the president coupled his pay-raise plan with a proposal
that the officials justify their right to the higher salaries every
three years to be able to keep receiving them.
   Bush's proposal would give full 25 percent hikes to just the most
senior officials, matching a salary hike he has already advocated
for federal judges.
   More junior officials would get smaller increases, at least
initially, under the plan.
   The president also called for a phaseout of congressional
peechmaking honoraria over a two-year period and said it should be
linked to a pay raise for lawmakers. But he stopped short of
recommending a specific level.
   Presidential press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said Bush wanted
Congress to take the initiative on that politically touchy subject
itself, but that he was ready to work with congressional leaders on
a complete package.
   The plan would raise the pay of top federal officials, including
Cabinet members, to $124,400 from the present $99,500.
   It would also raise the salary of Vice President Dan Quayle from
$115,000 to $143,000. But it would not affect Bush's $200,000 salary.
   The total pay package would cost taxpayers $101 million in the
fiscal year that begins next Oct. 1; and $147 million in the
following fiscal year, Fitzwater said.
   He said the increases would be in addition to a 3.6 percent
cost-of-living increase the president is seeking for 2.2 million
federal workers.
   The package would, for the first time, set up a special super
category for federal employes with special talents, enabling them to
get salaries up to the $124,400 top level. Fitzwater said 200
individuals would qualify for these special salaries, to be
determined at a later time.
   He suggested that nuclear scientists, physicians or others with
special talents would be the type of individual considered for the
special salaries.
   The most controversial part of the new package, however, may be
the requirement that all members of the Senior Executive Service
undergo a re-certification process every three years to keep their
higher salaries.
   The procedure is designed to ``assure that these people perform
at a level that justifies the higher salary. We do not believe it
would weaken their rights,'' Fitzwater said.
   He said the certification would not apply to the government's 700
high-level political appointees _ like Cabinet members and others
appointed by the president and confirmed by the Senate _ because
they ``can be removed at any time without appeal'' by the president.
   The 7,200 members of the Senior Executive Service and 700 appoint
executives currently make $68,700 to $80,700. Their pay is tied to
the $89,500 that members of Congress get, and lawmakers' rejection
of a proposed 51 percent congressional pay increase in February
meant no raise for them or for judges.
   A private commission headed by former Federal Reserve Board
Chairman Paul Volker has recommended a 25 percent increase
immediately followed by a similar amount in 1991, applying to
judges, executive branch officials, members of Congress and others
such as top military officers.
</TEXT>
