<FIRST>r w AM-US-AfricaDebt     07-07 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Africa Debt,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>US to Forgive Debt to 16 African Countries</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's decision to forgive some
African debt includes 16 nations and totals about $1 billion,
officials said Friday.
   Bush's announcement Thursday will ease the debt burden starting
Oct. 1 for Benin, Cameroon, Ghana, Guinea, Ivory Coast, Kenya,
Madagascar, Malawi, Mali, Niger, Nigeria, Senegal, Somalia,
Tanzania, Uganda and Zaire.
   One official estimated the face value of the loans at $590
million to $600 million. The rest would be interest already due or
expected to become due over the life of the loans.
   An additional $400 million will be forgiven to seven other
countries if they adopt new economic policies to put themselves into
better financial shape, in cooperation with the World Bank and the
International Monetary fund, the officials added. But they said some
of the seven, such as Ethiopia, are not likely to adopt such
programs.
   The others are: Zimbabwe, Sudan, Liberia, Botswana, Zambia and
Swaziland.
   The officials from the State Department and the Agency for
International Development spoke on condition that their names not be
used.
   Though Latin America has much heavier debt than Africa, the
burden on many African countries is considered heavier because their
populations are much poorer and smaller.
   The forgiveness was announced Thursday by President Bush at a
news conference for non-American reporters and stems from last
year's economic summit. The leaders of the seven major non-Communist
governments, including Bush, will meet in Paris next week for a
meeting.
   One State Department official said the other nations already have
forgiven most of such debt owed to them, and so have some other
creditors including the Nordic countries and the Netherlands.
   One AID official explained that many of the debts to the United
States go back as much as 30 years. More recently aid to the poorest
countries has been given in the form of grants, as it was when major
U.S. aid programs began in the 1940s.
   ``Some of the grants have been going to pay interest on the old
loans,'' the official added.
   Some debtor governments have not been paying for years, so that
forgiving their debts will not have much practical effect for them.
   The loans to be forgiven were made for development projects and
as economic aid to countries considered strategically important to
the United States. The officials said there would be no effect on
loans given by the government's Export-Import Bank to encourage the
sale of U.S. industrial products, by the Agriculture Department to
encourage the sale of farm products or by the Defense Department for
weapons and training.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
