<FIRST>r i AM-Extradition-US     07-07 0605</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Extradition-US,0627</SECOND>
<HEAD>German Wins Rights Court Ruling Against Extradition to USA</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINA MACKENZIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   STRASBOURG, France _ In a landmark ruling Friday, the European
Court of Human Rights said a West German must not be extradited to
the United States because he could face execution if he is convicted
of a double murder.
   Jens Soering, 22, who is jailed in Britain, is wanted for the
stabbing deaths of a girlfriend's parents in Virginia in 1985. The
British government agreed last year to his extradition.
   But the court in Strasbourg said if Soering is sent to Virginia,
the prospect of execution violates his rights under the European
Human Rights Convention, whose charter bans ``inhuman or degrading
treatment or punishment.''
   ``The applicant's extradition to the United States would expose
him to a real risk'' of treatment banned under the European human
rights charter, the court ruled.
   The court said if Soering were sent instead to West Germany,
which also has asked for his extradition, he would not face the
death penalty and would not serve years on death row, which the
court said also violates the charter.
   Court officials said the ruling broke new ground because it
involved human rights abuses that had not yet occurred.
   ``Normally the court has the power to rule only on ... violations
of human rights,'' said Paul Mahoney, a lawyer at the court.
   Rulings by the rights court, a branch of the 23-nation Council of
Europe, are not binding on the 23 council nations but are rarely
ignored.
   Soering was arrested in Britain on a check fraud charge in April
1986 after evading arrest in the United States, where he is charged
in the March 30, 1985, slayings of William and Nancy Haysom in their
home in Bedford County, Va.
   Elizabeth Haysom, his girlfriend at the time, is serving a
90-year sentence for her part in the killings.
   The court did not address Soering's guilt in the deaths of the
parents, opposed Soering's relationship with their daughter.
   Mahoney said Soering has admitted to participating in the
killings but has given differing accounts of the circumstances.
   Sending Soering to West Germany ``would not involve suffering of
such exceptional intensity or duration,'' said Rolv Ryssdal of
Norway, the court's president.
   The ruling noted inmates spend between six and eight years on
Virginia's death row as their cases go through a lengthy review
process.
   West Germany abolished the death penalty in 1949. If convicted in
West Germany, Soering faces a maximum prison sentence of 10 to 15
years.
   Ryssdal said the court's ruling against extradition also took
into account Soering's state of mind and that he was 18 at the time
of the killings.
   Psychiatrists have said he ``had lost his personal identity in a
symbiotic relationship with his girlfriend _ a powerful, persuasive
and disturbed young woman.''
   The court ordered the British government to pay Soering's legal
costs of about $42,720. It dismissed minor claims by Soering,
including the allegation he did not get a fair hearing in British
courts that considered the U.S. extradition request.
   Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., who was in Strasbourg for Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's speech to the Council of Europe,
denounced the ruling as ``indefensible.''
   Jim Updike, the Bedford County, Va., prosecutor heading the case
against Soering, said the decision was ``illogical.'' ``He is guilty
of the extremely brutal murder of two human beings,'' Updike told
The Associated Press.
   The European Court of Human Rights is a body of Council of
Europe, the oldest organization striving for European unity. It was
founded in 1949 and is separate from the 12-nation European Economic
Community.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
