<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0610 07-07 0637</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0610,0651</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syria Shells Christian Coast</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE casualties. Pickup 5th graf, `Nabih
Berri ...''; SUBS 15th graf, ``Pro-Iranian militiamen ...'' to conform.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian troops shelled the Christian coast
Friday, and the head of a Moslem militia said he wants missiles to
counter those reportedly acquired by Christian forces and ``aimed at
my house.''
   Also Friday, scattered clashes between rival Moslem militias left
two people dead and four wounded, police said.
   The shelling _ a daily effort to keep ships from supplying the
Christian enclave _ killed three people and wounded seven, police
said.
   The casualties from the shelling raised the overall toll to 405
people killed and 1,558 wounded since March 8, when the fighting
started between the Christian forces loyal to the government led by
Gen. Michel Aoun and Syrian troops backing a rival Moslem Cabinet.
   Nabih Berri, head of the Shiite Moslem Amal militia, said in the
Syrian capital, Damascus, that he wants to match a shipload of
Soviet-designed Frog-7 missiles as well as T-54 and T-55 tanks he
said the Christians received Thursday from Iraq.
   ``They're not to threaten Syria or any other country,'' he said.
``They're to be used against the Lebanese and the parties of the
national coalition,'' an alliance of six Moslem parties.
   His vow threatened to escalate the conflict that the Arab League
has been trying to halt. Amal had stayed out of the fighting over
the past 16 weeks.
   Christian sources reported in April that Iraq _ Syria's main Arab
foe _ delivered six Frog-7s to the Lebanese Forces, the Christians'
main militia.
   Syria, which maintains 40,000 troops in Lebanon, demanded that
the missiles shipped in April be removed because they can hit
Damascus, 40 miles from Christian positions in mountains northeast
of Beirut. Syria has linked the issue to lifting the naval blockade.
   Aoun has not confirmed that his 20,000 mainly Christian troops
possess Frog-7s and his aides have been vague in answering questions
about the missiles.
   Berri made his comments after meeting with Druse Moslem chieftain
Walid Jumblatt, who heads the Progressive Socialist party militia.
   Berri said he had told Syrian officials that the Christians'
missiles were ``aimed at my house, the house of Walid Jumblatt and
at the Syrian headquarters'' in Moslem west Beirut.
   ``The Syrians must help us. We are their allies. If they cannot,
or will not, then it is our right to seek to purchase such advanced
weapons from any source,'' Berri said.
   He said no official request has been made to the Syrians, but
that he was waiting for President Hafez Assad to return from his
summer residence in the coastal city of Latakia to make the request.
   Pro-Iranian militiamen of Hezbollah, or Party of God, and
fighters of the Syrian-backed Amal, the mainstream Shiite Moslem
militia, fought scattered gunbattles in south Beirut's seaside Ouzai
district Friday. Police reported two people killed and four wounded.
   Police said the fighting broke out after Amal militiamen tried to
sell their weekly magazine in Ouzai, a Hezbollah stronghold.
   Syrian soldiers ``are trying to separate the combatants,'' said a
police spokesman, who cannot be named in line with standing rules.
   The two groups, vying for dominance of the 1.2 million Shiites
who make up Lebanon's largest single sect, battled for two days in
Moslem west Beirut early this week. Three people were killed and 11
wounded, by police count.
   In another development, a source at Aoun's headquarters said
Syrian intelligence agents captured 32 Christian civilians and 10 of
Aoun's soldiers in Moslem sectors of Lebanon on Thursday. The
source, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the soldiers were
released Friday.
   ``Efforts are under way to obtain the release of the civilians,''
he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
