<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-Bus 1stLd-Writethru a0604 07-07 0788</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Bus, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0604,0807</SECOND>
<HEAD>Emotional Funerals for Victims of Bus Attack</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with Palestinian seriously injured
in stoning; Pickup 4th pvs, ``In Jerusalem ...''; SUBS 14th graf, ``Sandori
said ...'' to provide first full reference to Sandori.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TLV1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angry Israeli mourners demanded vengeance and a
harsh crackdown on the Palestinian uprising at funerals Friday for
those killed when a bus was forced into a ravine by an Arab
assailant.
   Police used tear gas to break up a crowd of stone-throwing
Israelis in Jerusalem protesting the attack that killed 14 people
Thursday. At another rally in the capital, officers on horseback
dispersed about 200 people chanting ``Kill the Arabs!'' A policeman
was slightly injured in one clash.
   A Palestinian from the Gaza Strip was seriously injured in an
apparent revenge attack when his car was stoned as he passed a
Jewish settlement in southern Israel. Hospital officials said he was
unconscious and suffering brain damage.
   Israel radio reported at least three other stoning attacks on
Arab cars across the country. Arab sources said three Palestinians
were hurt in the attacks.
   In Jerusalem, militants chased Finance Minister Shimon Peres from
a funeral by shaking their fists, banging on his car and screaming,
``Go home, maniac!'' Peres heads the left-leaning Labor Party, which
calls for giving up occupied land in exchange for peace.
   At another funeral, Cabinet Minister Avner Shaki of the National
Religious Party, vowed to seek ``new stubborn, non-routine and harsh
ways to end this filthy Arab terrorism.''
   An Israeli judge, meanwhile, ordered an Arab man from the
occupied Gaza Strip held an additional 15 days on suspicion of
staging the attack on a bus on the Tel Aviv-Jerusalem highway. He
was injured in the crash and arrested immediately afterward.
   Two of those killed were Canadian tourists _ the first foreign
victims of the uprising _ and at least 10 were Israelis. Eight of
the 27 injured were Americans.
   It was the worst attack on Israelis during the 18-month uprising,
which has claimed the lives of 546 Arabs and 33 Israelis.
   The Moslem fundamentalist group Islamic Jihad claimed
responsibility for the attack in a communique issued in Amman,
Jordan.
   ``One of our mujaheddin (freedom fighters) carried out an
operation and there will be other operations .... All aggressive
Jews should quickly leave the holy land or they will confront their
fate,'' it said.
   Police would not release the suspect's name or give details of
the investigation.
   A senior police official identified the suspect as a 28-year-old
man from a refugee camp in Gaza and referred to the incident as a
``terrorist suicide attack for nationalist reasons.''
   Police were investigating whether the suspect acted on his own or
on orders from a guerrilla group, officials said, adding that a
second suspect also had been questioned in the case.
   Jerusalem police spokesman Uzi Sandori said both the driver and
passengers told police the suspect grabbed the steering wheel of the
bus, shouting in Arabic: ``God is great.''
   Israeli newspapers said the Palestinian told investigators he
acted in revenge against beatings of relatives by Israeli soldiers.
   The reports also said the suspect carefully planned the attack,
riding on the bus route several times to choose the deadliest
location.
   Three of the bus victims were buried Friday. Shaki, a minister
without portfolio, spoke at the burial of lawyer Mordechai
Rosenberg, 50, in Holon, near Tel Aviv.
   He said outside the cemetery that he would press for a crackdown
on the uprising and added: ``It is not possible that they will kill
us and spill our blood almost every week.''
   The most tumultuous funeral was that of Miriam Tzarafi, a
40-year-old secretary and mother of three. Several dozen mourners
descended on Peres, who was swiftly ushered by secret service guards
back to his car before the funeral began.
   Many of the 200 mourners at the Mount Shaul cemetery wept loudly.
Relatives poured cold water on her 17-year-old daughter, Orit, to
keep her from fainting, Two men propped up her husband, Aziz, as a
rabbi recited the Jewish burial prayer, or Kaddish, which is Hebrew
for sanctification.
   ``Mommy, you loved me. I want to see my mommy,'' screamed Mrs.
Tzarafi's 5-year-old son, Orit, who was kept away from the funeral.
   ``It's hard to part from you Miriam. I wish they had taken me
instead,'' said her elderly father-in-law, Zion Tzarafi, a retired
postal worker.
   Several mourners said after the funeral they hoped the government
would take harsher measures against Arabs.
   ``We have to make sure that no Arab is allowed to travel freely
in our country without special passes,'' said a cousin, Shmuel
Turkiya, 55.
</TEXT>
