<FIRST>r i AM-Colombia     07-07 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Say They Will Kill Norwegian Anthropologist</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas who kidnapped a
Norwegian anthropologist last year said Friday they will kill him
because he exploited Indians.
   The rebel communique, released to newspapers and radio stations
in the capital, said the decision to kill Bruce Olson was taken
after rebels talked with settlers, peasants and others living in the
Catatumbo area near the Venezuelan border.
   It did not say when he would be killed.
   Olsen, who has lived in Colombia for 29 years, had been working
with Indians in the Catatumbo area. He was kidnapped in October 1988
by the National Liberation Army, a group that has attacked foreign
companies, especially oil interests.
   The president of the National Organization of Indian Leaders,
Anatolio Quira, urged that Olson be released.
   Others appealing for Olson to be spared have been President
Virgilio Barco's adviser on Indian Affairs, Barco's chief adviser on
human rights and a priest who works with the Indians.
   Olson's mother gave a statement to the Bogota daily El Tiempo in
which she appealed to the guerrillas to release her son. El Tiempo
published the statement Friday. The letter indicated Mrs. Olson
lives somewhere in California.
   Olson carries a Norwegian passport. He also had U.S. citizenship,
but Olson renounced it last year, said a source with the Colombian
Foreign Ministry who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The National Liberation Army, headed by a former Catholic priest,
has bombed Colombia's biggest oil pipeline every month for more than
a year. The pipeline runs 500 miles thorough northeast Colombia.
   Anthropologists, linguists and missionaries working with
Colombian Indians have long encountered opposition to their work in
Colombia. In 1982, a guerrilla group known as M-19, kidnapped and
killed a missionary, Chester Bitterman III, of Lancaster, Pa.
   Bitterman, a linguist with the Institute of Summer Linguistics,
of Dallas, was accused by the guerrillas of being a CIA spy.
   Earlier this year a bomb went off in the institute's offices in
downtown Bogota.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
