<FIRST>r i AM-Vineyard-Storm     07-07 0218</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vineyard-Storm,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>Storm Ravages Chateau d'Yquem, Other High-Priced Vineyards</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BORDEAUX, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A violent storm that swept through
southwestern France caused extensive damage to grapevines that
produce some of the world's finest wines, vintners said Friday.
   The storm, which hit Thursday night, also was blamed for two
deaths. Two men in a small plane were killed when they crashed while
trying to land in Pau, 480 miles southwest of Paris.
   The storm knocked down power lines, flooding factories, and
shredding corn and tomato crops as well as the precious grapes of
the Sauternes region.
   Many Sauternes were damaged, and some devastated. At Chateau
d'Yquem, which produces a prized sweet white desert wine, proprietor
Alexandre Lur Saluces said half his 1989 production was wiped out.
   Normally, Chateau d'Yquem produces about 75,000 bottles of wine
from its 250 acres of vines in production. A bottle of 1983 Chateau
d'Yquem, considered a top vintage by connoisseurs, sells for $150 to
$225 in Paris.
   ``More than 50 percent of the 1989 harvest has been wiped out,
and I have to say a part of the 1990 harvest seems to be in
question,'' said Lur Saluces, whose family has owned Chateau d'Yquem
since 1786.
   Some other vineyards in the area lost up to 100 percent of their
grapes for this year.
</TEXT>
