<FIRST>r i AM-Caribbean-Summit     07-07 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Caribbean-Summit,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leaders Discuss Regional Integration For European Market in 1992</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANA HAYWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. GEORGE's, Grenada (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Caribbean leaders wound up a week of
talks Friday on how to integrate their economies and prepare the
region for 1992, when trade barriers go down in Europe.
   Members of the 13-nation Caribbean Community and Common Market,
or Caricom, said they took the first steps toward creating a
Caribbean Stock Exchange, a Caribbean Court of Appeals and an
emergency fund for disaster relief.
   They also plan to ask the United Nations for an international
conference on drugs and emphasize the need for a U.N. task force to
combat drug trafficking in the Caribbean, a key transit route to
U.S. and European markets.
   A statement on Caricom's position on drugs was expected after the
five-day conference was scheduled to end Friday night.
   Jamaica Prime Minister Michael Manley has urged the group to take
action before 1992, when Western Europe is to form a single trading
market that could affect trade protection the region currently
enjoys on many of its exports.
   Among the key exports that could be adversely affected are sugar,
bananas, rice and rum.
   Jamaica, along with Trinidad and Tobago, have the largest
economies of the Caricom states and their leadership is seen as
crucial to the success of the group.
   The meeting also included heads of government from
Antigua-Barbuda, the Bahamas, Barbados, Belize, Dominica, Grenada,
Guyana, Montserrat, St. Kitts-Nevis, St. Lucia and St. Vincent.
   Also on the agenda were economic and social problems confronting
the English-speaking region, including foreign debt, the environment
and regional politics.
   The group announced foreign ministers from the Bahamas, Jamaica,
St. Lucia and Trinidad and Tobago were to visit Haiti sometime this
year to pressure for elections.
   A statement said Caricom hoped the Haitian government led by Lt.
Gen. Prosper Avril would pursue democratic reform, including the
holding of national elections.
</TEXT>
