<FIRST>r i AM-Summit-US     07-07 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Summit-US,0523</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brady Says Summit Unlikely to Change Economic Direction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady said
Friday leaders of the major industrialized nations are unlikely to
shift economic direction at next week's summit in Paris.
   ``We should bear in mind the economies of the world are doing
very, very well,'' he told reporters in a satellite broadcast from
Washington.
   ``I don't think anybody's talking about changing the throttle
settings at this particular point in time,'' he said.
   President Bush and the leaders of Britain, Canada, France, Italy,
Japan and West Germany will make their annual examination of their
economies' health.
   Brady said officials probably will reiterate the statement issued
last spring by finance ministers saying an excessive rise or fall in
the value of the dollar would be counterproductive.
   He turned aside criticism that industrialized nations' spring
efforts to stem the sharp rise in the dollar against other major
currencies had been futile.
   ``I don't subscribe to the line of thought that says that either
policy coordination or intervention is a thing of the past,'' he
said.
   ``I would only point out that markets do have from time to time
volatile periods,'' he said. ``We had one this spring.''
   He noted the dollar's value had come down in recent weeks and
currency markets were quiet. ``I think the process is working very
well,'' he said.
   Central banks of leading industrialized nations mounted an
expensive campaign last spring to drive down the value of the
dollar. They intervened heavily in the currency markets by selling
dollars to try to change its value.
   Finance officials of the seven major industrial powers have
pledged to work together to keep the dollar stable.
   Brady said there was no need to make the nations' cooperation on
exchange rates more formal, as some European officials suggest.
   ``We don't see any reason to change things in any material way
and that would include a more rigid approach to exchange rates,'' he
said. ``We think the market is doing its job, and we would feel very
uneasy about tinkering with success.''
   He also said the Bush administration does not expect the U.S.
economy to slip into a recession but rather have a ``soft landing.''
   ``Our economy has been going forward on an upward plane for the
last seven years, so if that plane changes its slope a little bit
... then that is what we think is a soft landing _ growth at slower
rate,'' he said.
   There have been growing fears of recession in the United States.
   Analysts predicted the Federal Reserve likely will loosen its
credit policy further in an effort to drive down consumer and
business interest rates.
   The Federal Reserve in March 1988 began a credit-tightening drive
that lifted interest rates, a move designed to dampen inflationary
pressures by reducing demands for borrowing.
   But the central bank, in a major policy shift, last month lowered
a key interest rate, and analysts believe it shortly will reduce
that rate again.
</TEXT>
