<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Unrest,0356</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tass Reports New Ethnic Clashes in Nagorno-Karabakh</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of two ethnic groups fought gunbattles
Friday and tried to set buildings on fire in Nagorno-Karabakh, one
of the country's most volatile ethnic regions, the official Tass
news agency said.
   The news agency said Armenians and Azerbaijanis, who have been
feuding for 1{ years, shot at each other with hunting rifles in
Kirkijan, a suburb of Nagorno-Karabakh's principal city, Stepanakert.
   ``A real likelihood of massive clashes between the Armenian and
Azerbaijani populations was created,'' Tass said.
   The shooting lasted several hours and was accompanied by attempts
to set private and public buildings ablaze with signal rockets, Tass
said. The report said some people had fled the village and hid in a
forest.
   An Armenian and Azerbaijani were slightly wounded before police
and Interior Ministry forces ended the clash, Tass said.
   The dispatch also said hooligans were disrupting food supplies
and telephone and telegraph service and staging demonstrations and
sit-ins. Rumors are sweeping through Nagorno-Karabakh that attacks
on innocent residents are imminent, according to Tass.
   Since 1923, Nagorno-Karabakh has been part of the republic of
Azerbaijan, but Armenians, who make up three-quarters of the
region's 162,000 inhabitants, claim that Azerbaijanis discriminate
against them. They want the region to be annexed to the neighboring
republic of Armenia.
   The Kremlin has refused, and in January, authorities in Moscow
placed Nagorno-Karabakh under Kremlin management.
   Strikes and demonstrations flared in the region and in Armenia in
February 1988 and continued sporadically throughout the year. More
than 90 people were killed in the unrest.
   A general strike has been under way in the region since May 3,
and Tass reported Tuesday it has cost Nagorno-Karabakh $53.5 million
in wages.
   Tass said the latest disturbances appeared designed to disrupt a
visit to Nagorno-Karabakh by a commission of the national
parliament, the Congress of People's Deputies.
   The commission was formed last month to try to work out a
compromise between Armenians and Azerbaijanis. Armenians have
accused Soviet authorities of trying to increase the number of
Azerbaijans in the district.
