<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     07-07 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Afghan Rebels Say Government Troops Halted After Garrison Loss</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem guerrillas said they stalled a
government offensive Friday after losing a strategic garrison on the
outskirts of the eastern city of Jalalabad.
   The guerrillas blamed the loss of the Samarkhiel garrison
Thursday on a shortage of weapons and manpower.
   Abdul Kabir, a rebel spokesman, said Afghan government troops
plowed through guerrilla-held positions before being halted about
seven miles east of Jalalabad, in eastern Afghanistan.
   ``We couldn't hold on,'' said Azim Nasser-Zia, whose guerrillas
had held Samarkhiel. ``The mujahedeen didn't even have enough
weapons for their own defence.''
   Kabir agreed.
   ``We have a problem with this. We have only small weapons or ones
that are not in good working condition.''
   Nasser-Zia said the loss of Samarkhiel, which had been captured
by the U.S.-backed guerrillas early in March, was a crushing blow.
   ``The only victory since the Russian withdrawal, and we lose
it,'' he said.
   The Soviet army pulled the last of its troops from Afghanistan in
February, ending a nine-year military involvement in the civil war.
The guerrillas have been fighting 11 years to oust Afghanistan's
Marxist government.
   The insurgents, who call themselves mujahedeen, or Islamic holy
warriors, launched an attack on Jalalabad in early March. After a
month of some of the bloodiest fighting in 10 years of war, the
offensive ended in a stalemate.
   The battle for Jalalabad destroyed predictions that the Kabul
government would collapse soon after the Soviet troop withdrawal.
   Nasser-Zia also blamed the defeat on the interim guerrilla
government, saying it has drained many of the will to fight.
   The government was formed with the idea it would replace the
Afghanistan government, but it only has representatives from the
guerrilla parties based in Pakistan.
   It does not include representation for guerrillas based in Iran.
</TEXT>
