<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Hajj     07-07 0225</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Hajj,0232</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pilgrimage Leader Says Iranians Can Skip Hajj for 10 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the Iranian organization that
arranges pilgrimages to Mecca and Medina said Friday that Iranians
can skip the ritual for 10 years to protest Saudi control of the
shrines, Iranian media reported.
   ``We aren't afraid if they don't let us into Mecca to make the
pilgrimage to the house of God for another 10 years,'' Mahdi Emam
Jamarani, head of the Hajj organization, the official Islamic
Republic News Agency reported.
   Jamarani, in a sermon in Zahedan, capital of southeastern
Sistan-Baluchestan, said Iranians had been refused entry into Saudi
Arabia for two years already for the annual pilgrimage or hajj.
   Traveling once to the holy shrines at Mecca and Medina is one of
the five basic duties of all Moslems.
   The Saudi Interior Ministry said Iranians were welcome as long as
they did not try to politicize the proceedings. Saudi Arabia severed
ties with Tehran last year, citing its support for subversion.
   More than 400 pilgrims, most Iranians, died in 1987 when Saudi
troops quelled a riot in Mecca.
   Last year, Saudi Arabia imposed a quota of 1,000 pilgrims per 1
million population for all countries. The usual Iranian contingent
of 150,000 would have been cut to a third that, and the Iranians
stayed away in protest.
