<HEAD>Two Canadians Killed in Bus Crash, 8 Americans Injured</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Canadian women were among 14 people killed
when a Palestinian grabbed the wheel and forced a bus to plunge down
a 200-foot ravine, police said Friday.
   They identified the victims as Shelley Halpenny, a dentist in her
mid-30s from Vancouver, British Columbia, and Fern Rykiss, 17, of
Winnipeg, Manitoba.
   Dr. Halpenny's sister, Eve Silberman, 36, also of Vancouver, was
being treated at Jerusalem's Sharai Zedek Hospital for minor
injuries and a concussion suffered in the crash.
   The sisters were accompanying their father, Manley Wolocho, 60,
who is competing on the Canadian shooting team in the 13th Maccabiah
Games beginning this week, game officials said.
   Ms. Rykiss' trip was her first opportunity to see at firsthand
the Jewish homeland she had learned about during 12 years of Hebrew
schooling in Canada.
   The two women are the first foreigners to die since Palestinians
began their uprising against Israeli rule in the West Bank and Gaza
Strip 19 months ago.
   Police also released the names of 10 Israelis killed in the
crash. They said they have not identified two bodies.
   One of the Israeli victims was Fadian Reznick, 25, who recently
emigrated from Argentina to Givat Haim kibbutz in northern Israel.
   U.S. Consulate officials said eight American passport holders
were among the injured but refused to release their names, citing
the Privacy Act. They said no Americans were believed killed in the
crash.
   Hospital officials gave names of some American patients but did
not have details. They are:
   _Rita Levine, 39, in serious condition.
   _Eliezra Ben-Yehuda Cassuto, 53, of New York, in moderate
condition.
   _Paul Fingersh, 25, with minor injuries.
   _Victor Assal, 24, an Israeli soldier who came to Israel last
year from Bethesda, Maryland.
   Fingersh's mother, Pella, was treated for light injuries and
released.
