<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Poland     07-07 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Poland,0491</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Solidarity Official Opposes Debate on Return of Former German Land
^By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Solidarity official on Friday opposed
any suggestions Poland should give up land that was in German hands
before World War II.
   ``Those who question existing borders damage perspectives for
stability in Europe,'' said Bronislaw Geremek, leader of
Solidarity's deputies in the Polish parliament.
   He was responding to a suggestion by West German Finance Minister
Theodor Waigel that Germany should be reunified within its 1937
borders. That would include about a third of what is now Poland.
   Geremek spoke to reporters after talks with West German
Chancellor Helmut Kohl and Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher.
   The West German and Polish governments are trying to reach
agreement on a new financial aid package for Poland and on improved
conditions for Poland's ethnic German minority.
   The talks are stalled over conditions for financial assistance.
The impasse forced Kohl to call off a visit to Poland he had
tentatively planned this month.
   Geremek said he sees ``new chances for (closer) relations between
Germans and Poles,'' and that problems holding up the agreement
``are only of the second order.''
   Relations were cooled further by Waigel's comment on Sunday that
Germans still have a legal right to parts of Eastern Europe _
including large sections of Poland _ that once belonged to Germany.
   ``The German Empire did not cease with the capitulation of the
German army on May 8, 1945,'' Waigel said in Hanover.
   Poland's Communist Party reacted angrily to Waigel's remarks, and
his comments drew negative responses from Kohl and Genscher.
   Genscher said in a radio interview Friday that current frontier
agreements ``are accepted by everybody'' and ``leave no room for
discussion.''
   Kohl said on West German television Thursday night: ``No one in
Poland must fear that we Germans are revisionists.''
   In his talks with Geremek and other Solidarity leaders, Kohl said
he considers closer ties with Poland ``a special matter, in view of
the burden and tragedy of our common history,'' said the
chancellor's spokesman, Hans Klein.
   ``The chancellor said he considers the situation is ripe now for
a major step in creating friendly relations'' between the two
countries, Klein told reporters.
   Geremek said Solidarity agrees with the West German position that
any new financial credit for Poland must be linked to definite
projects, which was not the case with aid to Poland in the 1970s.
   He also said any new credit to Poland should be based on
successful economic reforms in his homeland.
   ``Poland does not want to be Europe's beggar,'' he said.
   ``We want to underscore that only a reformed economy is worthy of
asking for support. That would ensure not only that the credit would
be paid back'' but also that countries that invest in Poland can
make a profit, he said.
</TEXT>
