<FIRST>r w AM-OilBugs     07-07 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Bugs,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil-Eating Microorganisms May Munch on Alaskan Oil Spill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials of the Environmental Protection
Agency said Friday they are optimistic that oil-eating
microorganisms may soon become valuable tools in cleaning up the
Exxon oil spill in Alaska.
   EPA Administrator William Reilly said preliminary findings from
an experiment in which nutrients were used to enhance the growth of
such organisms on small sections of Alaska's contaminated beaches
appear to show success.
   In some cases, the number of organisms multiplied 100-fold only a
week into the experiment and even in the early stages some beaches
treated with nutrients showed ``a striking disappearance of the oil
from rock surfaces,'' the EPA said.
   Reilly said that the results were ``potentially good news'' and
that if the preliminary findings hold up Exxon Corp. may begin later
this summer to treat large sections of beach with nutrients to
enhance oil-eating microorganism growth.
   Eric Brathauer, assistant administrator for research and
development, said it will be several weeks before some remaining
questions about the experiment will be resolved.
   The EPA began using nutrients to enhance microrganism growth on
six test plots along Alaska's contaminated King Island beaches June
8 in hopes the growth would spur oil degredation. Some degredation
has been observed in untreated areas, but in many cases there are
too few microorganisms to make a significant impact.
   But Brathauer said the nutrients acted as a fertilizer and
brought about significant increases in levels of oil-eating
organisms in the test areas. He said so far there have been no signs
of any side effects detrimental to the environment.
   In addition to the rapid growth of the microorganisms in the test
areas, there has been a noticeable cleaning of rock surfaces that
had not been anticipated so early, said Richard Valentinetti, an EPA
official involved in the project.
   Rock surfaces on which the nutrients were applied became much
cleaner shortly after contact similar to soap releasing dirt from an
object. But the officials warned that the cleaning may have been a
physical reaction and not biological.
   Valentinetti said in an interview that the agency hopes to learn
more about the cleansing action within the next few weeks and
determine whether it was a biological reaction. He said it remains
uncertain whether the oil that came off the rocks actually degraded
or was simply transported.
   The EPA estimates that anywhere from 700 miles to 1,200 miles of
Alaskan coastline _ much of it shear rock and boulders _ have been
contaminated by the March 24 Exxon Valdez spill in Prince William
Sound.
   Valentinetti said use of the oil-eating microorganisms is
expected to be most productive along about 100 miles of shoreline
where there is sand and sediment.
   He said Exxon has estimated it would cost about $5 million to
treat 50 miles of beach with the nutrient fertilizer to enhance
microorganism growth. Most areas likely would require more than one
treatment, officials suggested.
   That cost would be only a small portion of the overall cleanup
costs facing Exxon.
</TEXT>
