<FIRST>r i AM-NATO-SovietCrash     07-07 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NATO-Soviet Crash,0473</SECOND>
<HEAD>NATO Boss Says Tracking of Pilotless Mig-23 Shows System Works</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NATO's supreme commander in Europe, Gen. John
Galvin, said Friday that Western tracking of the pilotless MiG-23
that zoomed across West Europe undetected by Soviet radar proved the
allied alert system works.
   On another issue, Galvin reacted coolly to Soviet President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev's offer in Strasbourg, France, Thursday to make
another unilateral cut in short-range nuclear missiles.
   ``The main thing threatening us is overwhelming (Soviet)
conventional forces,'' Galvin told a meeting of American reporters.
   ``I question whether or not we are in a safer world in Europe
today than we were, say, 10 years ago.''
   On the runaway plane, Galvin said two U.S. F-15 fighters
scrambled from a NATO base in The Netherlands ``as a policing
action'' as it crossed into West Europe Tuesday. They shadowed it,
hoping it would reach the North Sea, but it crashed in Belgium,
killing a man.
   Galvin said he accepted Moscow's explanation that it was an
accident.
   The pilot ejected over Poland after reporting the plane was
smoking. The Soviets say their radar missed the MiG-23 as it flew on
for 500 miles.
   The incident recalled the failure of Soviet air defenses to
detect a small plane flown by German amateur pilot Mathias Rust, who
landed in Red Square.
   ``Mathias Rust is one thing _ a little tiny plane flying at low
altitudes.'' said Galvin. ``But this plane took off from their own
airfield and was flying at high altitude.''
   A Soviet officer, Lt. Col. Anatoly S. Balikin, said in Moscow it
was not practical or economical to monitor every plane.
   Galvin said U.S. pilots did not shoot down the MiG-23 or move
alongside and tip it over because it was over populated areas.
   Regarding Gorbachev's offer, he said that although the Soviets
had 1,400 short-range missiles launchers compared with North
Atlantic Treaty Organization's 88, Moscow's conventional superiority
was a bigger threat.
   ``If we get into the shorter-range nuclear forces too early we're
giving away the major motivating idea because the Soviets do want to
see us get rid of nuclear weapons,'' said Galvin. ``They are not so
anxious to get rid of conventional weapons.''
   Last month Gorbachev told U.S. Secretary of State James A. Baker
III he will withdraw 500 short-range missiles unilaterally. They
have a range of up to 310 miles.
   Galvin said that despite the appeal of glasnost, or openness, he
questioned whether Europe was safer because of the risk of Soviet
instability.
   ``I applaud the way the Soviet Union is moving,'' said Galvin.
``But it's a rocky road they're heading down. They're saying they
can't turn back but they don't know precisely where they're going.''
</TEXT>
