<FIRST>r i AM-Vatican-Abortion     07-07 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vatican-Abortion,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vatican Doctrine Guardian Praises U.S. Court Decision</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Vatican's chief guardian of doctrine
Friday praised last week's U.S. Supreme Court ruling that allows
states to restrict abortion.
   ``The decision is a sign of the birth of a new moral
consciousness on abortion,'' Roman Catholic Cardinal Joseph
Ratzinger said at a news conference at Madrid University.
   ``It is a kind of move away from earlier attitudes, where I see a
reflection that weighs more on the side of the value of human
life,'' said the prefect of the Congregation for the Doctrine of the
Faith, which makes sure that church officials adhere to Catholic
doctrine.
   Ratzinger made the comments after delivering a lecture titled
``Jesus Christ Today'' at a university seminar.
   In its decision issued on July 3, the U.S. Supreme Court voted
5-4 to give the states broad powers to restrict the availability of
abortions. The ruling narrowed the court's 1973 decision legalizing
abortion.
   On another topic, Ratzinger denied a recent Brazilian newspaper
report that the church had decided to order new sanctions against
the Rev. Leonard Boff of Brazil, a leading proponent of liberation
theology.
   In 1985, the Vatican sentenced Boff to nearly a year of
``obedient silence'' because of books he wrote that criticized the
Roman Catholic Church for not doing enough to aid the poor in the
Third World.
   Liberation theology stresses social activism by Catholics on
behalf of the oppressed. Pope John Paul II has objected to forms of
liberation theology that embrace Marxist theory.
   Ratzinger said the pope believes the theology to be ``useful and
necessary at times.'' ``But other aspects that present deviations
motivated by politics are not very correct,'' he said.
   Ratzinger also denied that the Vatican had been more severe with
liberal theologians than with ultra-conservative church figures such
as French Archbishop Marcel Lefebvre, who was excommunicated for
challenging the pope's authority.
</TEXT>
