<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-CallingHome     07-07 0172</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Calling Home,170</SECOND>
<HEAD>AT&amp;T to Help Reporters Call Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reporters covering President Bush's trip to
Europe next week won't have to master strange telephone systems when
they call home.
   American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. will set up 120 telephone
lines to allow reporters to speak directly with an AT&amp;T operator in
the United States.
   There will be 50 lines in the media filing center set up by the
White House at each stop on Bush's trip, with the remainder in
broadcast network production rooms.
   Company spokesman Herb Linnen said reporters will need AT&amp;T
credit cards.
   The system, AT&amp;T said, will relieve the host countries of
augmenting their telephone systems to accommodate the 240 reporters
expected to accompany Bush on the July 9-18 trip to Poland, Hungary,
France and the Netherlands.
   AT&amp;T will utilize a temporary satellite link for the
direct-access service in Poland and Hungary. In France and the
Netherlands, AT&amp;T will plug into its existing system that gives
callers access to U.S. operators on a regular basis.
