<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-89 1712EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Aviation-Security     07-07 0511</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Aviation-Security,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>FAA Toughens Policy On Security Bulletins</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government announced a stricter policy
Friday to deal with threats against aviation, including a system
that requires airlines to take countermeasures and imposes fines for
disclosing security alerts.
   A Federal Aviation Administration order, which will go into
effect Monday, replaces the system of issuing security bulletins,
which was criticized after the bombing of Pan Am Flight 103 over
Scotland last December that killed 270 people. Notices of threats
against U.S. airlines on the flight's route were posted in at least
one foreign embassy but not distributed to the general public.
   Under the new order, individuals or airlines that disclose
information from government security alerts without FAA authorizaton
will be fined _ up to $1,000 for individuals and $10,000 for
airlines.
   FAA spokesman John Leyden said the system for alerting airlines
will now include two types of adivsories: information circulars and
security directives.
   The information circulars will deal with general threats of
hijackings, bombings or other terrorist actions, Leyden said. ``They
are basically a heads-up warning and would require no particular
action,'' he said.
   The security directives, however, would require countermeasures
by an airline, such as additional baggage inspections, Leyden said.
These would be in response to specific threats against an airline,
an airport or an individual flight and might include such
information as the threatened time and method of attack, he said.
   Previously, airlines were not required to take any specific
actions in response to security bulletins.
   The FAA, in a news release on the new order, said airlines have
been responsive to actions suggested in security bulletins but
making compliance mandatory will strengthen security.
   Since 1986, the FAA has issued 93 security bulletings, about
one-third of them warning of specific threats.
   In the case of Flight 103, an FAA advisory had been issued about
the threat of a bomb aboard a U.S. airline flight from Frankfurt,
Germany, to the United States. The Pan Am flight originated in
Frankfurt with a different plane, but U.S. and European authorities
said they concluded that the threat was not related to the bombing
of Flight 103.
   Other warnings were issued about the possibility of plastic
explosives concealed in a radio-cassette player. Investigators said
that such a bomb caused the Pan Am explosion, although they have not
found who planted the device.
   Relatives of Americans killed in the Pan Am bombing have called
for public advisories whenever there is a threat against aviation,
saying passengers have a right to know when they are boarding an
aircraft that has been threatened.
   Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner has rejected the
suggestion, saying it would disrupt aviation and compromise
intelligence gathering.
   On Thursday, the FAA announced new rules requiring airlines to
install units that can detect plastic explosives in checked luggage
at 40 U.S. and foreign airports. It did not list the airports,
except for John F. Kennedy in New York and Gatwick in London, and
said it would take two or three years before all the units are
installed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
