<FIRST>r a AM-Food-Jail     07-07 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Food-Jail,0240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Gets Jail For Serving Food To Poor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA CRUZ, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman will spend 45 days in jail for
serving food to the city's street people.
   Sandra Loranger, 49, of Santa Cruz who was charged with not
having a permit to provide the food, was given the jail term
Thursday by Municipal Court Judge Robert Atack.
   Loranger, standing outside the courtroom, promised to keep
feeding hungry people in Santa Cruz, a popular coastal city about 70
miles south of San Francisco.
   ``I fully intend to keep on doing it,'' said Loranger, who does
not have to begin her jail term until next week. She added she would
stop her activities ``only if unconditional food is made available
(to the poor) on a daily basis ... but not until.''
   She was sent to jail because she refused to accept probation,
under which she would be required to ``obey all laws.''
   Loranger, a partner in an antique store, is the first of the
activists working for the city's homeless population to receive a
jail term for handing out food.
   She was cited Feb. 21 during one of the meals the activists
served at the Town Clock in downtown Santa Cruz.
   The city began requiring the permits earlier this year because
too many homeless persons were gathering in a busy section of town
where the activists were serving them meals.
</TEXT>
