<FIRST>r i AM-Peru     07-07 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>6 Police, 7 Rebels Killed in Ambush; Explosions in Lima</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guerrillas ambushed a police patrol and started
a gun battle in which seven rebels, six policemen and a civilian
were killed, the government said Friday.
   In Lima, guerrillas planted eight bombs at banks and private
companies, four of which exploded, police reported.
   An Interior Ministry statement said members of Shining Path, a
Maoist guerrilla group, ambushed the patrol Thursday in the Puno
region, 600 miles southeast of the capital near Lake Titicaca.
   The report said one policeman was wounded in the half-hour
battle, which ended when police reinforcements arrived. The civilian
killed had been hitching a ride on the police vehicle when it was
attacked, police said.
   Guerrillas of the pro-Cuban Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement
were responsible for the bombs in Lima, the police said.
   Four of bombs went off simultaneously at about 10:30 p.m.
Thursday at offices of the Peru Construction Council and the Grana y
Montero construction company, a tile factory and an auto parts
store. Bomb squads defused the others, which were planted near
downtown banks.
   Construction workers went on strike Monday for higher wages, and
their union held violent demostrations Wednesday and Thursday in
downtown Lima.
   Four members of the construction union were wounded and one was
killed Thursday in a confrontation with police after a march. A
policeman was wounded when a stick of dynamite was thrown from a
crowd of workers.
   Police did not comment on whether the explosions were related to
the strike.
   Shining Path began fighting nine years ago in the Andes and its
insurgency has spread to other areas. The Tupac Amaru group made its
appearance in 1984, and generally carries out bombings in cities.
   More than 15,000 people have been killed since the guerrilla war
began, according to government figures.
</TEXT>
