<FIRST>r i AM-MichelinMap     07-07 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Michelin Map,0358</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wiesenthal Center Protests Map That Omits Israel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Paris branch of the Simon Wiesenthal Center has
complained to Michelin about its map of northeast Africa that gives
Egypt and Jordan a common border and omits Israel.
   ``What we have here, at best, is discrimination in order to
satisfy the Arab market and at worst a position taken that would
seem to endorse the most extreme demands of those who would like to
eliminate Israel,'' said Shimon Samuels, European director of the
Wiesenthal Center.
   The Los Angeles-based center is an international organization
whose goal is combating prejudice..
   On June 14, Samuels sent a letter to Michelin President Francois
Michelin asking that the map be withdrawn and reprinted.
   ``At the very best we think this map is a blight on the
reputation for geograhical accuracy of Michelin guides and maps,''
he said in a telephone interview from London.
   The front cover of the map of ``Africa North East Arabia''
displays a small section of the full map. The cutout omits Israel
and shows instead a dotted line frontier running between Egypt and
Jordan, which occupied the West Bank from 1948 to 1967.
   The full map avoids the issue by placing in the area where Israel
would be located a small inserted map of the entire African
continent with the phone number for the Michelin company.
   A spokesman at Michelin's office here said the letter was
received two days ago by the department responsible for cartography,
which intended to respond.
   The spokesman, who spoke anonymously in keeping with company
policy, said the response ``will be private and not given in the
press.''
   He said the map of Arabia had been drafted and in print since
1967.
   Earlier this year, the Weisenthal Center's Paris office
complained to Air France after the national airline published a
Middle East tourist brochure with a map that omitted Israel. The
brochure listed hotels in the Middle East, but contained no listings
in Israeli cities.
   Samuels said his office was talking to the airline about
withdrawing or re-editing the brochure.
</TEXT>
