<FIRST>r w AM-Medicare-MedicaidJob     07-07 0289</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Medicare-Medicaid Job,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nominee for HHS Post Withdraws</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration is looking again for
someone to head the Health and Human Services Department agency that
handles the Medicare and Medicaid programs.
   Drew Altman, human services commissioner in New Jersey and the
second candidate who has been under serious consideration for
nomination to head the Health Care Financing Administration,
withdrew his name Friday.
   Altman, who is taking a job in the private sector, said his chief
reason for pulling out was the length of time it takes to move
through the personnel pipeline in Washington.
   However, sources in Washington and New Jersey who spoke on the
condition of anonymity said Altman's candidacy had run into trouble
at the White House over questions about his politics and an
unbudgeted $21 million spending spree by one of his New Jersey
division heads.
   Altman, 38, is a registered independent and did not participate
in the Republican president's New Jersey campaign last fall.
   In April, Sheila Burke, chief of staff to Senate Minority Leader
Bob Dole, R-Kan., withdrew from contention for the HHS job because
her husband is a vice president of the Aetna insurance group. Aetna
is one of several insurance companies under contract to the HHS
agency to handle Medicare claims. At the time, sources said an
arrangement could not be worked out to avoid potential conflicts of
interest.
   Altman's withdrawal appeared to mark the second time one of HHS
Secretary Louis Sullivan's candidates for a top job at the
department has withdrawn after running into opposition at the White
House.
   Earlier, Robert Fulton, Oklahoma social services secretary,
withdrew from consideration for nomination to head the department's
welfare agency in the face of criticism from right-to-life activists.
</TEXT>
