<FIRST>r a AM-MiamiRiots     07-07 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Miami Riots,0403</SECOND>
<HEAD>Citizen Panel Calling for New Police Hiring Policies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A community panel reviewing police activities
following January's riots has called for an overhaul of police
hiring practices and a permanent board to investigate citizen
complaints against officers.
   The Overtown Independent Review Panel also recommended Thursday
increasing the number of black officers in Miami from 18 percent to
21 percent and expanding the hours of a police substation in the
city's Overtown section, the center of the three-day riot that left
one dead.
   Blacks comprise about 21 percent of Dade County's 1.85 million
residents, the bulk of whom live in Miami. Hispanics make up 46
percent of the county's population and whites, 33 percent.
   City Manager Cesar Odio said he ``agreed with the general tone of
the report'' to be discussed by city commissioners next week. But
Police Chief Perry Anderson criticized most of the panel's
suggestions as unnecessary.
   He said internal police investigators do an adequate job
following up citizens' complaints and the 24-hour operation of the
substation is not needed even though the police shooting that
triggered the riots occurred across the street from the station when
it was closed.
   Three nights of looting and arson in Miami's black neighborhoods
were triggered by the fatal shooting of a black motorcyclist by a
Hispanic police officer Jan. 16.
   ``The whole incident was spontaneous,'' said Anderson. ``The
results would have been exactly the same if the mini-station was
open.''
   Anderson also defended the equality of the department's hiring
practices.
   ``What we need to do is generate enough black recruits to go
through the system,'' he said.
   The panel found that between 1974 and March 1989, 46 percent of
the black candidates failed to complete the five-month program at
the Southeast Florida Institute of Criminal Justice in Miami.
   The panel claims 37 percent of Hispanic candidates and 17 percent
of Anglos dropped from the program during the same period.
   Jim Stinchcomb, director of the institute, says the current
attrition rate is only 3 percent to 4 percent for all applicants and
the panel's figures may reflect some problems during the 1970s.
   Stinchcomb said dropout rates declined after the institute
revamped its firing range test and some academic exams in 1981.
   ``The numbers the panel is throwing out is no reflection on the
current situation,'' he said.
</TEXT>
