<FIRST>r w AM-NASAResignation     07-07 0194</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NASA Resignation,190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Director of NASA's Ames Research Center Resigns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William F. Ballhaus Jr., director of NASA's
Ames Research Center in Mountain View, Calif., announced his
resignation Friday, citing low pay and regulations about employment
after government service.
   ``My family situation is such that public service in the current
environment is no longer a viable option for me,'' Ballhaus said in
a statement released by the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration.
   NASA said Ballhaus cited ``inadequate compensation for senior
federal executives and vague new post-government employment
regulations'' as reasons for leaving.
   Ballhaus was director of Ames, one of NASA's major research
centers, from 1984 to 1988, and was named to the job again in
February. His resignation is effective July 15.
   Ballhaus is responsible for management of facilities at Mountain
View and the Dryden Flight Research Center at Edwards Air Force
Base, Calif., where more than 5,000 NASA employees conduct research
in aeronautics, life science, space science and space technology.
   Ballhaus has spent 18 years as a NASA engineer and manager, all
at Ames. He recently completed a one-year term as president of the
American Institute of Aeronautics and Astronautics.
