<SECOND>AM-Haiti,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gunmen Attack Home of Prominent Politician</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ A prominent politician said Friday
that gunmen fired on his home in an attack that came one day after
gunmen burglarized the home of another politician and killed his
brother.
   Jean-Claude Roy, head of the small centrist Union of Haitian
Constitutionalists party, said that at midnight Thursday three or
four gunmen began shooting at his house from his driveway in
suburban Freres, east of Port-au-Prince. He said he and his three
private security guards shot in the air and scared them away.
   On Thursday, Dr. Turneb Delpe, a critic of Haiti's military
government, said two gunmen burst into his Port-au-Prince home and
shot to death his younger brother Gregory.
   Delpe, head of the small leftist National Progressive Democratic
Party, said the gunmen stole $4,000.
   Haiti's ruler, Lt. Gen. Prosper Avril, has linked a foiled coup
attempt in April and a crime wave since then to die-hard supporters
of former dictator Jean-Claude Duvalier, who has been in exile in
France since 1986.
   Avril has said that Duvalier's supporters are trying to
destabilize his policy of ``irreversible transition to democracy.''
   ``Avril has claimed that he has things under control. His
enemies' clear message is that it just isn't so,'' Roy said.
   Serge Gilles, leader of the socialist National Progressive
Revolutionary Party, said: ``First Delpe, now Roy. These crimes are
not being committed for money. They are politically inspired.
   ``There is a group of people here who just does not want things
to change,'' Gilles said.
</TEXT>
