<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-89 1754EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-B-2Test     07-07 0457</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-B-2 Test,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pentagon Announces B-2 Flight Test For Next Week</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon announced on Friday that the
long-awaited first flight tests for the B-2 stealth bomber will be
held during a 15-day period beginning Sunday.
   The controversial plane, which is the most radical and expensive
bomber ever built, has become the target of budget cutters on
Capitol Hill.
   Critics in Congress have expressed opposition to footing the bill
for planes that could cost anyhwere between $500 million and $750
million a copy before the first plane has ever gotten off the ground.
   The plane, described as resembling a ``flying wing'' without
conventional fuselage, is designed to penetrate Soviet borders
without being detected by radar.
   The plane has no sharp angles and relies on the use of
radar-absorbing coatings on its surface.
   In total, the program is expected to cost taxpayers some $70
billion. To date, the Air Force has invested $22 billion into the
program.
   In a statement issued late Friday afternoon, the Pentagon said
that the plane is scheduled for ``outdoor tests and the first
flight'' during a 15-day period beginning July 9.
   The plane has been undergoing a final check at an Air Force plant
in Palmdale, Calif. The plane has been built and manufactured by
Northrop Corp.
   During the 15-day period, the plane is expected to be rolled out
of its hangar and undergo a series of dress rehearsal tests that
include turning on its engines, slow and high-speed taxi tests on
the runway and then, a full flight test.
   For its initial flight, the Air Force plans to take the plane
from Palmdale for an approximately 2{ hour test flight, landing at
Edwards Air Force Base, about 40 miles away, said Capt. Tess Taft,
an Air Force spokeswoman at Palmdale.
   The tests may take several days, but there can be no exact date
given for the test flight, Capt. Taft said.
   ``Only after it looks perfect, and everything looks right, will
they take it up. And you never know what day that will be,'' she
said.
   While the news media will be allowed to observe the outdoor
tests, the public ``is not invited,'' the statement issue at the
Pentagon said.
   The specific date and time of the tests will not be announced in
advance, but the media will be informed by midmorning if no tests
are scheduled for a particular day, the statement said.
   The Air Force will hold a news conference following the first
flight, the statement said.
   While the B-2 has not been operationally tested in the field yet,
individual systems were tried out along the way. The Air Force says
the B-2 will not be deployed before 1991.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
