<FIRST>u w AM-Hispanics 1stLd-Writethru a0639 07-07 0748</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hispanics, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0639,710</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democratic Leader, Labor Secretary Dole Address Hispanic Group</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS 10th graf, Brown also, Bush not cutting Head Start</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democrats' national chairman on Friday
accused the Republicans of merely paying lip service to Hispanics
and pledged grass-roots efforts to give Spanish-speaking Americans
more political clout.
   ``We Democrats know that empowerment begins not with political
tokenism at the top, but with a commitment at the local level,''
Ronald H. Brown told the annual convention of the National League of
United Latin American Citizens.
   Labor Secretary Elizabeth Dole spoke to the group later,
emphasizing a pending jobs bill rather than politics.
   Mrs. Dole said her No. 1 priority is to reduce minority youth
unemployment and she asked the group's support for a Bush
administration bill that would refocus the government's job-training
program.
   She said minority youth unemployment is a staggering 32.4
percent, while the jobless rate for young Hispanics averages 22
percent. The nation's overall unemployment rate is 5.3 percent.
   Mrs. Dole said Hispanic employment at the Transportation
Department rose by 25 percent while she was secretary during the
Reagan administration, and ``I intend to get the same results at the
Department of Labor.''
   Brown told the group earlier, ``You'll hear about President Bush
appointing Lauro Cavazos secretary of education,'' he said. ``You
won't hear about the cuts in Secretary Cavazos' budget or about
Republican support for `English only' education.''
   He said the Democrats are ``committed, absolutely committed to
bilingual education and committed to defeating `English only'
amendments no matter what state they appear in.''
   Brown also said Bush ``just said no'' when the
Democratic-controlled House requested $81 million in additional
funding this year for combating drugs. Brown took particular aim at
Bush's budget proposal for Head Start, saying ``more than three out
of four needy kids still won't get help.''
   ``Thousands of children in East L.A. are on the slow track before
they get to Mr. Escalante's classroom,'' he said, referring to Jaime
Escalante, the dynamic teacher who inspired the movie ``Stand and
Deliver'' and has become a hero of the administration.
   Brown addressed the scandal in the Department of Housing and
Urban Development as well, saying, ``When people in `colonias'
(shanty towns) go without running water and plumbing while (former
Interior Secretary) James Watt makes $300,000 for a few hours work
as a housing consultant, something is out of kilter.''
   In his speech and in remarks afterward, Brown repeatedly
criticized the Republicans as masters of a Madison Avenue approach
to politics, while he said the Democrats are still close to the
people.
   But he also acknowledged the GOP has made inroads with Hispanic
voters, especially in Florida and California.
   Addressing the fundamentals of building party strength, Brown
said after the speech, ``there is nothing more crucial than the 1990
census'' for the Democratic Party and its efforts to reach
minorities. Census data are used to draw congressional districts.
   Census officials say they could have missed as many as 3.5
million blacks and Hispanics in the 1980 census, while ``we think
it's about twice that amount,'' he said. He said the party will
``make sure the Census Bureau knows they are watched.''
   Brown also said the party needs to do more to register Hispanic
voters, and he acknowledged that Republicans have done a better job
of winning the allegiance of resident aliens in California by
courting them in the years before they become citizens.
   About 60 percent of eligible Hispanics have not registered to
vote, he said. The Census Bureau estimated the Hispanic population
at 17.5 million in 1985.
   Mrs. Dole, talking about jobs for minorities, said she and Bush
crafted legislation that redirects the Job Training Partnership Act
from merely a ``training for a job'' program to one that will
provide skills training, literacy and remedial education and
counseling.
   ``Each individual in the program will be assessed for his or her
particular needs, and goals will be set to meet those needs _ in
short, a total support system will be available. Funding will depend
not on how many kids are trained and pushed into jobs slots _ but on
achievement and longer term evaluation. There will be follow-up
after six months on the job, and a year later, to determine
progress.''
   Mrs. Dole urged members of the group, billed as the largest and
oldest Hispanic organization in the United States, to attend a
Senate subcommittee markup of the bill next Wednesday.
</TEXT>
