<FIRST>r w AM-VADoctors 1stLd-Writethru a0649 07-07 0608</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-VA Doctors, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0649,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Credentials of VA Physicians Not Being Checked</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Inserts 6 grafs after 4th graf pvs, The VA, with statement from
Vietnam Vets group, comment from VA; inserts 1 graf after 6th graf pvs,
The full, with background on earlier legislation.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Veterans officials were unable to prove they
had checked the licenses of more than half the doctors they hired
from 1986 to 1988, according to a published report Friday.
   According to a draft of a General Accounting Office study
obtained by The Washington Post, officials in the Department of
Veterans Affairs have failed to verify credentials for doctors and
medical residents at the nation's 172 VA hospitals.
   ``By not following applicable procedures, VA medical centers
could unknowingly hire `problem' physicians and-or be allowing
physicians with sanctions against their licenses to treat
veterans,'' the Post quoted the report as saying.
   The VA, declining direct comment on the report, issued a
statement Friday saying:
   ``Secretary (Edward J.) Derwinski views GAO studies as an
effective, independent management guide aiming for better quality
care for veterans. GAO is concurrently conducting major management
studies at VA at Derwinski's request. VA and Congress are partners
in seeking and delivering quality care for vets.''
   The Vietnam Veterans of America said the GAO report and an
earlier report on mortality rates at VA hospitals show that veterans
with service-connected disabilities should be allowed to seek health
care from the provider of their choice.
   ``If the government is unable to provide acceptable health care
through the veterans hospital system, then these veterans should
have the right to seek medical treatment elsewhere,'' said Mary R.
Stout, president of the 35,000-member group.
   VA spokeswoman Donna St. John said the group is making a false
comparison.
   ``Any attempt to connect the mortality review or the GAO report
with the quality of care is totally inappropriate,'' she said,
explaining that mortality rates fail to reflect the condition of the
patients who enter a particular hospital. Hospices, for example,
have reported 100 percent rates.
   She noted that the GAO report, according to the Post, said: ``The
conditions cited do not mean that the medical services provided by
the VA are substandard or that VA physicians are incompetent.''
   The GAO study was requested two years ago by Sen. Frank
Murkowski, R-Alaska, ranking minority member of the Senate Veterans'
Affairs Committee. His staff said it could not release a copy of the
report because it was in draft form. The VA said it could not
release the draft report, either.
   The full report, with VA comment, is due for release in August.
   Murkowski wrote a 1985 law telling the VA to act on those
problems after the American Medical Association found 87 doctors
were working for the agency even though their licenses had been
revoked, suspended or restricted.
   VA officials said they could prove they had checked the licenses
of only 105 of the 207 physicians hired from 1986 to 1988, the
report said. The report also said the VA had not fulfilled promises
to ensure that its doctors are qualified to practice their
particular specialties.
   A further problem was detected with medical residents who work at
VA hospitals, according to the draft report.
   The government watchdog agency said a records check with the FBI
found that 165 of the 16,756 residents had been charged with
criminal offenses between the early 1970s and May 1987, the Post
reported.
   Among the more serious offenses were 68 charged with drunken
driving and 67 charged with drug violations, five with vandalism and
five with burglary. The records did not indicate how many charges
led to convictions.
</TEXT>
