<DOCNO> AP890707-0158 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-89 1755EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-PaymentProbe     07-07 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Payment Probe,0468</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chicken Giant Gives Out $10,000 Checks to Lawmakers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL HOLMES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>and</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>SCOTT ROTHSCHILD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writers</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A millionaire who handed out $10,000 checks
on the Senate floor while legislation that interested him was
pending said the checks were political contributions, not an attempt
to bribe lawmakers.
   ``It would be difficult to make it into a bribery case,'' said
Travis County District Attorney Ronnie Earle, who believes it's time
to change Texas' loose campaign finance laws. ``In Texas, it's
almost impossible to bribe a public official as long as you report
it.''
   The $10,000 personal checks, with the payee's name left blank,
were offered by Lonnie ``Bo'' Pilgrim, an East Texas chicken
processor, to nine of the 31 senators two days before Friday's vote
on a House workers' compensation bill.
   Business interests have favored the House plan, but senators
rejected it.
   Pilgrim said he was concerned about the high cost of workers'
compensation in Texas and that he would like a law that would be a
``win-win situation for all of us.''
   ``The common practice of mine is to give large contributions to
people _ preachers, educational institutions and politicians _ and
$10,000 or $100,000 is a common practice with me,'' Pilgrim said.
   ``It's primarily just for the name identification with the
politicians ... They will answer your calls and give you an
appointment and listen to you describe an issue. It does not infer a
bribe,'' Pilgrim said.
   Most lawmakers said they returned the checks _ or planned to. But
Sen. O.H. ``Ike'' Harris said he saw nothing wrong with accepting
the money.
   Blank payee lines like those on Pilgrim's checks are common _
because many people don't know the formal name of a politician's
campaign committee, Harris said.
   ``I've received campaign contributions that size before. If the
principle's wrong, it don't matter if it's a dollar or a million,
right? Everybody's got a different style,'' Harris said.
   Texas law does not limit campaign contributions, although
officeholders are barred from raising money during regular
legislative sessions. There is no such prohibition on special
sessions, and the Texas Senate has been in special session for three
weeks.
   ``I think it's outrageous. It offends the integrity of the whole
process,'' said Earle.
   ``It looks horrible,'' said Sen. Kent Caperton.
   ``When I first heard it, I thought they were joking. It's just so
outrageous. The law needs to be changed,'' said Caperton. ``We need
more limits about when we can take money and how much.''
   Rep. David Hudson said he was introducing a bill to prohibit
campaign contributions on the Capitol grounds.
   ``Such overt attempts to influence the way laws are made should
be stopped,'' Hudson said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
