<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     07-07 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Rake Northeast; West Bakes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A storm lashed the East with powerful wind and occassionally
heavy rain on Friday, toppling trees and power lines and unleashing
thunderstorms from New York to Maine.
   Much of the desert Southwest had readings between 100 and 109
degrees. Denver hit a record 100 degrees in the fourth consecutive
day of temperatures above 100 degrees.
   Strong wind pushed a utility pole onto a car with four people
inside at East Rodman, N.Y., and knocked over trees and utility
lines in Port Byron, Otisco and Onondaga, N.Y. One-inch diameter
hail fell at North Tonawanda.
   Flooding was reported near Roanoke, Va., Mount Savage, Md., and
in parts of Delaware.
   Other strong thunderstorms developed over western portions of the
Carolinas, central Texas, Tennessee and the lower Mississippi Valley
into Florida. Strong wind near Conway, Ark., destroyed several
mobile homes, including one that was blown onto a nearby highway.
   Thunderstorms were also scattered over southwestern North Dakota,
where small hail was reported.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDT
included .57 inches at Lake Charles, La.; .53 inches at Waco, Texas;
.46 inches at McComb, Miss., and .13 inches at Sioux City, Iowa.
   Temperatures began warming up across much of the nation. A large,
stagnant upper level high-pressure system was centered over Colorado
and contributed to the hot weather.
   Afternoon readings were in the 90s from the lower Ohio Valley
across the middle Mississippi Valley, the central and southern
Plains, the central and southern Rockies to interior California.
Temperatures in the 90s also were common from Florida to along
portions of the Atlantic Coast.
   It was the seventh day of 100-plus temperatures at Scottsbluff,
Neb., breaking the record of six days set in July 1936.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 56
degrees at Arcata, Calif., to 109 degrees at Needles, Calif.
   The low in the nation Friday morning was 38 degrees at Truckee,
Calif.
   Saturday's forecast called for scattered showers and
thunderstorms from eastern Texas across the Gulf Coast region to the
southern Atlantic Coast and Florida; scattered thunderstorms across
the upper Great Lakes and the southern Plateau; showers along the
coast of Washington state; and sunny skies over much of the
remainder of the nation.
   Highs were expected to be in the 60s or 70s along much of the
Pacific Coast; 70s from eastern portions of the upper Great Lakes to
northern New England; above 90 degrees from the southern Atlantic
Coast and Florida across the Gulf Coast region, Mississippi Valley,
the Plains and Rockies into interior California and Oregon; above
100 degrees from the central high Plains across the central Rockies,
central and southern Plateau to interior valleys of California; and
in the 80s for the remainder of the nation.
</TEXT>
