<FIRST>u i AM-WarsawPact 1stLd-Writethru a0646 07-07 0793</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Warsaw Pact, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0646,0815</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev, Allies Discuss Response to Western Proposals</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to RECAST; picks up 11th `Ion Diaconu...'
and SUBS 16th pvs `Gorbachev said...' to CLARIFY Bush proposal.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<UNK>Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>BUCHAREST, Romania (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev told the other
Soviet bloc leaders Friday they are free to pursue their own views
of communism, but suggested his own program of economic and social
reform as a guide.
   ``Each country and each party has its own specifics and can
continue its own individual road to socialist democracy and
progress,'' he said in a dinner toast after the first day of a
Warsaw Pact summit.
   His host at the banquet was President Nicolae Ceausescu of
Romania, the most vocal critic of Gorbachev's reforms.
   The alliance's seven members are divided over the new policies,
with the Soviet Union, Hungary and Poland on the liberal side and
Bulgaria, Czechoslovakia, East Germany and Romania sticking to the
orthodox course.
   Their purposes at this summit are to discuss Western
arms-reduction proposals and the Warsaw Pact's role in a new world
where Gorbachev speaks of a ``common European home'' with no threat
or fear of war.
   In his dinner toast, the Soviet president said: ``We took new
steps today toward European security, rapprochement and East-West
dialogue.'' He also condemned unspecified ``forces'' that want
military confrontation.
   Ceausescu renewed what he described as the Soviet bloc's ``appeal
to NATO to give up its policy of nuclear deterrence.''
   Neither he nor Gorbachev mentioned what was decided Friday.
   Reporters were barred from the conference itself, but were
admitted to the banquet hall in the former royal palace long enough
to hear the brief dinner toasts.
   Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady Gerasimov told an
earlier news briefing Gorbachev and his colleagues discussed NATO
proposals for reducing conventional forces, and how the Soviet bloc
``should change, adapt ... become contemporary.''
   ``Everybody would agree there are vast changes, in our country,
in the world,'' Gerasimov said. ``They are talking about the role of
the Warsaw Pact in these changing conditions.''
   Gerasimov was evasive about whether the topics at the two-day
summit would include political divisions within the bloc.
   Ion Diaconu of the Romanian Foreign Ministry refused comment on a
report by the Soviet news agency Novosti that the leaders were
discussing creation of a Warsaw Pact ``political commission'' to
arbitrate disputes between members.
   Diaconu denied reports that Romania had requested a discussion at
the summit of its feud with Hungary over Romania's alleged
mistreatment of its 1.7 million ethnic Hungarians.
   Gerasimov said disputes within the bloc were not on the agenda,
but ``each delegation can say a few words about its own problems.''
   He said Gorbachev and other leaders addressed the meeting Friday,
but gave no details of the deliberations.
   Reporters were admitted to the palace for a few minutes while
Ceausescu greeted his guests.
   Gorbachev said in West Germany last month that the Bucharest
summit would respond to President Bush's proposal May 29 for a joint
reduction in U.S. and Soviet troops stationed in Europe to 275,000
for each side by 1993, accompanied by cuts in combat aircraft and
other conventional weapons.
   The Soviet leader said the Bush proposal, which will not be on
the table until September, had increased chances for quick agreement
at Vienna negotiations on conventional forces.
   He also is pushing for talks with NATO on reducing tactical, or
short-range, nuclear weapons in Europe, but the United States wants
the issue tied to cuts in conventional forces.
   West Germany, where most of NATO's battlefield nuclear weapons
are stationed, favors talks. The disagreement between the two allies
subsided after Bush made his conventional disarmament offer and said
it could be agreed within a year.
   On Thursday, during a visit to France, Gorbachev again tried to
push the Western alliance into talks on the short-range weapons,
offering the possibility of more unilateral cuts in the Kremlin's
nuclear arsenal if NATO agreed.
   His last offer to scrap nuclear weapons _ about 500 warheads _
came in May during a visit to Moscow by Secretary of State James A.
Baker III, while NATO was arguing about short-range missiles.
   There was unconfirmed speculation in Bucharest that documents
released after the summit ends Saturday might include numbers for
the Strasbourg offer.
   Presidents, Communist Party chiefs, premiers, defense and foreign
ministers and other ranking offiials from the seven Warsaw Pact
nations are attending the summit.
   Romanian television broadcast scenes of delegations arriving on
Thursday. Rezsoe Nyers, the Hungarian party chairman, appeared to be
the only delegation head Ceausescu did not greet with a comradely
kiss on the cheek.
   After Gorbachev arrived, reporters asked him what he expected of
the summit.
   ``I'll tell you when we've finished,'' he said.
</TEXT>
