<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Secrets     07-07 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Secrets,0339</SECOND>
<UNK>Court Allows Material Which Got Harper's Banned In Britain</UNK>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has lost a legal battle to stop
publication of a retired intelligence agent's book after banning an
American magazine that published excerpts.
   The House of Lords, Britain's top court, ruled on Thursday that
``Inside Intelligence'' by Anthony Cavendish could be published
because the government had acknowledged the book was not a threat to
national security.
   The government barred distribution in Britain of last December's
issue of the American magazine Harper's, which carried excerpts.
   It was the second major defeat for Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher's attempts to gag former intelligence agents.
   Last October, the five-judge court rejected a long and costly
attempt through British and foreign courts to ban publication of
``Spy Catcher,'' the memoirs of another ex-agent, Peter Wright.
   Two Scottish newspapers and Scottish Television, which fought the
Cavendish case, hailed the judgment as a victory over what critics
call excessive secretiveness by the Thatcher government.
   ``It was an overweening use of government authority,'' said
Arnold Kemp, editor of the Glasgow Herald.
   ``The government resorted to the tactics of the bully to try to
intimidate the press,'' he said.
   The Thatcher government says it is seeking to hold ex-agents to a
vow of lifelong silence.
   Harper's publisher, John MacArthur, had threatened to fight the
magazine case in the European Court of Human Rights. But Cavendish,
a 62-year-old merchant banker, said he had not given Harper's
permission to publish the excerpts.
   Cavendish, an agent from 1948-53 in Britain's foreign
intelligence operation, described spying in East bloc countries.
   He also claimed that Harold Wilson resigned abruptly as British
Labor Party prime minister in 1976 because the Soviet KGB had
embarrassing information about him.
   In December 1987 Cavendish, defying government instructions not
to publish the book, had 500 copies printed at this own expense and
sent them to friends as Christmas cards. A Scottish legislator
passed the book on to a newspaper, The Scotsman.
</TEXT>
