<FIRST>r i AM-Philippines-Rights     07-07 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-Rights,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soldiers in Killing of Youth Activist Arrested</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Philippines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Friday one soldier
has been arrested and two are being sought in a widely publicized
human rights case involving the killing of leftist Reynaldo
Francisco.
   The announcement by J. Antonio Carpio, director of the National
Bureau of Investigation, was seen as an apparent bid to defuse
criticism of President Corazon Aquino's civil liberties record
during her visit to Europe.
   She leaves on Saturday for West Germany, France and Belgium.
   Carpio said Constable 2nd Class Dioscoro Ambagay Jr. was arrested
and warrants were issued for Sgt. Arnel Jocson and Constable 1st
Class Ramon Clavo in the March 1988, slaying of Francisco and an
attempt on the life of his companion, Hilario Bustamente.
   Bustamante was found near death on March 21, 1988, with deep stab
wounds and cuts across his body.
   He told authorities he and Francisco were abducted on a Manila
street three days earlier while putting up posters protesting U.S.
bases in the Philippines. He said they were taken to the
headquarters of Mrs. Aquino's security force, tortured and then
driven to a remote area where Francisco was slain.
   Bustamente left for the Netherlands last April to address a human
rights conference and has remained there.
   Carpio now wants him to return here to identify the suspects so
they can be charged in court.
   In a memorandum, Carpio noted that the case ``is one of the human
rights cases exploited abroad by the CPP-NDF propaganda,'' referring
to the Communist Party of the Philippines and its ally, the National
Democratic Front.
   In Iligan city, 500 miles southeast of Manila, assailants on
Friday shot to death Capt. Nick Enterina, a provincial police chief,
and Police Sgt. Rogato Garido as they chatted on the street near the
police station, the Philippine Constabulary reported.
   It said the gunmen, believed to be members of the communist New
People's Army, fled on foot.
</TEXT>
