<FIRST>u a AM-Abortion-Louisiana     07-07 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion-Louisiana,0408</SECOND>
<HEAD>District Attorneys Eager To Bring Back Old Anti-Abortion Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET McCONNAUGHEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several Louisiana prosecutors are eager to
resurrect the state's old law banning abortions, in light of the
U.S. Supreme Court's upholding Missouri's restrictions on the
operation.
   ``I firmly believe that abortion is homicide and killing of an
unborn fetus. If a crime has been committed, we will enforce the law
as written here in Rapides Parish,'' District Attorney Charles F.
Wagner said Friday.
   ``The statute's still on our books ... We intend to use that as a
vehicle to get back in court,'' said Harry Connick, district
attorney in Orleans Parish.
   The state House, in a resolution approved 81-13, asked
prosecutors Thursday to enforce whatever pre-1973 abortion laws they
consider constitutional.
   The Senate rewrote the resolution Friday to call for enforcement
of a more recent law similar to the Missouri law that forbids use of
state money, workers or facilities for abortions.
   Federal courts ordered Louisiana in 1976 not to enforce its
abortion law, which carried a penalty of up to 10 years in prison.
However, it never was ruled unconstitutional, said John S. Baker
Jr., a professor at Louisiana State University Law Center.
   Wagner and other prosecutors said they would have to review
Monday's decision before deciding whether to use Louisiana laws
suspended after the 1973 Roe vs. Wade decision that gave women a
right to abortions.
   Some prosecutors were flatly dubious.
   ``I don't think the U.S. Supreme Court has abrogated Wade,'' said
Nathan Stansbury of Lafayette. ``I don't think our general statute
that says all abortions are prohibited is renewed by the Missouri
decision.''
   Baker, who argued the case as an assistant district attorney for
Orleans Parish, said he and Connick have talked about bringing it
back into federal district court but have not made a final decision.
   ``I told Mr. Connick that ... there seemed to be an invitation in
(Monday's ruling) to raise the issue, and that this case might be a
vehicle for doing so,'' Baker said.
   Baker said they probably will decide soon whether to ask the
federal court to reconsider the case that prohibited abortion in
Louisiana.
   Jefferson Parish District Attorney John Mamoulides said his staff
was drawing up a memo for the sheriff's office, outlining which
parts of the old law might legally be enforced.
</TEXT>
