<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-MilitaryBases     07-07 0120</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Military Bases,90</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panel Will Study Other Uses for Military Bases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush created a commission Friday to
study whether military bases can be used for alternative purposes
such as housing nonviolent prisoners, assisting the homeless and
treating drug abusers.
   Bush said the panel will be staffed by representatives of the
Pentagon, the Bureau of Prisons, the National Institute on Drug
Abuse, the General Services Administration, the Department of
Housing and Urban Development and other agencies.
   The Pentagon representative, yet to be named, will be the panel's
chairman.
   Bush said the Pentagon will provide the commission with a report
on active and nonactive military facilities that are not fully
utilized or deemed excess to defense needs.
</TEXT>
