<FIRST>u a AM-NASAIndictments     07-07 0216</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NASA Indictments,0221</SECOND>
<HEAD>Company Accused Of Fraudulent Billings To NASA</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal grand jury has indicted a space
equipment supply company for allegedly billing the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration for fraudulent labor costs on a
space shuttle contract.
   ILC Space Systems of Houston was indicted Thursday with 11 counts
of filing false billing vouchers in 1985. If convicted on all the
counts, the company faces a $5.5 million fine.
   The amount of the alleged fraudulent billing was not included in
the indictment and Assistant U.S. Attorney John Smith declined to
provide the specifics of the allegation.
   Although none of the company's employees was named in the
indictment, Smith said additional indictments are possible.
   Frank Mossman, a spokesman for ILC Dover Inc., ILC Space Systems'
Delaware-based parent company that builds the space suits used by
NASA astronauts, said he could not comment because he had not seen
the indictment.
   ILC Space Systems is under contract to manufacture a heat-shield
system used on the space shuttle's solid-fuel rocket boosters.
   The federal indictment and investigation stem from allegations
that ILC Space Systems illegally passed through labor costs to the
space agency for work actually performed under a fixed-cost
contract, in which the contractor is supposed to pick up the tab for
any unexpected costs.
</TEXT>
