<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-89 2155EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-MissileTest     07-07 0199</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Missile Test,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>SLAM Missile Tested</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon announced Friday that the first
free-flight test of a so-called SLAM missile resulted in a direct
hit last month at a California test site.
   The weapon, also known as a Standoff Land Attack Missile, is a
derivative of the Harpoon missile system.
   It is designed to be fired from aircraft carrier-based planes and
hit targets on land or ships at sea. A ``standoff'' weapon can be
fired from some distance away from the target so that the plane
carrying the weapon is not exposed to enemy fire.
   The SLAM missile makes use of an infrared system that sends a
video image to the plane's pilot, who can select a specific area of
the target.
   In a statement, the Pentagon said the June 24 test was conducted
at the Pacific Missile Center Range in California.
   The missile was fired from a A-6E attack bomber and scored a
``direct hit'' on a simulated missile communication site, the
statement said.
   Nine additional flights are schedule for the test program, the
statement said.
   The missile, built by McDonnell Douglas Missile Systems Co., is
manufactured in St. Charles, Mo., the statement said.
</TEXT>
