<FIRST>r i AM-Sudan-Trial     07-07 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan-Trial,0352</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ousted Premier to Face Tough Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALIA BALIGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sudan's new military ruler said Friday
that ousted Prime Minister Sadek el-Mahdi and 40 other arrested
politicians will face military tribunals on charges of corruption.
   Lt. Gen. Omar Hassan Ahmed el-Bashir said special military courts
will be formed soon for the trials.
   ``I will only be gentle to an honest man,'' el-Bashir said in an
interview with the British Broadcasting Corp. and the U.S.
government-funded Voice Of America. The Associated Press was given
access to the tape.
   ``Those politicians will wish they were being tried under Sharia
(Islamic) laws,'' he said, indicating they will face tough trials.
   El-Mahdi escaped immediately after el-Bashir's coup on June 30
but was arrested in a Khartoum suburb on Thursday.
   Sudan's Islamic laws, passed in 1983, caused an outrcry in the
West because of punishments that include cutting off limbs for
theft, death by stoning for women who commit adultery and lashing
for drinking alconol.
   The laws, currently suspended, are one of the main complaints of
the rebel Sudan People's Liberation Army, which has been fighting
for six years for greater autonomy and political, economic and
administrative reforms.
   El-Bashir has pledged to hold a national referendum on the laws
if planned peace talks with the rebels in the Ethiopian capital
Addis Ababa fail.
   El-Bashir, at the request of the Ethiopian government, postponed
plans for sending a delegation to Addis Ababa, the official Sudan
News Agency reported Friday. It did not elaborate.
   Disbanding Sudan's 36 political parties was among el-Bashir's
first decrees after the coup, and he said Friday the decision was
final.
   He accused political parties of being the cause of Sudan's
problems and said he would find another way for the nation's people
to participate in government.
   ``I don't think Sudan is ready for democracy with multiple
parties,'' el-Bashir said.
   He said the United States could play a role in Sudan by providing
economic aid and helping his administration reach a settlement with
the rebels.
</TEXT>
