<FIRST>r i AM-Brazil-BusHijacking     07-07 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Bus Hijacking,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Escaped Convicts KIlled After Hijacking Bus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police killed three escaped
convicts Friday, captured three others and rescued unharmed a
12-year-old hostage after a bus hijacking and chase through remote
northeastern Brazil, officials reported.
   The six men, armed with revolvers and a shotgun, escaped from the
Lemos de Brito penitentiary, Carlos Anselmo, head of the Bahia State
Security Bureau, said by telephone from the state capital of
Salvador.
   Anselmo said the six first tried unsuccessfully on Thursday to
rob a branch of the Bahia State Bank in Uaua, about 200 miles from
Conceicao do Coite.
   He said they then stopped a bus carrying about 40 passengers and
ordered the driver to head for Conceicao do Coite, a city of about
60,000 lying about 1,180 miles northeast of Rio.
   There, scores of police surrounded the bus and exchanged gunfire
with the hijackers. Three passengers were slightly injured, Jackson
Ferreira of the mayor's office at Conceicao do Coite said by
telephone.
   Before dawn Friday, the hijackers took several hostages from the
bus and fled in a car provided by local authorities. Outside of town
they released all hostages except a 12-year-old boy, then abandoned
the car and fled on foot through the brush, Ferreira said.
   Early Friday, police surrounded a peasant's cottage where the
fugitives had holed up with their hostage and killed three of the
escapers and seized the other three, mayoral aide Ferreira said.
   ``They wanted to hide in the outback, but a lot of peasants live
in the region and it was easy for the police to find them,'' he
added.
