<FIRST>r i AM-China-Economy     07-07 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Economy,0297</SECOND>
<HEAD>China's Growth Rate Slows, Government Gives Mixed Reports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's industrial production grew much more
slowly in the first half of 1989 than in 1988, according to figures
released Friday, but the government seemed unsure whether that was
good or not.
   From an economic standpoint, the news was good: China has been
trying since last fall to slow what it called overheated industrial
growth that was fueling inflation and shortages.
   But since quelling nationwide pro-democracy protests last month,
the government has sought for political reasons to show that
factories are operating normally and production is climbing. News
media have been filled with reports of improved production
nationwide.
   Total industrial output from January through June was $172.9
billion, up 10.8 percent over the same period last year, the
official Xinhua News Agency said, quoting the State Statistics
Bureau.
   By comparison, industrial output in the first half of 1988 grew
17.2 percent over the same period one year earlier. This year, the
government set target of gradually declining growth rates, beginning
with below 16 percent in the first quarter and below 13 percent in
the second. The goal for the year is a 10 increase in production
over 1988.
   Xinhua might well have reported that the nation overfulfilled its
target for controlling too-rapid growth.
   Instead, it focused on industrial production's having grown
``steadily.'' Another Xinhua dispatch said Shanghai, China's leading
industrial city, topped its production quota for the first half of
the year.
   The news agency said Shanghai's industrial output was $13.9
billion up 9 percent from last year.
   It said the growth ``was achieved in the face of shortages of
energy, funds and raw materials during the turmoil which lasted
nearly two months in the city.''
</TEXT>
