<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-89 1955EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Crowe     07-07 0548</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crowe,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crowe: US-Soviet Ties May Be Unsettled For Long Period</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Adm. William J. Crowe, retiring head of the
Joint Chiefs of Staff, said Friday that his historic 11-day visit to
the Soviet Union revealed the superpowers are entering a period of
``uneasy transition'' that ``does not ... make me feel comfortable.''
   Crowe, in a speech before the National Press Club, said he hopes
the two military giants are moving toward a new era in the
superpower relationship, but ``to conclude that we are already there
would be a serious mistake.''
   The 64-year-old admiral, speaking a day after President Bush
rejected a new call from Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev for
talks to eliminate short-range nuclear missiles in Europe, said he
believes United States should avoid ``dramatic counter-responses''
to Kremlin initiatives ``at this point.''
   Crowe met for more than an hour with Gorbachev two weeks ago in
Moscow during his precedent-setting tour of once-secret Soviet
military installations and visits with Soviet military officers.
   It was the first formal visit of a Joint Chiefs chairman to the
Soviet Union and was the latest in a series of high-level visits
designed to dispel distrust between the superpowers. Last July,
Crowe hosted Marshal Sergei F. Akhromeyev, then the Soviet chief of
staff, on a U.S. visit.
   ``There is little question in my mind that real change is afoot
in the Soviet Union,'' Crowe said, adding that he believed that
Gorbachev and his supporters were committed to ``fundamental
reform.''
   Crowe said that while there are encouraging signs that
Gorbachev's reforms and promised military cutbacks may help move
away from the confrontational legacy of the postwar era, the Soviet
changes ``have yet to be translated into reality.''
   ``Our systems remain fundamentally competitive,'' he said.
   The Soviets still retain the world's largest military force and
have made no major changes in their space, air defense or strategic
weapons, he said.
   The admiral lauded the Soviet military officers he met as
``disciplined, well-trained and motivated'' and found their
equipment to be ``impressive and capable in the field.''
   He termed political and social changes the Soviets have initiated
as ``immense and risky.''
   Crowe said he believed the Soviets don't always understand the
United States and ``don't appreciate why we don't respond
move-for-move'' and ``sometimes interpret this phenomenon as
threatening to them.''
   ``All of this does not give me a warm, fuzzy feeling, nor make me
comfortable,'' Crowe said. ``What can be said is that we are
entering a period of uneasy transition and hopefully we are moving
toward a new era in the superpower relationship.''
   The admiral said the Soviets are attempting to ``shed their
past'' and ``don't appreciate why our historical realtionship still
weighs heavily in our decisions.''
   Therefore, Crowe argued, the two superpowers ``may be in this
unsettled state for a long period of time.''
   ``My deepest concern is that our own impatience doesn't force us
to move too far before we understand where the world is headed,''
Crowe said. The United States must ``move gradually and deliberately
in reasonable steps as the horizon becomes clearer _ not before,''
he added.
   The military chief announced on Sunday that he will retire on
Sept. 30 at the end of his second two-year term as chairman.
</TEXT>
