<FIRST>u w AM-ConsumerCredit 1stLd-Writethru   07-07 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Consumer Credit, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0642,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Consumer Borrowing Rebounds in May</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS graf 3: ``Consumer spending,'' to CORRECT that credit not
spending increased 8.5 percent in 1988, with new grafs 3-4 bgng: ``Consumer
credit,''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans took out $3.6 billion more in
consumer debt than they retired in May as the pace of borrowing
turned upward again, the government reported Friday.
   The Federal Reserve Board said consumer credit in May rose at a
seasonally adjusted annual rate of 6.2 percent, up from the 4.3
percent pace of the previous month. Still, it was a smaller rise
than increases of 6.6 percent in March and 9.5 percent in February.
   Consumer credit had increased 8.5 percent over all of 1988.
   Consumer spending is closely watched as a barometer of the
economy's health since it represents two-thirds of overall economic
activity.
   Cynthia Latta, an economist with Data Resources Inc., in
Lexington, Mass., said the report suggests consumer confidence.
   ``Consumers are still adding to their debt,'' she said. ``When
they really get worried, they retrench and start paying down.''
   Interest rates, she said, do not have as much influence on
consumer credit as with other types of loans.
   ``Revolving credit rates hardly move at all, and auto rates only
a percent or so,'' she said. This type of consumer ``is more
concerned with the amount of the monthly payments, not the amount of
interest.''
   Until the spring, interest rates had been rising as the Fed
tightened its grip on credit in its attempt to stem inflation. Since
early last month however, the central bank has loosened its grip and
interest rates have declined somewhat.
   Leading the overall consumer credit increase in May was the
category of debt that includes credit cards. It rose $1.94 billion,
a 12.6 percent annual rate of growth, after a 10.9 percent increase
in April.
   Auto loans were up $1.02 billion May, a 4.2 percent increase on
an annual basis compared to a 2.8 percent rise in April, the Fed
reported. Auto loans had gone up only 0.3 percent in March.
   Bank and credit union loans not secured by real estate increased
by $659 million in May, a 4 percent annual rate of advance, up from
2 percent in April.
   Borrowing for mobile homes fell for the fourth consecutive month,
declining by $15 million at an annual rate of 0.7 percent. That
followed drops of 8.7 percent in April and 84.2 percent in March.
The steep March drop occurred largely becasue of a shift in debt
from the mobile home category into that of bank loans.
   The various changes left total consumer debt in May at a
seasonally adjusted $697.26 billion.
</TEXT>
