<SECOND>AM-Kenya-Illegal Brew,0144</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Raid 27,500 Illegal Brewers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel arap Moi said Friday that
police have raided 27,500 illegal breweries in the month since he
banned the brewing and drinking of traditional alcoholic beverages.
   Moi announced the figure while addressing an agricultural show in
western Kenya.
   Moi, a teetotaler, banned Kenya's traditional drink, chang'aa, on
June 10 and said at the time that he was ``not prepared to lead a
drunken nation.''
   Various kinds of chang'aa are home-brewed mainly from fermented
honey, sugar cane, coconut, and grains such as corn, millet and
sorghum.
   Chang'aa is a popular drink, particularly in the countryside,
during social occasions and at traditional ceremonies.
   Moi said the largest number of illegal brewers discovered were in
Kenya's southwestern Nyanza province on Lake Victoria, where police
raided an estimated 11,000 distilleries.
