<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Personnel 1stLd-Writethru   07-07 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Personnel, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0711,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oregon Lawyer Tapped for Endowment Post</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS graf 6: ``Interviewed by,'' with comment from nominee.
Note contents of 11th graf may offend some readers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush will nominate Oregon lawyer John
E. Frohnmayer as chairman of the National Endowment for the Arts,
the independent federal agency that awards nearly $170 million in
grants each year.
   Frohnmayer, whose nomination requires Senate confirmation, would
succeed Frank Hodsoll.
   A graduate of Stanford University, the University of Chicago and
the University of Oregon Law School, Frohnmayer is an accomplished
singer, avid art collector and longtime supporter of Oregon arts
organizations. He practices law in Portland.
   Frohnmayer was a member of the Oregon Arts Commission for eight
years, serving as chairman from 1980 to 1984. He worked for Bush's
presidential campaign in Oregon.
   Anne Murphy, executive director of the American Arts Alliance, a
Washington arts advocacy group, called Frohnmayer ``a very bright,
caring guy'' who ``has a real commitment to the arts.''
   Interviewed by telephone in Oregon, Frohnmayer himself said: ``I
think it would be premature for me to suggest what I might do before
I'm nominated and confirmed. I certainly would say my enthusiasm for
this job is unbounded.''
   If confirmed for a four-year term, Frohnmayer would take charge
of an agency whose grant-making procedures have been harshly
criticized by several conservative members of Congress who have
accused it of supporting pornographic or blasphemous art.
   The controversy focuses on the endowment's financial support of a
national tour of an exhibition of photographs by Robert
Mapplethorpe, who died of AIDS in March, and a grant made to an
artist through the Southeastern Center for Contemporary Art.
   The Mapplethorpe show, which includes explicit homoerotic
pictures, was scheduled to open July 1 at the Corcoran Gallery of
Art here but was canceled.
   Corcoran director Christina Orr-Cahall said the gallery wanted to
avoid getting embroiled in a political battle over the endowment's
congressional appropriation.
   The works of the other grant recipient, artist Andres Serrano,
include a depiction of Jesus on a crucifix submerged in the artist's
urine.
   Bush was reported to have chosen Frohnmayer over several other
candidates, including Schuyler G. Chapin, former dean of the
Columbia University arts school, and Milton Rhodes, president of the
American Council of the Arts.
   Hodsoll, appointed by President Reagan, left the post in February
after eight years to work in the White House Office of Management
and Budget.
   Bush also announcedhis intention to nominate:
   _Arthur W. Fort, assistant secretary of state for administration.
Fort is former commander of the Pacific Division of Naval Facilities
Engineering Command and commander of the Pacific Fleet Seabees.
   _Milton James Wilkinson, deputy representative of the United
States in the U.N. Security Council with the rank of ambassador. He
would succeed Patricia Mary Byrne.
</TEXT>
