<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-89 2247EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-CoinAuction     07-07 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Coin Auction,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>1804 Silver Dollar Auctioned for Record Price of Nearly $1 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 1804 silver dollar, one of the most prized
coins known to collectors, was sold at auction Friday for $990,000,
the highest amount ever bid for a coin.
   Hugh Sconyers, of the American Rare Coin Fund in Los Angeles,
purchased the 1804 silver dollar for $900,000 and the 10 percent
auction fee at the Auction '89 sale at the Hyatt Regency Chicago.
   He called the purchase a ``cut and dried business decision.''
   ``It's perhaps one of the most famous coins in all of numismatics
and our fund feels that it reprsents a good long-term value,''
Sconyers said after the record purchase.
   The most ever paid for any coin at auction was $725,000 for a
1793 colonial Brasher doubloon in 1979. The current auction record
for a U.S. coin is $625,000, paid in 1982 for an 1870s $5 gold piece.
   The 1804 dollar is one of only 15 U.S. silver dollars bearing
that date, although none actually was minted in 1804.
   During the 1830s, U.S. leaders needed gifts to be given to
foreign governments by ambassadors, so mint workers retrieved an
unused 1803 dollar die and changed the date to 1804. Only 15 such
coins were struck during the next 30 years.
   Seven of the 1804 dollars are in museums and individual
collectors hold the remaining eight.
   The coin sold at auction Friday belonged to Leon Hendrickson,
co-owner of SilverTowne, a rare coin and precious metals dealer in
Winchester, Ind.
   Hendrickson said he bought the coin for $500,000 four years ago
from George Vogt of Houston. ``I bugged him for a few years to sell
it, and he finally did,'' he said.
   ``It's the king of the coins,'' said the 62-year-old Hendrickson,
who began collecting coins during the 1940s. Hendrickson said he
decided to sell the silver dollar after having open-heart surgery
last year.
   ``I'm really going to be sad in lots of ways, glad in other
ways,'' he said. ``I think it's kind of like maybe when you have a
daughter get married, something like that. You're glad and happy and
sad, too, to see them leave home.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
