<HEAD>Fire Breaks Out Again in Peachtree 25th; No Serious Injuries Reported</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads throughout to update with arson suspected, further details;
no pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A suspicious fire broke out briefly Friday night
in the mid-rise office building where a blaze last week killed five
people, but authorities said no serious injuries were reported in
the second fire.
   ``We suspect arson at this time,'' said acting Fire Chief Larry
Mahle, after firefighters extinguished the fire that broke out
shortly before 9 p.m. in a fourth-floor women's rest room. It was
extinguished within five minutes.
   Two maintenance workers who suffered smoke inhalation were taken
to Piedmont Hospital, where they were reported in good condition.
   After Friday night's blaze, Mahle said, an arson investigator
took samples of a couch where the second fire apparently started.
   The building had been reopened to the public only hours earlier,
at 2:30 p.m., Mahle said, and only six maintenance workers were
inside when the fire began.
   On June 30, more than 30 people were injured after a fire broke
out on the fourth floor. Four people died of smoke inhalation in
that blaze, apparently triggered by an explosion that killed an
electrician changing a fuse.
</TEXT>
