project involving a longtime friend of Pierce.
   Kemp's comments were his most direct to date in appraising the
difficulties he inherited when he became housing secretary earlier
this year.
   ``I'm making a lot of changes, so that, by definition, is
suggesting that Secretary Pierce unfortunately _ a very decent and
honest man _ did not in my view manage HUD as carefully or closely
as it should have been managed,'' he told reporters after speaking
to a Republican group.
   ``That reflects on Mr. Pierce and, I say this with sadness not
anger, it reflects on the Reagan administration,'' Kemp said. He and
President Bush will be to blame, Kemp said, if they are unsuccessful
in reforming the agency, a huge task that now involves major
internal reviews of virtually all of the agency's major programs.
</TEXT>
