<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     07-07 0778</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0811</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boyd L. Jefferies, who admitted to an illegal
stock scheme with inside trader Ivan Boesky, was spared a jail term
by a federal judge who praised his cooperation but called Wall
Street greed ``absurd and probably obscene.''
   U.S. District Judge Morris Lasker sentenced Jefferies on Thursday
to five years probation and fined him $250,000. Jefferies, who
pleaded guilty to two felonies, provided information and testimony
in the government's continuing securities fraud investigations in
exchange for leniency.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The country's big chain stores reported their sales improved
modestly in June from May's disappointing results, but the tallies
still indicated consumer spending remains sluggish.
   ``The gains were stronger than we had seen in the prior month but
across the board they were certainly not outstanding,'' Joseph
Ronning, a retail industry analyst with the investment firm Brown
Brothers Harriman &amp; Co., said of Thursday's figures.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The accounting firms Deloitte Haskins &amp; Sells and Touche Ross &amp;
Co. agreed in principle to join forces while two larger Big Eight
firms confirmed they had entered into merger negotiations.
   Subject to the approval of partners at Deloitte and Touche Ross,
the combined company would have worldwide revenue exceeding $4
billion and employ over 65,000 people in 101 countries. It will be
known as Deloitte &amp; Touche in the United States, the firms said
Thursday.
   Separately, Arthur Andersen &amp; Co. and Price Waterhouse confirmed
reports that they had begun talks about a possible merger of their
worldwide operations.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Time Inc. lawyers have charged Paramount
Communications Inc. with trying to deceive the Federal
Communications Commission about how long it would take Paramount to
complete its $12.2 billion hostile bid for Time.
   The media giant's attorneys, in a letter to FCC mass media bureau
chief Alex D. Felker released to the media Thursday, accused
Paramount of making false statements in applications for approval of
former Defense Secretary Donald Rumsfeld as a voting trustee to hold
Time stock.
   Time is fighting Paramount's $200-a-share bid while trying to
preserve a planned merger with Warner Communications Inc.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Net withdrawals from savings and loan
institutions slowed by more than 50 percent in May to $2.4 billion,
the Federal Home Loan Bank Board said.
   After counting interest credited to depositors' accounts, total
deposits in the nation's 2,934 S&amp;Ls grew by $587 million during May
to $955.2 billion, the agency said Thursday. It was the first
increase since last December.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency ordered a
ban on most remaining uses of cancer-causing asbestos, forbidding
its use in hundreds of products ranging from automobile brake parts
to water pipes.
   The prohibition announced Thursday will be phased in over the
next seven years and apply only to new products. Asbestos-containing
products already in use _ and not affected by previous restrictions
_ are not included because in some cases replacement might be more
hazardous than a gradual phase-out, officials said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coffee drinkers could be the winners of a
possible marketing war among roasters following this week's
suspension of coffee bean export quotas, analysts say.
   The International Coffee Organization's decision to suspend
quotas will enable smaller coffee producing countries severely
restricted under the quota system to export high-quality coffee
beans to willing U.S. customers, observers said Thursday. It also
could mean lower retail prices by year's end.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush has cancelled the debt of
sub-Saharan African countries to the United States.
   The president said at a news conference Thursday that beginning
Oct. 1, the U.S. government will forgive official development loans
in the sub-Saharan countries. In 1987, the most recent year in which
figures were immediately available, the State Department put the
total of U.S. loans to sub-Saharan Africa at $4.3 billion, including
$743 million in development loans, $1.5 billion from the U.S.
government's Export-Import Bank and $1.2 billion in U.S. government
loans to buy surplus American farm products.
   Bush did not say which of these categories would be included.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market eked out its third straight gain in another
quiet session Thursday as the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials
rose 5.88 to 2,462.44.
   The dollar closed narrowly higher against all key currencies.
   Bond prices rebounded amid further signs that the Federal Reserve
might be easing monetary policy and pushing interest rates lower.
   Raw coffee futures prices slid to 8-year lows; sugar futures fell
sharply for the second straight day; energy futures fell; pork
futures continued to retreat; grains and soybeans were mixed; and
precious metals were mixed.
</TEXT>
