<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-89 0100EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-RetailSales Bjt   07-07 0745</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Retail Sales, Bjt,0772</SECOND>
<HEAD>Retailers Post Slightly Better Sales Gains in June</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Retail Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales picked up slightly at the country's big chain stores last
month from May's weak pace, but growth was kept in check by a
general slowdown in economic activity.
   ``The gains were stronger than we had seen in the prior month,
but across the board they were certainly not outstanding,'' said
Joseph Ronning, a retail industry analyst with the investment firm
Brown Brothers Harriman &amp; Co.
   Economists monitor retail sales for clues about consumer
expenditures, which account for about two-thirds of the country's
economic activity.
   The reports from U.S. retailers Thursday suggested that spending
on big-ticket goods, like home appliances, has slowed while outlays
for less expensive merchandise haven't been crimped as much by
rising credit charges, reflecting interest rate hikes earlier this
year.
   Several department stores and specialty retailers said they
benefited again last month from the gradual comeback in women's
clothing sales following a deep slump during the past two years.
   Limited Inc., one of the nation's biggest apparel retailers,
posted an 11 percent increase in sales in the five weeks ended July
1. Besides its flagship women's clothing shops, Limited owns
specialty stores such as Victoria's Secret and Abercrombie &amp; Fitch.
   The take at Limited's stores open at least a year, called
same-store or comparable store sales, rose 12 percent in June.
   Retailers and analysts consider the same-store sales a more
accurate reflection of a company's performance than totals that
include sales at newly opened stores. Not every retailer reports
sales on this basis.
   Other beneficiaries of the recovery in women's apparel included
Dayton Hudson Corp., which said total June sales rose 14.2 percent.
The department store operator, which also runs Target and Mervyn's
stores, reported same-store sales were up 6.1 percent.
   J.C. Penney Co. Inc. attributed its sales pickup to demand for
summer fashions and increased purchases of soft home furnishings
like bedding and bath goods. Its June sales rose 7.6 percent and
same-store sales increased 5.6 percent.
   Fred Wintzer, who follows specialty clothing merchants for the
investment firm Alex. Brown &amp; Sons Inc. in Baltimore, said: ``The
apparel retailers are making progress but they are a little bit
disappointing given how bad last year's results were.''
   Recent monthly sales by apparel sellers may look much better than
they actually were because they are being compared with last year,
which was an exceptionally bleak time for fashion merchandising.
   Among the leading general merchandisers, K mart Corp., the
country's second-largest retailer after Sears, Roebuck and Co., said
its June sales represented an improvement after a string of
disappointing months. The discounter said sales at all of its stores
went up 5.7 percent in June after a 2.5 percent increase in May.
   Sales at K marts open at least a year picked up 2.3 percent in
June after falling 0.6 percent in May.
   Rival discounter Wal-Mart Stores Inc., third among U.S.
retailers, turned in another robust performance, reporting a 25
percent increase in total June sales and a 10 percent gain in
same-store sales.
   Jeffrey Edelman, an analyst with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.,
said industrywide sales were uneven during June, with the weaker
figures from the non-clothing categories.
   A series of indexes Edelman prepared indicated most types of
retailers fared better in June than in May. The weighted average of
37 merchants' sales, on a same-store basis, rose 5.3 percent in June
after a 4.2 percent May gain.
   The Drexel index of sales at 14 department stores and discounters
rose 4.6 percent last month vs. 3.8 percent the month before while
the measurement of apparel retailers repeated a 7.7 percent increase.
   The index for hard goods, including furniture, electronics and
household appliances, dropped 1.8 percent in June after rising 3.4
percent in May.
   In reports from other major retailers Thursday:
   Sears said its sales rose 2.9 percent in the five weeks ended
July 1 from a year earlier. On a comparable-store basis, Sears'
sales increased 3.6 percent.
   May Department Stores Co. said sales rose 6.8 percent during the
five weeks and same-store sales were up 5 percent.
   Melville Corp. reported a 14.6 percent increase in June sales.
Melville does not report same-store sales.
   Montgomery Ward &amp; Co. said its June sales increased 6.6 percent
overall and 6.4 percent on a same-store basis.
   F.W. Woolworth Co. said its domestic sales increased 8.2 percent
in June while its same-store sales rose 3.6 percent.
</TEXT>
