<FIRST>r f PM-CNWCuts     07-07 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-CNW Cuts,0199</SECOND>
<HEAD>CNW to Slash Executive Jobs By 25 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CNW Corp. says it will cut about a fourth of its
managers to help reduce costs and pay for a pending $1.6 billion
buyout of the company.
   James Foote, a CNW spokesman, said the company was offering
voluntary buyouts to each of its 1,000 managers to reduce the top
ranks by 250.
   He said managers have until Monday to decide whether to accept
the buyout packages, which include severance payments based on the
length of employment with CNW.
   ``If we don't get the 25 percent voluntarily, then we'll make
involuntary cuts,'' Foote said Wednesday. ``It's part of our overall
effort to reduce manpower. We are accelerating that effort because
of the sale of the company.'' CNW, parent company of the Chicago &amp;
North Western railroad, last month agreed to a $50-a-share offer by
an investment group formed by Blackstone Capital Partners L.P. and
CNW's senior management.
   CNW accepted the managment-led bid following a hostile tender
offer from Japonica Partners, a New York investment partnership.
   CNW has cut its total work force to 8,500 from 10,200 in 1985.
</TEXT>
