<DOCNO> AP890707-0203 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-89 0114EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-AccountingList     07-07 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Accounting List,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Biggest Accounting Firms</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Accounting Merger, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a list of the biggest accounting firms on
the basis of their fiscal 1988 revenue from U.S. operations,
compiled by Bowman's Accounting Report of Atlanta.
   The list assumes completion of the merger announced in May of
formerly third-ranked Ernst &amp; Whinney with Arthur Young &amp; Co., which
had been No. 6. The U.S. partners of those firms approved the merger
last month, while votes by various overseas partners are expected
through the end of the year.
   1. Ernst &amp; Young, $2.0 billion U.S. revenue, $4.3 billion
international revenue.
   2. Arthur Andersen, $1.71 billion U.S. revenue, $2.82 billion
international revenue.
   3. KPMG (Peat Marwick Main &amp; Co.), $1.64 billion U.S. revenue,
$3.90 billion international revenue.
   4. Coopers &amp; Lybrand, $1.14 billion U.S. revenue (estimate),
$2.50 billion international revenue (estimate).
   5. Price Waterhouse, $960 million U.S. revenue, $2.20 billion
international revenue.
   6. Deloitte Haskins &amp; Sells, $820 million U.S. revenue, $1.92
billion international revenue.
   7. Touche Ross, $796 million U.S. revenue, $1.84 billion
international revenue.
   8. Laventhol &amp; Horwath, $306 million U.S. revenue, $556 million
international revenue.
   9. Grant Thornton, $200 million U.S. revenue, $721 million
international revenue.
   10. BDO Seidman, $157 million U.S. revenue, $758 million
international revenue.
   11. McGladrey &amp; Pullen, $139 million U.S. revenue, $402 million
international revenue.
   12. Kenneth Leventhal, $126 million U.S. revenue, $292 million
international revenue.
   13. Pannell Kerr Forster, $87 million U.S. revenue, $317 million
international revenue.
   14. Spicer &amp; Oppenheim, $70 million U.S. revenue, $344 million
international revenue.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Note: Arthur Andersen and Price Waterhouse disclosed Thursday
they have begun formal talks on a merger of their worldwide
operations.
