<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-89 0115EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-FundRankings     07-07 0483</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fund Rankings,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>Utility Mutual Funds Fare Best, Gold Funds Worst in 2nd Qtr</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mutual funds that invested in utilities posted
the biggest returns as a group in the second quarter, while
gold-oriented funds fared the poorest, according to a new survey of
mutual fund performance.
   The survey by Lipper Analytical Services, distributed for release
today, said utility funds had an average rate of return of 11.25
percent in the three months ended June 30, while gold-oriented funds
lost 2.97 percent.
   That placed those two groups at the top and bottom of the list,
respectively, of 20 fund groups that Lipper tracks. Its tallies
assume that all dividends and capital gains distributions are
reinvested. Lipper has been publishing its fund performance analysis
for 16 years.
   ``Utility funds benefitted from both lower interest rates and
particular interest in telephone company securities,'' said A.
Michael Lipper, president of the research concern that bears his
name.
   He said funds invested in gold companies or bullion, on the other
hand, ``have not had a period of good performance for so long that
they are bound to have one some day.''
   The only other group posting a negative rate of return for the
quarter were international funds, which lost an average of 0.27
percent.
   Overall, Lipper said general equity funds outperformed fixed
income funds, with a rate of return of 7.28 percent compared with
5.66 percent.
   That compares with a 7.61 percent rate of return in the Dow Jones
industrial average of 30 blue chip stocks and 8.82 percent in the
S&amp;P 500 index, assuming dividend reinvestment, Lipper said.
   Despite the slower overall performance of fixed-income funds, a
pair of fixed-income funds invested mainly in zero-coupon Treasury
securities had the highest rate of return of more than 1,730
individual funds tracked.
   The Benham Target 2015 fund had a rate of return of 27.42 percent
for the period while Benham Target 2010 fund gained 23.61 percent,
the Lipper survey said.
   Eagle Growth Shares, a growth fund with large holdings in media
companies, had the third-highest rate of return at 23.57 percent, it
said.
   The worst-performing individual funds were Strategic
Gold-Minerals, a gold-oriented fund that lost 9.01 percent, and
Prudent Speculator: Large Cap, a capital appreciation fund that lost
8.30 percent.
   The growth fund group was the best performer among the general
equity funds, with an average rate or return of 7.79 percent.
Capital appreciation funds gained an average of 7.33 percent, while
growth and income funds and equity income funds each had average
returns of 6.92 percent.
   The slowest-growing general equity fund was the group of small
company growth funds at an average of 6.77 percent.
   Among funds invested in specific areas, the science and
technology funds group had an average rate of return of 7.07
percent, the health and biotechnology fund group gained 5.25 percent
and the natural resources funds gained 3.31 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
