<FIRST>r f PM-InsuranceRollback     07-07 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Insurance Rollback,0360</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Farm Announces Lawsuit Against Nevada Insurance Rollback</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE McDONALD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARSON CITY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State Farm Mutual Automobile Insurance
Co. says it will file a lawsuit challenging a Nevada law that
requires auto insurers to cut their rates.
   ``We'll probably file the complaint by the end of next week or
early in the week after that,'' said Dave Hill, a spokesman at the
insurer's headquarters in Bloomington, Ill.
   Hill said Thursday the company plans to challenge the law under
the Nevada and U.S. constitutions on the grounds that the forced
rollback violates the prohibition against taking property without
due process.
   The law requires insurers to cut their rates to 15 percent below
the levels of July 1, 1988, on new or renewed policies, starting in
October.
   Gov. Bob Miller, who signed the rollback into law Thursday, has
said he's uncertain about the measure's constitutionality. But he
said Nevadans who support a rate rollback deserve a chance to have
the state defend their position in court.
   The law allows insurance companies to raise rates only if they
prove to the state insurance commissioner that they would go
bankrupt without an increase.
   Nevada has the fifth-highest auto insurance rates in the nation,
with drivers paying average annual premiums of $880, according to
the state Insurance Division.
   The American Insurance Association has said it also planned to
challenge the rollback in court.
   Jeff Beyer, a spokesman for Farmers Insurance Group Inc., one of
Nevada's largest auto insurers, said the company hasn't decided
whether to challenge the rollback.
   He said a similar bankruptcy test in California's Proposition 103
insurance rollback was ruled unconstitutional by that state's
Supreme Court on the grounds it denied insurers a fair return on
their investment.
   ``Farmers is as concerned as anybody about containing the cost of
auto insurance in Nevada, but this is simply not a workable way to
solve the problem,'' Beyer said in a telephone interview from
Farmers' Los Angeles headquarters.
   ``You can't roll back prices by fiat without doing something
about the underlying costs.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
