<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern-Tickets     07-07 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Tickets,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Approves Ticket Refund Plan Between Eastern, Travel Agents</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Airline Discounts, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A plan worked out by strike-hobbled Eastern
Airlines and travel agents for refunding unused tickets has won the
approval of a federal bankruptcy judge.
   The plan ties the refunds to future ticket sales by the agents.
   At a court hearing Thursday, U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R.
Lifland approved the plan agreed to by Eastern, its major creditors
and the American Society of Travel Agents.
   The travel agent group earlier had petitioned the bankruptcy
court to require Eastern to pay refunds on unused tickets to travel
agents, who would pass the refunds on to their customers.
   Miami-based Eastern sought bankruptcy protection from creditors
on March 9, five days after the start of a crippling strike by the
Machinists union that was joined by pilots and flights attendants.
At that time, the airline said its debts included about $165 million
in unused tickets issued before the bankruptcy filing.
   That amount has since been reduced to about $80 million, Eastern
spokesman Robin Matell said Thursday.
   Eastern estimates it sells 75 percent of its tickets through
travel agents.
   Under Eastern's existing policy, travelers who paid cash for
unused tickets must apply directly to Eastern or to bankruptcy court
as creditors. Those who bought tickets by credit card can apply for
refunds from the card issuer.
   Alternatively, customers can use their tickets to fly Eastern,
where available, or sister carrier Continental Airlines. Although
airlines generally honor each other's tickets, competitors stopped
honoring Eastern tickets after it filed for bankruptcy protection.
   Under the new plan, effective today, travel agents will be
reimbursed for ticket refunds they gave their customers. The total
amount of refund money available will be based on the volume of new
Eastern tickets sold by the agents.
   Eastern will put $5 million into the reimbursement fund up front.
In addition, for the rest of July, Eastern will pay into the fund
each week the total amount of agents' sales of Eastern tickets that
exceeds $3.6 million, up to a maximum of $1.25 million a week.
   In August, the cap on the amount that could go into the fund each
week will increase to $2 million. A maximum of $20 million could be
put into the fund from ticket sales during the life of the program.
   The pilots union at Eastern blasted the agreement, calling it
``nothing short of the blackmail of travel agents who are creditors
in the Eastern bankruptcy.''
   In a statement, the union said the agents are, in effect,
required to sell Eastern tickets in order to make sure they can
collect the money Eastern owes them.
   In addition, the pilots said, the plan makes no provision for
customers who purchased their Eastern tickets directly, rather than
through a travel agent.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890707-0211 </DOCNO>
