<FIRST>r f PM-AirlineDiscounts Bjt   07-07 0584</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Airline Discounts, Bjt,0613</SECOND>
<HEAD>Holiday Discount Fares Light Up Reservation Switchboards</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY JORDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Airline reservation switchboards are lighting up
like fireworks this week as thousands of travelers take advantage of
bargain air fares that were sparked by the midweek July 4 holiday,
airline officials say.
   Continental Airlines ignited the Independence Day fare war with
its ``Spirit of '76'' ticket prices _ $76 one way almost anywhere
the airline flies in the continental United States.
   Rivals that matched the fare, and those that upped the ante,
reported the price-slashing lit a fire under air travelers looking
for bargains.
   The special fares are designed to drum up business during the
slack midweek holiday travel period, airline officials said.
   ``Traditionally, when you see a holiday falling in midweek,
business travelers decide not to travel that week. That is the case
this week. But this is win-win situation,'' said Ned Walker, a
Continental spokesman at the airline's Houston headquarters.
   After Continental announced its low fares Sunday, Braniff Airways
matched the offer the next day. Bookings at Braniff on Monday broke
the airline's one-day record by about 40 percent, said spokesman Don
McGuire.
   ``The holiday weekend was extremely strong. The public response
has been beautiful,'' he said in a telephone interview from Braniff
headquarters in Orlando, Fla.
   United Airlines and American Airlines also matched the cut-rate
fares.
   Tickets for most of the special fares must be purchased by
Saturday and travel must start by that day. The fares require a
round-trip purchase and carry other restrictions.
   Most industry observers said the holiday discounts are nothing
new and amounted to an excuse to advertise. But one analyst said
Braniff's program has a different intent.
   ``It is a typical action by an airline that is perhaps a little
tight on cash,'' said Robert J. Joedicke, an analyst at Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc. ``It is an attempt to sell fares now in order to
get working capital.''
   The discounts are not part of a long-term trend toward lower
airline fares, he said.
   ``The truth is, discounted fares are harder and harder to find,''
said Joedicke.
   Joedicke said Continental's $76 fare, offered for such a short
period, wouldn't make much of a difference in the airline's revenue
figures.
   But Walker said response to Continental's holiday fares was so
great that the airline added several thousand additional seats for
the program.
   ``We are selling seat inventory that might otherwise go unsold,
and the American consumers get a bargain they haven't seen in
years,'' he said.
   Following Continental's lead, American Airlines adopted a $152
round-trip fare, which applies to any of the 111 markets it serves
in the 48 contiguous states.
   The Dallas-based airline also reported its best one-day traffic
period ever last Friday, when it flew 276.84 million revenue
passenger miles with an 83.5 percent load factor, officials said.
   ``We had extremely full flights anyway'' before the fare was
announced, said American spokesman Jim Brown.
   United's similar fares extend to all cities it serves in the 48
states, said spokeswoman Sara Dornacker at the airline's Chicago
headquarters.
   ``They are selling extremely well. We are having an extremely
higher period of bookings than we had last year,'' she said.
   As a result of existing higher demand, Atlanta-based Delta Air
Lines decided not to match the other fares.
   ``We looked at our loads for those days and they were high,''
said Delta spokesman Jim Lundy. ``So we were looking at diluting
revenue we already had on the books.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890707-0212 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-89 0123EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Time Bjt   07-07 0736</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Time, Bjt,0762</SECOND>
<HEAD>Time Accuses Paramount of Trying to Deceive FCC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Time Inc. lawyers have charged Paramount
Communications Inc. with trying to deceive the Federal
Communications Commission about how long it would take Paramount to
complete its $12.2 billion hostile bid for Time.
   The media giant's attorneys, in a letter to FCC mass media bureau
chief Alex D. Felker released to the media Thursday, accused
Paramount of making false statements in applications for approval of
former Defense Secretary Donald Rumsfeld as a voting trustee to hold
Time stock.
   Time is fighting Paramount's $200-a-share bid while trying to
preserve a planned merger with Warner Communications Inc.
   Time's lawyers charged that although Paramount told the FCC it
expected its original $10.7 billion bid to expire July 5, Paramount
executives knew before their offer was announced that it could not
close for several months because it is conditioned upon obtaining
regulatory approval to operate about 800 cable television systems
that Time owns. The offer is now scheduled to expire July 28.
   Paramount called the charges a delaying tactic.
   ``Time continues frantically to try to block our $200-a-share
tender offer _ the only real issue in this whole matter _ by raising
questions on timing,'' Paramount said in a statement.
   ``Of course it might take a few months to get the approvals,''
the statement continued. ``Our process is well under way.''
   Paramount released a letter from its own attorneys responding to
queries from the FCC. The letter, also addressed to Felker, said
Paramount expects it will take ``a few months'' to obtain the cable
approvals.
   At issue is Paramount's request for special temporary approval
for Rumsfeld, who would hold Time stock after the conclusion of
Paramount's tender offer and while Paramount awaits approval for the
transfer of licenses for microwave relay systems operated by Time's
cable TV subsidiary, American Television &amp; Communications Corp.
   The FCC has jurisdiction over the transfer of the relay
facilities.
   Time's attorneys claimed in their letter that because of
misrepresentations by Paramount, it would be against the public
interest for the FCC to grant Paramount's requests.
   Along with the letter, Time released parts of depositions given
by Paramount executives. In one deposition, Paramount's chief
financial officer, Michael Hope, said he did not believe company
officials gave Paramount's board ``any reason to believe that that
(July 5) would be a realistic date to expect to close this
transaction.''
   Paramount criticized Time for releasing only parts of the
depositions. ``The whole record should be available in this case
with a few minor exceptions,'' the company said. ``Time only wants
to open up for public inspection those carefully selected areas of
the record they think are useful to them.''
   While Time and Paramount quarreled over the trustee, the primary
issue in the struggle is before Delaware Chancery Court, which will
decide whether Time, in agreeing to merge with Warner earlier this
year, in effect put itself up for sale.
   If the court rules that Time did in fact put itself on the block,
the media giant's board must give serious consideration to the
Parmount offer, which Time directors rejected as financially
inadequate and too conditional.
   A hearing is set for Tuesday.
   In another courtroom, this one in Stamford, Conn., arguments were
heard Thursday in a suit brought by Time's ATC subsidiary that seeks
an injunction to stall the Paramount bid.
   Paramount attorney John L. Warden charged ATC sought the
injunction merely to keep in place Time's management, ``which has
negotiated extremely lucrative contracts for the next decade.''
   But ATC attorney James Stapleton denied the charge, saying,
``We're not trying to stop the tender offer.'' He said Paramount
officials were interested only in Time and ``they don't care about
ATC.''
   ATC, the nation's second-largest cable company with more than 4
million customers, wants Paramount to obtain approval as a cable
television franchise owner before proceeding with a takeover.
   The Time subsidiary said contracts for 200 of its franchises
require regulatory approval of a new parent company before the new
parent company assumes control.
   ATC contends it could be stripped of the 200 franchises if
Paramount fails to gain prior approval of its takeover bid.
   On Wall Street Thursday, Time stock rose 37{ cents a share to
close at $155.62{. Paramount fell $1.50 to $57.87{ a share, and
Warner picked up 50 cents to close at $61.75 a share.
</TEXT>
