<DOCNO> AP890707-0214 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-89 0139EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-AutoSupply Bjt   07-07 0531</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auto Supply, Bjt,0547</SECOND>
<HEAD>Larger Incentives, Lower Financing Could Be On Its Way</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   DETROIT _ Car buyers who resisted the incentives of this spring
and summer may have their patience rewarded during the next few
weeks. The scenario they've been waiting for _ high rebates and low
interest rates _ may be on its way.
   The prime rate has dropped recently and there have been
indications that other interest rates, including those for cars,
will fall.
   ``I think there's no question that the direction of interest
rates is downward,'' Donald Ratajczak of the Economic Forecasting
Center at Georgia State University in Atlanta said Thursday.
   The incentives, which have been around since April, are likely to
stay through the end of the model year this fall because they
apparently haven't done the trick.
   Earlier this week, the eight major vehicle manufacturers with
domestic plants reported their car and light truck sales for the
first half of 1989 were 4.8 percent behind the sales pace during the
same time last year.
   That could prompt automakers to add more incentives or beef up
existing ones to move out 1989 models and clear dealer lots for the
1990s, which officially debut Oct. 1, analysts say.
   ``It's an incredibly good buying time,'' said auto analyst John
Kirnan of Kidder, Peabody &amp; Co. Inc.
   However, he added: ``The industry is going to be very hard
pressed to turn the spigot on for the third quarter. You've got the
greatest levels of incentives out there and they don't seem to be
generating the interest.''
   Bill Meier, general manager of Ray Green Chevrolet in
Jacksonville, Ill., agreed.
   ``It's been slow and it's beginning to taper off,'' he said
Thursday.
   Manufacturers and dealers are wrestling with high inventory
levels, estimated by some to be as much as 80 days' worth of stock
at the current selling rate.
   ``My guess is that the industry had 76 days (worth of cars) at
the end of June, with the Big Three at 78 to 80 days,'' said analyst
David Healy of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in New York. ``It's not a
disaster, but it's uncomfortably high. A year ago, you were looking
at 60, 61 or 62 days.''
   One way to deflate inventory is to close production, drying up
the supply of cars coming into the retail sales pipeline. That, in
turn, forces layoffs.
   A United Auto Workers spokesman, declining to be identified, said
the union was monitoring the sales and production figures closely to
be sure that any layoffs are allowed under contracts with the Big
Three.
   Selective plant production cuts began several months ago. This
week and the next kick off the traditional summer vacation and
model-changeover time, as factories are prepared for the next model
year. Ford Motor Co. has no production scheduled during that time.
   On Thursday, Ward's Automotive Reports said domestic automakers'
production levels were sharply lower this week compared with the
same week a year ago. The trade journal said automakers scheduled
the production of 71,167 cars and trucks in the United States this
week, 42.6 percent fewer than the 124,029 vehicles they produced
during the same week last year.
</TEXT>
