<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-89 0735EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Accutane     07-07 0518</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Accutane,0538</SECOND>
<HEAD>Acne Drug Maker Loses First Jury Verdict over Side Effects</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Whether or not the first jury verdict against
Hoffmann-La Roche Inc.'s Accutane acne medicine leads to more
lawsuits will probably be irrelevant to the billion-dollar drug
company, analysts say.
   ``There is nothing that can happen to Hoffmann-La Roche as a
result of this situation,'' said Calvert Crary, a litigation analyst
at Labe Simpson &amp; Co. Inc. in New York.
   Last week, a federal jury in Mississippi agreed with the claim by
Mary Kathryn Thomas that the acne medicine sent her to the hospital
with bouts of disorientation, seizures and eventually comas that
lasted several days.
   The jury awarded Ms. Thomas, 59, $1 million.
   Even if hundreds of people began filing such lawsuits, ``It would
be a matter of utterly no consequence'' to the Nutley, N.J.-based
drug maker, said Crary.
   ``In a way, I suppose you could say that's what's so sick about
the whole system, but that's the system,'' he said.
   The powerful drug, a highly effective medicine for a severe and
scarring form of acne, has been linked to 73 cases of birth defects.
Its potential side effects include skin dryness, vomiting, nausea,
headaches and visual disturbances.
   A jury in Aberdeen, Miss., found that the company failed to warn
Ms. Thomas's doctor adequately about Accutane's potential side
effects when it was prescribed in 1984. Ms. Thomas at the time lived
in Columbus, Miss., and now lives outside Orlando, Fla.
   ``They're not emphasizing just how toxic this drug is,'' said Ms.
Thomas's attorney, John Owens of Tuscaloosa, Ala.
   ``We feel the verdict is wrong, that it's inappropriate,'' said
company spokeswoman Carolyn Glynn. Hoffmann-La Roche, the U.S.
subsidiary of Swiss pharmaceutical giant F. Hoffmann-La Roche &amp; Co.,
is considering an appeal, among other options, she said. Ms. Glynn
would not comment on what those might be.
   Accutane is not a proven cause of the seizures, but the company
in 1985 included warnings indicating that such seizures have been
reported in Accutane users, she said.
   Analysts discounted the lawsuit avalanche common to the asbestos
industry, the Dalkon Shield or even, to a lesser degree, cigarette
makers, who despite last year's first jury loss face fewer product
liability suits.
   There just aren't enough potential plaintiffs, said Karl
Habermas, a pharmaceutical analyst with Sanford C. Bernstein Inc. of
New York.
   ``I'm sure this will induce others to file suit and encourage
those who have, but I don't think there are that many people who
have been injured by the product,'' he said.
   Hoffmann-La Roche has yearly U.S. sales of $1.9 billion; Accutane
accounts for only about $45 million to $50 million, said Ms. Glynn.
Since the prescription drug's introduction in 1982, 1.4 million to
1.5 million people are estimated to have used it, she said.
   Insurance covers jury awards, and even without it, future cases
would be ``financially insignificant,'' Crary said.
   Ms. Glynn said 30 to 35 Accutane cases are pending, and a
somewhat greater number have been settled, thrown out of court or
won by the company.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
