<FIRST>r f BC-Mexico-Stocks     07-07 0160</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Mexico-Stocks,0166</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Opening Stock Market to Foreign Investment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has opened Mexico's stock
exchange to foreign investment in a move that paves the way toward
eventual foreign-owned brokerages, newspapers reports said.
   Oscar Espinoza Villareal, president of the National Stock
Commission, labeled as ``historical'' the introduction of new
investment mechanisms since the government liberalized the rules on
foreign investment in May. Many sectors of the Mexican economy had
been reserved exclusively for the government and Mexican investors
for years.
   The official said that effective Thursday, foreign companies
could serve as advisers and intermediaries to Mexican brokerages
from overseas offices. They would also be able to invest using
foreign currency, the reports said.
   Enpinoza was quoted as saying that opening up the stock market
would allow it to operate in a more sophisticated manner.
   Foreigners previously have been able to invest in the Mexican
stock market, but only through local brokers and only in pesos.
</TEXT>
