<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-89 1049EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Coors-Keystone     07-07 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Coors-Keystone,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coors Will Offer Lower-Priced Brew</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Adolph Coors Co. said it will offer a
lower-priced beer starting Sept. 11, for the first time in its
116-year history.
   The brewer, the nation's fourth-largest, plans a large
advertising campaign to introduce Keystone and Keystone Light, Mike
Willey, brand development manager for Keystone, said Thursday.
   Coors will brew Keystone at its Golden plant with existing
employees, Willey said. Production on other labels will not be cut.
   Beer pricing is divided into categories: import; super premiums
such as George Killian's; premiums such as Miller High Life, Coors
and Budweiser; popular brands such as Old Milwaukee, Old Style,
Rainier, and economy brands such as Meisterbrau.
   Popular and economy beers account for a fourth of the $40 billion
retail beer market in the United States every year.
   ``There's considerable demand for a high-quality beer at a
popular price. It's a category we haven't been in,'' Willey said.
   ``Old Milwaukee and Heileman are losing their market share. We
think they're vulnerable,'' he added.
   Emanuel Goldman, an analyst with Paine-Webber in San Francisco,
said Coors' strategy makes sense in the highly competitive industry.
   ``It's a good-sized business. Stroh and Heileman are having a
difficult time of it. Coors has to be in it,'' he said.
   Old Milwaukee sells for less than $5 for a 12-pack in the Denver
area. Premium beers sell for more than $6 a 12-pack, with imports
going for more than $7.
</TEXT>
