<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 11am,0248</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market pushed ahead today in a lukewarm
response to the latest government statistics on employment.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 5.69 to 2,468.13 by
11 a.m. on Wall Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 4 to 3 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 640 up, 471 down and
579 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 49.60 million shares at
midmorning.
   Analysts said the Labor Department's employment data for June
didn't do much to resolve the debate on Wall Street over whether the
economy might be headed for a recession or a more benign ``soft
landing.''
   The report showed an increase of 180,000 in nonfarm payroll
employment, below most advance estimates.
   But figures for May were revised to show a gain of 207,000, more
than double the estimate of 101,000 reported a month ago.
   The equivocal numbers left traders watching the credit markets
for signs of how the Federal Reserve might have interpreted them.
   Gainers among the blue chips included American Telephone &amp;
Telegraph, up \ at 35|; Philip Morris, up { at 141; General
Electric, up [ at 52\, and Eastman Kodak, up | at 48\.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.34 to 180.16. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .85 at 361.96.
