<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   07-07 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Mostly Lower on Cooler, Wetter Forecasts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were mostly lower
in early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade in response to
forecasts for cooler, wetter weather in the Midwest next week.
   Some selling may also have reflected pre-weekend
position-adjusting by traders reluctant to go home holding ``buy''
positions amid uncertainty about the weather.
   ``This is a very nervous market,'' said Dale Gustafson, an
analyst with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in Chicago.
   Prices rallied strongly earlier in the week on predictions of an
extended heat wave in the Corn Belt but some forecasters have since
offered more moderate outlooks.
   A change to cooler, wetter weather would be particularly good for
the corn crop, analysts said.
   Wheat futures retreated in early trading on weather forecasts
favorable for winter-wheat harvesting.
   In early trading, wheat was 1 cent to 1{ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in July at $4.04 a bushel; corn was 3\ cents
lower to 1 cent higher with July at $2.75{ a bushel; oats were
unchanged to { cent lower with July at $1.60 a bushel; soybeans were
7 cents lower to 3{ cents higher with July at $7.68{ a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mostly lower while pork futures were mixed in
early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were unchanged to .48 cent lower with August at 69.92
cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .25 cent lower with
August at 81 cents a pound; live hogs were .30 cent lower to .30
cent higher with July at 47.07 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .85 cent lower to .33 cent higher with July at 30.80 cents a
pound.
   Cattle futures settled mixed on Thursday while pork futures
retreated.
</TEXT>
