<FIRST>r f PM-CoalStrike 1stLd-Writethru f0071 07-07 0492</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Coal Strike, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0071,0500</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Wildcat Stikers Fired In Bitter Coal Walkout</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with pickets blocking hearing,
and CORRECT number of workers fired to 28 sted 29. Picks up 5th graf pvs,
`The dismissals...'. This also moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY P. KISSEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUNTINGTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A coal company whose contract with the
United Mine Workers includes a no-strike clause has fired 28 wildcat
strikers who refused to return to work, the first firings of the
four-week wildcat walkout, officials said today.
   The company couldn't hold a formal hearing on the firings late
this morning in Beckley, because 2,000 UMW members blocked a meeting
hall. Representatives of Toney's Branch Coal Co. and the UMW refused
to cross a picket line that surrounded the Raleigh County Armory.
   Dismissal forms given the workers said they were fired for
refusing to cross pickets at Toney's Branch's mine in Racine. The
delay in the formal hearing does not mean the firings are postponed.
   ``This should tell them that all it's going to do is incite the
workers,'' UMW international executive board member Howard Green
said in a telephone interview from Beckley.
   Earlier, officials at Toney's Branch headquarters in Beckley
refused to comment on the dismissals beyond saying the company was a
member of the Bituminous Coal Operators Association, which in
February 1988 signed a UMW contract that included a no-strike
clause. A coal industry manual says there are 56 employees at the
Toney Branch's Racine mine, but does not specify how many are UMW
members.
   The dismissals are the first during a four-week wildcat sympathy
strike by UMW members backing colleagues at the Pittston Co. who
have been on strike since April. Pittston, unlike most other coal
companies, has no contract with the UMW, and the union has
sanctioned that strike but not the wildcat walkout at other
companies.
   As many as 46,000 miners in 10 states have stayed off the job at
one time or another since the unauthorized walkouts began June 12.
Today, about 37,000 miners in eight states were off their jobs.
   A two-week vacation period for many miners ends at midnight
Sunday and several locals have discussed or plan to consider
returning to work, fearing what happened to the Toney's Branch
miners.
   ``Some of them think if this goes down the drain, miners might be
in bad shape _ they (coal companies) might bust the union,'' said
Charlie Greer, the president of a UMW local that represents
Zanesville, Ohio-area miners.
   U.S. Sen. Robert Byrd said Thursday he wanted Labor Secretary
Elizabeth Dole to step in and help end the strikes.
   Byrd, D-W.Va., said Dole should ask UMW President Richard Trumka
and Pittston Chairman Paul Douglas to settle their organizations'
differences so that 1,900 striking Pittston miners can return to
work.
   The union and the company haven't been at the bargaining table
for several weeks now.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
