<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreetNoon     07-07 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Noon,0309</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market staged a broad rally today amid
expectations of renewed declines in interest rates.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 23.71 to 2,486.15 by
noontime on Wall Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by more than 2 to 1 in nationwide
trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 899 up, 402
down and 507 unchanged.
   The market opened on a hesitant note, but then jumped ahead at
midsession as traders concluded that the Federal Reserve apparently
had been encouraged to relax its credit policy in response to the
Labor Department's employment data for June.
   The report showed an increase of 180,000 in nonfarm payroll
employment, below most advance estimates.
   By contrast, figures for May were revised to show a gain of
207,000, more than double the estimate of 101,000 reported a month
ago.
   Still, brokers said, Wall Streeters came increasingly to believe
that the Fed interpreted the data as reason enough to ease up on its
credit restraints.
   Interest rates fell in the credit markets. Yields on long-term
Treasury bonds dropped to the 8.02 percent-8.06 percent range.
   Gainers among the blue chips included American Telephone &amp;
Telegraph, up ] at 35}; Philip Morris, up 1\ at 141}; General
Electric, up 1 at 53[, and International Business Machines, up { at
112[.
   Honeywell jumped 5[ to 78\ on takeover speculation fueled by a
Business Week column in the issue that reached readers today.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
1.32 to 181.14. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up 1.69 at 362.80.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 78.19 million shares at noontime,
up from 67.46 million at the same point Thursday.
</TEXT>
