<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-89 1255EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-UniversalFoods     07-07 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Universal Foods,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>High Voltage Raises Offer for Universal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   High Voltage Engineering Corp., which has been
pursuing Milwaukee-based Universal Foods Corp. since last year,
announced today it was willing to raise its offer to $42 a share.
   Laurence Levy, chairman of High Voltage, based in Burlington,
Mass., said his company delivered a letter to Universal's board of
directors, offering to buy the company in a negotiated transaction.
   ``We are attempting to negotiate with them because we think that
is a better route,'' said Evan Zeppos, a spokesman for High Voltage
in Milwaukee.
   High Voltage currently has a $38 per share cash tender offer for
Universal, but only about 30 percent of the stockholders have
tendered their shares, according to a statement last week from
Universal.
   ``We remain committed to the acquisition of Universal,'' the
letter from High Voltage said. ``We would like to meet with you at
your earliest convenience to complete the negotiation of the merger
agreement.''
   A Universal spokeswoman said the company had no immediate
response to the offer.
   High Voltage began its quest for Universal last December with an
offer of $30.50 per share. The proposal, however, has been rejected
by Universal's board of directors.
   High Voltage challenged an anti-takeover law in Wisconsin that
essentially blocks bidders from making direct contact with
shareholders unless the company's management approves.
   The law was upheld this year by the 7th Circuit U.S. Court of
Appeals in Chicago, although the decision stated: ``Wisconsin's law
may well be folly; we are confident that it is constitutional.''
   In its letter to Universal, High Voltage said, ``the court noted
that bidders could seek to require that directors fulfill their
fiduciary obligations as they relate to the (anti-takeover)
statute.''
   ``I think they will find this offer very generous and it will
force them to take a look at it,'' Zeppos said.
   Investment analysts said $42 per share, which would amount to
about $640 million, would be a strong offer, but they said the
outcome was hard to predict.
   ``I would hope the Universal Foods board would now initiate some
sort of discussions,'' said Richard Elam, a food industry analyst
with Blunt Ellis &amp; Loewi Inc. in Chicago.
   Clinton Mayer, an analyst with Bear, Stearns &amp; Co. in New York,
said he did not foresee any quick resolution.
   He noted that the smaller, individual stockholders have been more
reluctant to part with their shares than the larger, institutional
investors.
   ``The stock seems to be held by conservative investors who don't
seem concerned with short-term prices,'' Mayer said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
