<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-89 1536EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-BritishStocks 1stLd-Writethru f0036 07-07 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-British Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0036,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares Rise As Outlook Turns Optimistic</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with later activity, closing index;
No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices rose sharply Friday on the London
Stock Exchange, boosted by evidence of a slowing U.S. economy as
well as a stronger British pound.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index ended 27.9
points, or 1.29 percent, higher at 2,189.1, its best level of the
day.
   For the week, the key index gained 38.1 points, or 1.8 percent.
   The narrower Financial Times 30-share index was up 20.3 points at
1,815.0. The Financial Times 500 closed 13.87 points higher at
1,246.12.
   Volume was heavy as 774.8 million shares changed hands, up
sharply from 563.5 million on Thursday. However, more than a third
of Friday's volume resulted from aggressive buying of shares in
Gateway Corp. PLC by Newgateway PLC, which is bidding 2.2 billion
pounds for the food retailer.
   Share prices rose at the start of trading, helped by the activity
in Gateway shares and by speculation that other companies in the
food sector also could be targeted for takeover.
   Analysts said the advance was extended after the release of U.S.
employment data for June, which showed growth slowing more than had
been expected. Countering this, however, was an upward revision in
May's pace of job growth.
   ``There was conflicting evidence in today's (employment) figures.
But overall it's pointing to the economy slowing down,'' said one
London dealer. Wall Street also rose briskly after a hesitant
opening, further underpinning the London market's performance, he
said.
   The dollar ended lower against the pound following the U.S.
employment report, giving the British currency a chance to extend
its recent gains. That eased market concerns about the outlook for
British interest rates, analysts said.
   The pound was quoted late in the day at $1.6245, up from $1.6220
late Thursday in London.
</TEXT>
