<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-89 1621EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Princeton-Newport 1stLd-Writethru f0167 07-07 0637</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Princeton-Newport, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0167,0656</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Rests Case in Racketeering Trial; Plays `Sleaze' Tapes</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 3rd graf from end to CORRECT spelling of Rabinowitz; picks
up penultimate graf pvs bg'ng, The case ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government rested its case Friday in the
first securities racketeering trial after playing a tape of a former
Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. trader telling a Princeton-Newport
Partners LP executive after an alleged illegal deal: ``Welcome to
the world of being a sleaze.''
   Also, defense lawyers declined Friday to cross-examine Drexel
Chief Executive Frederick H. Joseph for fear of introducing into
evidence potentially damaging information about Drexel's $650
million plea deal with the government.
   The ``sleaze'' tape was one of 14 conversations played by federal
prosecutors at the closely watched Wall Street fraud trial of five
partners in Princeton-Newport, a defunct brokerage, and ex-Drexel
trader Bruce Lee Newberg.
   The tape involves charges that Newberg told Princeton-Newport to
sell blocks of stock in C.O.M.B. Co. to try to drive its share price
below $16 in 1985 before a $25 million Drexel bond offering to the
Minneapolis-based merchandiser.
   ``I want you to, you know, get rid of it,'' Newberg told
Princeton-Newport partner Charles M. Zarzecki on April 11, 1985. ``I
want you to get it down to at least 15} at least, and hopefully
lower.''
   Zarzecki later that day told Newberg he sold 40,000 shares of the
stock through another party in an attempt to drive the price down.
   Newberg: ``Agreed, uh, that was good. ... You're a sleaze bag.''
   Zarzecki: ``You taught me man. ... Hey, listen turkey.''
   Newberg: ``Welcome to the world of being a sleaze.''
   After playing the tape to the jury of nine women and three men,
prosecutors rested their case.
   Zarzecki's lawyer, Paul Grand, told U.S. District Judge Robert L.
Carter that certain charges against his client should be dismissed
because C.O.M.B.'s stock never fell below $16.
   Grand said disclosure of the transaction was unnecessary because
the stock was traded in the over-the-counter market, which is
governed by different rules than major exchanges.
   Other defense lawyers asked Carter to throw out a bevy of mail
fraud, wire fraud and racketeering charges. The judge did not
immediately rule on the requests, but indicated he was uncertain
about some of the government's charges.
   The C.O.M.B. deal also played a major role in defense lawyers'
decision not to cross-examine Joseph, who took the stand Thursday
for the first time in a Wall Street corruption case.
   Under questioning from Assistant U.S. Attorney Mark Hansen,
Joseph described Drexel compliance systems and practices for
underwriting securities such as convertible bonds, the kind used in
the C.O.M.B. transaction.
   Defense lawyers said Friday that cross-examining Joseph in an
attempt to show that the C.O.M.B. transactions were harmless could
have opened the door for the government to introduce Drexel's $650
settlement of securities law charges reached last December.
   The government is barred from introducing the Drexel deal as
evidence because it is unrelated. Defense lawyers did not want to
risk mentioning the deal because for fear it would have prejudiced
the jury against Princeton-Newport.
   One of six felony counts to which Drexel has agreed to plead
guilty involved the C.O.M.B. transaction.
   In addition to Newberg and Zarzecki, on trial are
Princeton-Newport partners James Sutton Regan, Jack Z. Rabinowitz
and Paul A. Berkman, and the firm's controller, Steven B. Smotrich.
   The case overlaps the government's 98-count fraud and
racketeering indictment of former Drexel financier Michael Milken.
Much of the same evidence is expected to be introduced at Milken's
trial, scheduled to begin in March 1990.
   Princeton-Newport, a small securities firm with offices in
Princeton, N.J., and Newport Beach, Calif., went out of business
after the indictment was brought last August. Neither
Princeton-Newport nor Drexel is charged in the case.
</TEXT>
