<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close, 1st Ld-Writethru,0287</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Retreat Amid Better Rain Prospects</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lede to CORRECT rain forecast to late next week sted early
next week; Picks up 2nd graf pvs bg'ng, Prices had ...; SUBS last graf
to DELETE extra numeral from wheat price, making it $4.04{; no pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed mostly
lower Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade, reflecting an increased
likelihood of rain in the Midwest this weekend and late next week.
   Prices had opened higher on forecasts Thursday for mostly hot and
dry weather in the Corn Belt through next week. But attitudes
changed after some private meteorologists reported a weakening of
the high-pressure ``ridge'' that has prevented showers and cool
temperatures from reaching the Midwest this week.
   ``I think people came in this morning feeling comfortable about
buying the market and expecting higher prices next week, but when
the weathermen started adding precipitation, they all lost their
courage,'' said Steve Freed, a grain-market analyst in Chicago with
Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   Weather concerns continue to dominate the grain and soybean
markets, as is the rule for the growing season.
   ``This is a very nervous market,'' said Dale Gustafson, an
analyst with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in Chicago.
   At the close of trading, wheat was { cent to 4{ cents lower with
the contract for delivery in July at $4.04{ a bushel; corn was 2
cents to 5\ cents lower with July at $2.72} a bushel; oats were 1}
cents to 4 cents lower with July at $1.57} a bushel; soybeans were
15 cents lower to 2 cents higher with July at $7.67 a bushel.
</TEXT>
