<FIRST>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   07-07 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0495</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Visions of renewed declines in interest rates
provided the inspiration for a broad advance in the stock market
Friday.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials climbed 25.42 points to
2,487.86, stretching its advance for a holiday-shortened week of
four consecutive gains to 47.80 points.
   Issues rising in price outnumbered losers by more than 2 to 1 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
1,064 up, 472 down and 458 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 166.43 million
shares, up from 140.45 million in the previous session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in those
stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter market,
totaled 195.24 million shares.
   The market opened on a hesitant note, but then picked up steam at
midsession as traders concluded that the Labor Department's
employment report for June had apparently encouraged the Federal
Reserve to relax its credit policy.
   The report showed an increase of 180,000 in nonfarm payroll
employment, below most advance estimates.
   The figures for May were revised to show a gain of 207,000, more
than double the 101,000 originally reported a month ago. Still,
brokers said, Wall Streeters came increasingly to believe that the
Fed interpreted the data as reason enough to ease up on its credit
restraints.
   Interest rates fell in the credit markets. Prices of long-term
Treasury bonds rose more than $5 for each $1,000 in face value,
reducing their yields to the 8.03 percent-8.06 percent range.
   That helped fuel speculation that major banks might soon announce
new reductions in their prime lending rates.
   Gainers among the blue chips included American Telephone &amp;
Telegraph, up { at 35~; Coca-Cola, up 1{ at 58]; Philip Morris, up |
at 141[; General Electric, up 1 at 53|, and International Business
Machines, up { at 112[.
   An exception was General Motors, down } at 40[ on word of new
cutbacks in the company's production plans for the third quarter.
   Honeywell climbed 4| to 77} on takeover speculation fueled by a
column in Business Week magazine.
   UAL, also buffeted by continuing takeover rumors, jumped 13{ to
166. Among other leading airline issues, Delta Air Lines gained 1~
to 72 and AMR was up \ at 64\.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market increased $30.43 billion, or 0.96
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks gained
1.74 to 181.56.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index rose 3.68 to 370.87, and S&amp;P's
500-stock composite index was up 3.36 at 324.91.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market added
2.85 to 442.42. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index closed at 363.75, up 2.64.
</TEXT>
