<TEXT>
   Here are weekly price trends for selected commodities:
   Grain and soybean futures rose on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Wheat for delivery in July settled Friday at $4.04} a bushel
compared with $3.97\ a week earlier; July corn rose to $2.74 a
bushel from $2.66}; July oats climbed to $1.57} a bushel from
$1.49{; July soybeans rallied to $7.66{ a bushel from $7.35.
   Livestock and meat futures declined on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange.
   August live cattle dropped to 69.75 cents a pound from 70.15
cents; August feeder cattle slipped to 80.82 cents a pound from
80.87 cents; July hogs fell to 47.15 cents a pound from 48.67 cents;
July frozen pork bellies plunged to 30.85 cents a pound from 35.85
cents.
   Gold and silver futures rose on New York's Commodity Exchange.
   August gold settled at $385.70 a troy ounce, up from $377.30 a
week earlier; July silver rose to $5.209 a troy ounce from $5.155.
   Crude oil futures advanced for the fourth straight week but
refined product prices fell on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil for August delivery rose to
$20.75 a barrel from $20.27; August heating oil slipped to 49.77
cents a gallon from 49.89 cents; August unleaded gasoline dipped to
56.59 cents a gallon from 57.77 cents.
