<FIRST>u f AM-BladeBattle     07-07 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Blade Battle,0267</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wilkinson Sword Barred From Showing Ultra Glide Ads</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge Friday temporarily barred
Wilkinson Sword Inc. from airing television commercials for its new
Ultra Glide razor.
   The preliminary injunction was sought by the Gillette Co., which
sued Wilkinson for false advertising in May.
   U.S. District Judge Kimba Wood in Manhattan said Gillette was
``likely to succeed on the merits'' of its allegations that the
commercials misled the public by implying Ultra Glide's shavers were
six times smoother than Gillette's product, Atra Plus.
   In the ads, Atlanta-based Wilkinson says Ultra Glide's special
lubricating strip provided a smoother shave than a similar strip on
Atra Plus.
   Wood's ruling reversed a written opinion she made Thursday
rejecting Gillette's request for the preliminary injunction that
would bar Wilkinson from showing the television commercials.
   She said she reconsidered after reviewing a market study that
found no substantial differences in the smoothness of the two
shaving systems.
   A Wilkinson attorney, Steven E. Levitsky, asked for a stay of the
order because he said its effect would be ``devastating'' to the
company. The commercials are the only television advertising
Wilkinson is currently showing, he said.
   Wilkinson is a small player in the $750 million wet-shave razor
market with about a 4 percent share, compared with more than 60
percent for Gillette.
   Wood declined to stop the injunction, which will be in effect
until the case is resolved. A trial date could be set for later this
summer.
   Boston-based Gillette is seeking undetermined monetary damages.
</TEXT>
