<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold 1stLd-Writethru   07-07 0648</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold, 1st Ld - Writethru,0662</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls Amid Fears of Interest Rate Cuts</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf pvs, Rumors circulated... to CORRECT to ``reduce''
sted ``boost.''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar finished lower against all major
currencies except the Japanese yen Friday after a steady selloff
sparked by fears that interest rates would decline.
   Gold prices also lost ground. On the New York Commodity Exchange,
gold bullion for current delivery slipped to $383.60 a troy ounce
from $386.40 on Thursday. Republic National Bank of New York quoted
a late bid for gold of $382.00 an ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, down from
Thursday's late bid of $384.25.
   Domestic currency trading began with a jolt as the Labor
Department issued a report showing the nation's unemployment rate
climbed 0.1 percent to 5.3 percent last month.
   Traders initially were confused by the specifics of the report,
which showed lower-than-expected non-farm payroll growth coupled
with a sharply higher revision for May.Non-farm businesses added
just 180,000 jobs last month, but May's payroll expansion was
revised upward to 207,000 jobs.
   ``The first reaction was the dollar went up,'' said Kevin Lawrie,
vice president and manager at Bank of Boston's New York office.
   ``But that only lasted five minutes before the dollar came
barreling off,'' he said. The report ultimately depressed the dollar
by serving as yet another example of the economy's slowdown.
   Traders said the dollar remained under pressure from the
fundamental threat it has faced throughout the week: the prospect of
lower interest rates. Dollar-denominated securities like bonds are
more expensive when interest rates edge lower, which depresses the
need for dollars to purchase them.
   Rumors circulated through the market that the Federal Reserve may
be preparing to reduce its discount rate before the weekend.
   ``We got a lot of (dollar) selling this afternoon,'' said Stephen
Flanagan, a vice president at Manufacturers Hanover Trust Co.
   Flanagan did not attribute the selloff solely to the unemployment
report, however. He stressed instead that the report ``set the stage
for upcoming statistics due out next week'' by suggesting that
further weakness in the economy is likely.
   The government is scheduled to report on industrial production,
factory use and retail sales next week. Each bearish report gives
the Federal Reserve a greater incentive to trim interest rates.
   Earlier in Tokyo, the dollar closed at 139.65 Japanese yen, up
from 138.90 yen. Later in London, the dollar inched up to 139.75
yen. In New York the dollar rose to finish at 139.20 yen, up from
138.88 yen late Thursday.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.6245 late Friday, more
expensive for buyers than late Thursday's $1.6220. In New York it
cost $1.6313 to buy one pound, more expensive than $1.6265 late
Thursday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Thursday,
included: 1.8705 West German marks, down from 1.8850; 1.6095 Swiss
francs, down from 1.6175; 6.3505 French francs, down from 6.3935;
1,355.00 Italian lire, down from 1,365.50, and 1.1908 Canadian
dollars, down from 1.1917.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday,
included: 1.8840 West German marks, down from 1.8885; 1.6200 Swiss
francs, down from 1.6210; 6.3915 French francs, down from 6.4070;
2.1272 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1310; 1,368.00 Italian lire, down
from 1,370.50, and 1.1907 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1919.
   Traders noted that European currency markets appeared to shut
down earlier than usual.
   Gold closed in London at a bid of $385.25 a troy ounce, down from
$386.25 on Thursday, in light trading. The late bid price in Zurich,
Switzerland, was $384.60, down from $385.00. Earlier in Hong Kong,
gold closed at $383.75 bid, down from $384.45.
   Silver prices were mixed. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for
current delivery fell to $5.209 a troy ounce from $5.377 on
Thursday. Earlier in London, silver traded at a late bid price of
$5.37 a troy ounce, up from $5.36.
</TEXT>
