<FIRST>u f AM-Bonds     07-07 0687</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bonds,0716</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bond Prices Climb</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond prices climbed Friday, pushed up by June
employment data that provided more evidence of a slowing economy.
   The Treasury's closely watched 30-year bond rose about 21-32
point, or $6.50 for every $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which
moves in the opposite direction from price, declined to 8.03 from
8.09 percent late Thursday.
   The Labor Department reported that the nation's unemployment rate
edged up to 5.3 percent in June from 5.2 percent in May as
businesses created a modest 180,000 new jobs. There were signs in
the report that economic growth is cooling and an indication as well
of an easing of the wage inflation that has troubled some analysts.
   Nancy Vanden Houten, money-market economist for Merrill Lynch
Capital Markets in New York, said the increases in non-farm payroll
and hourly earnings were below market expectations.
   ``The consensus was about 225,000 and there was only a one-cent
increase in hourly earnings,'' she said. ``The market for a long
time has been focusing on signs of inflation. That definitely was
positive news in terms of inflation.''
   Average hourly earnings of production and supervisory workers
were essentially unchanged, after rising an average 0.3 percent in
the first five months of the year, the government said.
   The report was one of many in recent weeks that suggested the
economy is easing off its brisk pace of the last several years and
underscored a widely-held belief that the Federal Reserve might now
allow short-term interest rates to decline.
   Jay Goldinger, a principal at the investment firm Capital Insight
in Beverly Hills, Calif., said despite the gains market activity was
volatile in thin dealings as traders anticipated the Fed's next move.
   ``Some investors didn't know what to do with the (employment)
numbers,'' Goldinger said. ``The market was confused over whether
the Fed would ease. That caused the bond market to be more volatile
than usual.''
   The Fed has kept a tight grip on credit by encouraging higher
interest rates in recent months in hopes of curbing growth and
taming inflation. Inflation erodes the value of fixed-income
securities such as bonds and notes. Higher interest rates also
depress bond prices.
   Market observers noted on Thursday that the Fed had eased policy
as indicated by a declining federal funds rate and the fact that the
central bank had not drained reserves from the banking system.
   In the secondary market for Treasury securities, prices of
short-term government issues rose between 3-16 point and 7-32 point,
intermediate maturities gained between 7-32 point and \ point and
20-year issues advanced between 11-32 point and 19-32 point,
according to Telerate Inc., a financial information service.
   The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the
price of a bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Shearson Lehman Hutton Daily Treasury Bond Index, which
measures price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with
maturities of a year or longer, rose 3.31 to 1,190.16.
   In corporate trading, industrials rose. Moody's Investment Grade
Corporate Bond Index, which measures total return on a portfolio of
80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years or longer, gained
0.97 to 328.76.
   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively
traded municipal bonds closed at 94 11-16, up 3-16 from Thursday.
The average yield to maturity slipped to 7.19 percent from 7.20
percent late Thursday.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills fell to 7.96 percent as the
discount dropped 8 points to 7.71 percent. Yields on six-month bills
declined to 7.86 percent as the discount tumbled 7 basis points to
7.47 percent. Yields on 1-year bills fell to 7.86 percent as the
discount slid 8 basis basis points to 7.33 percent.
   A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield
is the annualized return on an investment in a Treasury bill. The
discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face
value, which is paid at maturity.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, was quoted late in the day at 8~ percent, down from 9 5-16
percent late Thursday.
</TEXT>
