<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     07-07 0228</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Rise While Gasoline Prices Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices for crude oil and gasoline rose while
heating oil declined Friday as a skittish energy futures market
continued to respond to reports of labor strife in Europe.
   The August contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude, rose 45 cents to close at $20.75 a barrel on
the New York Mercantile Exchange after falling 46 cents on Thursday.
   Wholesale unleaded gasoline for August delivery picked up 0.32
cent to settle at 56.59 cents a gallon after falling 1.15 cents
Thursday.
   And the August contract for home heating oil fell 0.12 cent to
close at 49.77 cents a gallon after slipping 1.17 cents in
Thursday's session.
   Andrew Lebow, an analyst with E.D.&amp;F. Man International Futures
Inc., said the market seemed to be gyrating within a broad trading
range amid light volume.
   News that British dockworkers were calling a strike for Monday
set off fears in the market that oil exports from the North Sea
might be curtailed, Lebow said.
   Energy futures prices have bounced up and down this week in
response to other labor problems affecting North Sea oil operations,
but Lebow said it was unlikely the dockworkers' action could have a
major impact on exports.
   ``I think the market is at this point confused about its
direction,'' Lebow said.
</TEXT>
