<FIRST>u f AM-Dunkin'Donuts-Canadians     07-07 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dunkin' Donuts-Canadians,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>Partnership Says it Has Arranged Financing for Dunkin' Donuts Bid</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: All dollars are US.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Canadian partnership making a hostile bid for
control of U.S.-based Dunkin' Donuts Inc. said Friday it has
arranged $275 million in financing to back its offer to shareholders.
   Cara Operations Ltd. and The Kingsbridge Capital Group said the
financing, in addition to the equity each of them is putting up,
will be enough to fund its cash bid of $43 for each outstanding
Dunkin' Donuts share.
   The offer is worth $305.3 million.
   This latest bid for Dunkin' Donuts, which has 1,700 doughnut
franchises in the United States, was made June 15 and rejected last
week by the company's board. An earlier friendly bid in May was also
turned down.
   The partnership, under the name DD Acquisition Corp., has said
the offer is conditional on acquiring 50.1 per cent of the
outstanding 7.1 million common shares of Dunkin' Donuts. The offer
expires July 13.
   Financing was arranged through Toronto-based Trilon Financial
Corp. and its merchant bank affiliate, Great Lakes Group. Inc., the
partners said in a statement on Friday.
   Cara is a Canadian food-service company that owns chains of
fast-food and family restaurants, such as Swiss Chalet and Harvey's.
Kingsbridge is a Canadian-based merchant bank that already owns
about 12 per cent of Dunkin' Donuts shares.
   Dunkin' Donuts is based in Randolph, Mass.
</TEXT>
