<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-89 1937EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Time     07-07 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Time,0467</SECOND>
<HEAD>Forty Banks Agree to Financing for Warner Bid, Time Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Time Inc. said Friday it had received financing
commitments from 40 banks for its $14 billion tender offer for
Warner Communications Inc.
   Time, which is pursuing a merger with Warner and trying to fend
off an unwanted $12.2 billion bid from Paramount Communications
Inc., said the banks offered to provide a total of $27.5 billion in
financing. The media giant has said it needs $8.35 billion to
complete the cash portion of its offer for Warner.
   Time is offering $70 a share in cash for half of Warner's 200
million outstanding shares, and will exchange cash and securities
worth $70 a share for the remaining 100 million shares.
   The announcement came as lawyers prepared for a hearing in
Delaware Chancery Court on Tuesday that could determine the outcome
of the three-way struggle for Time.
   Chancery Court Judge William Allen will hear arguments on
Paramount's contention that Time, in agreeing to a friendly
stock-swap merger with Warner earlier this year, put itself up for
sale and therefore must seriously consider the $200 a share
Paramount offer.
   The Time board rejected the Paramount offer as financially
inadequate and too dependent on conditions to be viable.
   Time stock fell $4.12{ a share to $151.50 in New York Stock
Exchange composite trading Friday. Peter Appert, an analyst with
C.J. Lawrence, Morgan Grenfell Inc., said traders were growing
increasingly nervous about Paramount's chances of success as
Tuesday's hearing drew closer.
   Time stock has traded as high has $182.75 in the month since
Paramount announced its offer, but has fallen back as some
investors, fearing the hostile bid will fail, have taken profits.
   Warner stock was unchanged Friday, closing at $61.75 a share,
while Paramount stock slipped 87{ cents to $57 a share.
   Time said it had designated Bankers Trust Co., Manufacturers
Hanover Trust Co., Bank of Boston, Bank of New York Co., Chemical
Banking Corp. and Morgan Guaranty Trust Co. as co-agents to
coordinate the financing for the Warner bid.
   Other banks agreeing to provide financing include Bank of
America, Chase Manhattan Bank, First National Bank of Chicago,
Mellon Bank, Wells Fargo Bank as well as foreign institutions
including Mitsubishi Bank Ltd., Bank of Tokyo Ltd., Sanwa Bank Ltd.,
Swiss Bank Corp. and Barclays Bank PLC.
   Last week, Paramount announced it had lined up seven banks to
serve as co-agents for its offer for Time. Paramount said each of
the banks would contribute $1 billion, or a total of $7 billion,
toward the $15.6 billion estimated financing costs for the bid,
although Paramount did not yet have commitments for the rest of the
money.
</TEXT>
