<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-89 2241EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-727Cracks     07-07 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-727 Cracks,0461</SECOND>
<HEAD>FAA Considering More Inspections of Older 727s</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Aviation Administration may order
inspections of more older Boeing 727 jetliners as a precaution after
cracks were found in the fuselages of three 727s flown by United
Airlines, an FAA spokesman said Friday.
   Spokesman David Duff said FAA officials were considering
requiring inspections on approximately 400 of the three-engine jets
built by The Boeing Co. in the late 1960s. No cracks have been
reported among those jets, and any inspection would be ``purely a
precautionary and prudent measure by the FAA,'' Duff said.
   If not corrected, the FAA said, the cracks could lead to sudden
decompression of the aircraft cabin.
   The FAA ordered inspections and any necessary repairs of the 47
oldest 727s after United found a 20-inch crack in a 25-year-old jet
during a June 26 maintenance check. United spokesman Rob Doughty
said tiny cracks were found on the two other 727s after the FAA
issued its airworthiness directive June 30.
   All three planes have been repaired, Doughty said. United has 16
jets that required inspection, and the checks were being completed
Friday night, he said.
   Boeing said 41 of the 47 planes are still in service. Among other
carriers flying them are Continental Airlines, with two planes, TWA,
with three, American Airlines, with seven, and Trump Shuttle, with
one. Spokesmen for those companies said most of the planes had been
inspected, with no cracks found.
   The FAA deadline for completing the inspections is July 15. Duff
said he had not received an official report of how many planes had
been checked.
   The 20-inch crack was in the same general area as the break in an
Aloha Airlines 737 that lost part of its top over Hawaii last year,
but Boeing and the FAA said the cracking appeared to be entirely
different.
   ``This is the first time a report of cracking has been made in
this area,'' Duff said, adding that the cracking was not typical of
the type often found in older aircraft.
   Duff said Thursday FAA officials suspect ``hoop tension''
fatigue, caused by outward forces in pressurized flight against the
different thicknesses of aircraft skin where skin sections overlap.
   The cracked segment was brought earlier this week to Boeing
laboratories in Seattle where engineers are trying to find out why
it occurred. Boeing Commercial Airplanes spokesman Jack Gamble said
Friday it probably would take about a week for the analysis to be
completed.
   The three-engine 727, built from 1962 to 1984, was the
best-selling commercial jet before being surpassed by the Boeing
737. Boeing said 1,765 of the 727s are still in service.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
