<FIRST>r f BC-BusinessHighlights     07-07 0876</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Business Highlights,0913</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's unemployment rate climbed 0.1
percentage point to 5.3 percent in June as continued declines in
manufacturing and construction slowed overall job growth, the
government said.
   Analysts were split on whether the jobless data provided Friday
by the Labor Department suggested a recession was nearing, but they
were unanimous in saying there was nothing in the report to change
the Federal Reserve's apparent decision to ease monetary policy.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Reserve, faced with further signs
of a weakening economy, launched a second round of credit easing
this past week even before the end of a crucial midyear review of
monetary policy, private economists said.
   The analysts predicted Friday that the move would send a variety
of consumer and business interest rates lower, with one saying that
a cut in commercial banks' prime lending rate could come as early as
Monday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans took out $3.6 billion more in
consumer debt than they retired in May as the pace of borrowing
turned upward again, the government reported.
   The Federal Reserve Board said Friday that consumer credit in May
rose at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 6.2 percent, up from
the 4.3 percent pace of April.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Time Inc. said it had received financing
commitments from 40 banks for its $14 billion tender offer for
Warner Communications Inc.
   Time, which is pursuing a merger with Warner and trying to fend
off an unwanted $12.2 billion bid from Paramount Communications
Inc., said Friday the banks offered to provide a total of $27.5
billion in financing. The media giant has said it needs $8.35
billion to complete the cash portion of its offer for Warner.
   The announcement came as lawyers prepared for a hearing in
Delaware Chancery Court on Tuesday that could determine the outcome
of the three-way struggle for Time.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government rested its case in the first
securities racketeering trial after playing a tape of a former
Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. trader telling a Princeton-Newport
Partners LP executive after an alleged illegal deal: ``Welcome to
the world of being a sleaze.''
   Also, defense lawyers declined Friday to cross-examine Drexel
Chief Executive Frederick H. Joseph for fear of introducing into
evidence potentially damaging information about Drexel's $650
million plea deal with the government.
   The ``sleaze'' tape was one of 14 conversations played by federal
prosecutors at the closely watched Wall Street fraud trial of five
partners in Princeton-Newport, a defunct brokerage, and ex-Drexel
trader Bruce Lee Newberg.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government announced a stricter policy to
deal with threats against aviation, including a system that requires
airlines to take countermeasures and imposes fines for disclosing
security alerts.
   A Federal Aviation Administration order, which will go into
effect Monday, replaces the current system of issuing security
bulletins, criticized after the bombing of a Pan Am flight over
Scotland last December that killed 270 people.
   Under the new order disclosed Friday, individuals or airlines
that disclose information from government security alerts without
FAA authorization will be fined _ up to $1,000 for individuals and
$10,000 for airlines.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of AT&amp;T's two unions have
overwhelmingly ratified new 3-year contracts providing them with the
company's first profit-sharing plan for union workers and a package
of family-related benefits, the unions said.
   The Communications Workers of America and the International
Brotherhood of Electrical Workers did not provide a breakdown of the
secret-ballot ratification vote but said Friday it was approved by
``huge margins'' in every bargaining unit nationwide.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Food and Drug Administration said it is
banning sales of non-prescription antibaldness creams and
aphrodisiac products because none has been shown to work.
   Over-the-counter hair-growth products _ usually sold by mail or
through barbers or beauticians _ have dwindled in number since the
FDA indicated in 1985 that it would ban the products.
   But the FDA said Friday these products ``have continued to be an
area of considerable fraud. The ban of all such products will
provide a greater and more uniform protection to the public.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Labor Department proposed nearly $2 million
in fines against a Ford Motor Co. subsidiary it said had repeatedly
violated an agreement reached with the automaker two years ago by
failing to adequately report injuries and illnesses.
   The subsidiary, Ford Electronics and Refrigeration Corp. of
Lansdale, Pa., was given 15 working days to contest the fine
proposed by the Occupational Safety and Health Administration, the
government said Friday.
   Ford officials did not immediately return telephone calls seeking
comment.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market advanced broadly Friday, as the Dow Jones
average of 30 industrials climbed 25.42 points to 2,487.86,
stretching its advance for a holiday-shortened week of four
consecutive gains to 47.80 points.
   Bond prices climbed on more evidence the economy is slowing.
   The dollar finished lower against all major currencies except the
Japanese yen after a steady selloff sparked by speculation that
interest rates would decline.
   Silver futures prices fell sharply; gold futures settled lower;
copper futures made strong gains; coffee futures sank; oil futures
rose; grains and soybeans were lower; and livestock and meat mostly
fell.
</TEXT>
