<FIRST>r f AM-China-SwineSemen     07-07 0161</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Swine Semen,0167</SECOND>
<HEAD>Swine Semen Regulations Announced</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New regulations for importing swine semen from
China were announced Friday, but Agriculture Department officials
say it is unlikely that shipments will be allowed until U.S.-China
relations improve.
   The rules, proposed in March, went into effect Wednesday, said
James W. Glosser, administrator of the department's Animal and Plant
Health Inspection Service.
   But spokesman Wayne Baggett said the actual shipment of semen
``is very unlikely because of the political situation.''
   U.S. officials have criticized China for its recent crackdown on
pro-democracy demonstrators.
   China, the world's largest swine producer, may have valuable
breeding stock that could be used by U.S. producers. The semen
program, designed with that in mind, includes rules to guard against
the introduction of certain diseases.
   For example, donor boars must originate in areas of China
certified as free of hog cholera, rinderpest, foot-and-mouth
disease, brucellosis, tuberculosis and other afflictions. The semen
samples also must be tested for disease.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
